<1ST_LINE>r a PM-APMEConvention     10-18 0647</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-APME Convention,0665</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>APME President Urges Editors: Fight Campaign Attempts To Manage
News</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Newspapers must fight attempts by presidential
campaigns to orchestrate the news in hopes of getting good
television coverage, says the president of the Associated Press
Managing Editors association.
   ``The most important journalism in this campaign is being
delivered by the reporters who are going in after the candidates
have been there and are talking to voters about impressions of the
candidates and about the real problems of their regions,'' Robert
H. Giles, vice president and executive editor of The Detroit News,
told the APME on Tuesday, the first day of its annual convention.
   He told the newspaper editors: `My premise is that newspaper
editors are allowing television news directors and the campaign
strategists for George Bush and Michael Dukakis to influence their
Page 1 agendas.''
   ``As a result,'' he added, ``we are the targets of criticism
about biased or frivolous coverage that is more appropriately the
fault of television.''
   Giles suggested newspapers rely on wire services for much of the
day-to-day campaign coverage, and concentrate on providing readers
with ``issues stories.''
   On the wide perception that the current campaign has been
especially negative, Walter R. Mears, AP vice president and
executive editor, said contests in the 1960s, such as the
Goldwater-Johnson race in 1964, were no less strident or less
shaped by image-makers.
   ``We, meaning the people who report the campaign, have been
telling the voters this is a campaign of sound bites, crafted by
handlers and interpreted by spin-control specialists,'' he said.
``Those buzzwords make it sound as though these were all 1988
creations. I don't think there's anything unique about it.''
   More than 600 editors from around the country are attending the
week-long annual convention. The AP, the largest newsgathering
organization in the world, serves 1,467 daily newspapers.
   In his address to the editors, AP President and General Manager
Louis D. Boccardi said the wire service is in the midst of its most
extensive modernization in its photography, financial and technical
delivery services.
   ``As our periodic announcements may have suggested to you, we
are in the midst of the most thorough and concentrated rebuilding
and modernizing of AP services that has been attempted in modern
times,'' Boccardi said.
   Editors also heard presentations from AP editors on developments
in news and photography distribution, and discussions of changes in
the Soviet Union and its press.
   Stanislav Menshikov, a Soviet economist who collaborated with
Harvard economist John Kenneth Galbraith on a book about the United
States and the Soviet Union, told the editors that economic change
is meeting some resistance from the Soviet bureaucracy.
   ``They still control most of the economy and make economic
change a fiction and not a fact,'' Menshikov said.
   Galbraith said U.S. fears of communism and Soviet fears of
capitalism have abated in recent years. ``We live in a time when
both of those fears have evaporated, except on the paranoiac
right,'' he said.
   At a session on the Soviet press, Alexander Shalnev, New York
correspondent for Izvestia, said Soviet newspapers reacted to
greater press freedom with more negative stories about their
country and more positive ones on America.
   He cited an ``upsurge in the inclination to write as many
negative things as we could find out'' and said the boundaries on
what is acceptable still are being defined.
   At a panel discussion on New England, David Nyhan, political
columnist for The Boston Globe, advised the visiting editors to
``watch where you walk and how you drive.''
   ``Driving is the most dangerous thing you can do in
Massachusetts, even more than taking advice from Harvard,'' he said.
   Judson Hale, editor of Yankee magazine, said New England's
greatest export is its conscience. ``The New England conscience
never kept anyone from doing anything, but it does keep you from
enjoying it,'' he said.
</TEXT>
