<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ContinentalCracks     10-18 0604</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Continental Cracks,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Routine Painting Leads to Discovery of Airline Cracks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A routine repainting job led to the discovery
of a foot-long crack in an aging Continental Airlines Boeing 737,
five months after the government had ordered special inspections to
look for such flaws.
   A spokesman for Continental confirmed that the large crack as
well as 29 smaller ones were discovered near a window of the
first-class section after paint was stripped from the plane in
preparation for repainting Oct. 5.
   The cracks stretched about 30 inches along a joint where
sections of metal skin overlap, according to investigators of the
National Transportation Safety Board, whose metallurgists are
examining the section.
   NTSB chairman James Kolstad called it a ``chilling discovery''
in a speech Monday to an aviation group in Montreal and said it was
``frightening'' because the cracking was found ``in the same
general area'' where an Aloha Airlines plane broke apart last April
while in flight.
   The NTSB has yet to issue a finding of the reason for the Aloha
breakup, although it has been widely speculated that corrosion and
a type of ``cold bonding'' used in older Boeing 737s played a part.
A 20-foot section of the Aloha jet tore away during flight,
sweeping a flight attendant to her death. The plane miraculously
landed safely despite the gaping hole.
   The Aloha and Continental planes both were built in 1969 using
the cold bonding method. While the Aloha plane had 89,000 takeoffs
and landings at the time of the incident, the Continental aircraft
had only 55,446 such cycles, officials said.
   The Aloha plane was No. 152 off the Boeing assembly line, while
the Continental jet was No. 17O.
   Federal Aviation Administration officials cautioned against
drawing too close a parallel between the Aloha incident and the
cracks found on the Continental jet.
   One FAA official, speaking on condition he not be further
identified, said the cracks on the Continental jet were located
lower on the aircraft, near a window, where repair work apparently
had been performed by a previous owner of the plane.
   The FAA last May issued an order that all older Boeing 737s _
those with at least 30,000 cycles _ undergo a special visual
inspection for cracking. Planes with at least 55,000 cycles had to
undergo ``eddy current'' tests using high-frequency electronic
equipment along the top of the aircraft.
   Ned Walker, a spokesman for Continental, said the aircraft in
question had been visually inspected, as required by the FAA, last
May and no cracks were found. He said the section where the
foot-long crack was discovered Oct. 5 was not subject to the more
sophisticated electronic ``eddy current'' test under the FAA
directive.
   An FAA spokesman, Bob Buckhorn, said the agency expects to issue
a new directive soon to airlines broadening the inspection
requirements, including increased use of eddy current testing. The
new rule also will require that the planes be stripped of paint
when inspected, he said.
   Walker said after the cracking was discovered Oct. 5,
Continental inspected all 42 of its older Boeing 737s within 72
hours and found no cracking problems with any of the planes.
   ``This appears to be an isolated incident,'' he said from
Continental's headquarters in Houston.
   The Boeing 737 is widely used for short-haul flights. According
to the Boeing Co., 212 older Boeing 737s operated by 19 U.S.
airlines in domestic service were subject to the special FAA
inspection requirements last May.
   A Boeing spokesman said the manufacturer was aware of the cracks
discovered by Continental, but referred all questions to the
airline.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881018-0017 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-88 0057EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FarmScene     10-18 0846</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Scene,840</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dairy Farmers To Benefit From New Government Computer System</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers soon will be getting information from
a new computer system devised by the Agriculture Department to help
them select only the best cows for their milking herds _ the cream
of the crop, so to speak.
   The genetic evaluation system, called the Animal Model, takes
into account more of a cow's relatives than does the older system,
the Modified Contemporary Comparison, which has been used since
1974, the department's Agricultural Research Service said Monday.
   Under the new system, milk production of a cow's daughters will
be considered when the mother is being evaluated. And the
evaluation of bulls, based in part on the records of the male's
offspring, also take into account the impact of the bull's mate on
those offspring.
   The new system will be used for the first time in dairy genetic
evaluations to be prepared in July 1989, the report said. The
information then will be reported to dairy farmers who can use it
to decide which cows and their calves to keep in the herd.
   ``With this information in hand, the farmer can select with more
accuracy the calves likely to be the most efficient milk
producers,'' the report said.
   The new system, a revision of the older method, was developed by
George R. Wiggans, a research geneticist at the agency's facility
in Beltsville, Md. The older method was developed by Duane Norman,
also of Beltsville.
   Agency work in genetic evaluation for many years has been an
important part of a nationwide effort to improve the U.S. dairy
herd. Milk output rose from 7,029 pounds per cow in 1960 to 13,293
pounds in 1986, the report said.
   The trend has continued, with USDA figures showing the average
milk production last year rose further to an average of 13,932
pounds.
   ``Approximately 60,000 farmers participate in the improvement
program, which involves recording milk production of each cow for
one day every month,'' the report said. ``Information on each
animal is compiled and sent to the Animal Improvement Programs
Laboratory at Beltsville, home to approximately 39 million milk
production records on 15 million cows.''
   The participating dairy farmers then receive reports on each of
their animals, the report said.
   Wiggans began working on the new system two years ago and in May
1987 transferred the programs to computers at the Cornell National
Supercomputer Facility, Ithaca, N.Y.
   The Cornell supercomputer has a very large memory, which was
necessary to handle all the additional details of the evaluations,
including all the relatives of milk cows, he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The financial worth of burley tobacco
producers is far below the national average for other farmers, but
they also have fewer debts, an Agriculture Department study says.
   The study by the department's Economic Research Service involved
273 burley tobacco farms surveyed by questionnaire in Kentucky and
Tennessee for the 1984 crop, the most recent information available.
   It said the net worth of burley tobacco producers averaged
$130,715, substantially below the $322,732 average for all U.S.
farm producers. The average farm debt for burley farms was about a
third less than the average for all U.S. farm producers.
   According to the report, which was distributed here on Monday,
the farms produced an average of 2.3 acres of burley, a cigarette
tobacco. The crop is labor intensive and required an average of 240
hours of family and hired labor per acre, or 13 hours per 100
pounds of leaf produced in 1984. An additional 11 hours of custom
labor was used on each acre.
   The 2.3 acres of burley tobacco was grown on farms averaging a
total of 122 acres of farmland.
   ``Most farms relied on non-farm sources to supplement their
income,'' the report said. ``Small tobacco farms with less than 2.1
acres of burley generally averaged equal sales from crops and
livestock. Large tobacco farms with 6 or more acres of burley
tobacco depended less on livestock sales, receiving more than 70
percent of their gross cash farm income from crop sales.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new labeling law in Portugal may restrict
that country's imports of soybean oil in favor of other kinds of
vegetable oil, according to an Agriculture Department trade report.
   The law requires that some labels for edible vegetable oil
containers indicated ``oil for dressing and frying,'' while other
labels indicate ``oil for dressing'' only, says the department's
Foreign Agricultural Service.
   Basis for the labeling is whether the vegetable oil contains 2
percent or less of linolenic acid, which would qualify as ``oil for
dressing and frying.'' If the acid content is more than that, it
would be restricted to dressings.
   Sunflowerseed oil, which is produced widely in the European
Economic Community, has the lower acid content and would qualify as
a dual-purpose oil. Portugal is a member of the EEC. However,
soybean oil, mostly from outside the EEC _ including the United
States _ has 7 percent linolenic acid and would be restricted to
dressings, the report said.
</TEXT>
