<1ST_LINE>r w PM-BurgerKingSuit     10-18 0296</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Burger King Suit,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fast-Food Company Accused Of Discriminating Against Black
Operators</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A dozen black operators of Burger King Corp.
restaurants have charged in a lawsuit that the fast-food company
gave black franchise holders uprofitable locations and reserved
more lucrative outlets for white operators.
   The discrimination and anti-trust lawsuit, filed in U.S.
District Court in Washington on Monday, charged that Burger King
also gave white operators more favorable financing terms.
   Blacks were charged as much as twice what white operators paid
to purchase or lease stores and equipment, the lawsuit said.
   Joyce Myers, a Burger King spokeswoman, said Monday, ``We can't
really respond until we have had an opportunity to see the suit and
evaluate what the allegations are.''
   The Miami-based company also was accused of discouraging black
franchise holders from expanding to other locations by thwarting
their attempts to obtain loans.
   The black operators also charged that the company did not give
them the opportunity to obtain franchises for lucrative downtown
locations, which subsequently were awarded to whites.
   Blacks who were awarded franchises in middle- and upper-income
neighborhoods were leased stores that had ``deficient equipment,
poor dining facilities, poor parking and drive-thru locations and
inferior sales potential,'' the suit said.
   The lawsuit, which seeks $500 million in punitive and
compensatory damages, also accused company officials of trying to
``harass, threaten, coerce, intimidate and otherwise malign''
franchise holders after learning of their plans to file the suit.
   The lawsuit also charged that Burger King intentionally
misrepresented the sales potential of locations sold to black
operators.
   In addition to the 12 named plaintiffs, the lawsuit was brought
on behalf of some 100 current and former black franchise holders by
the Minority Business Enterprise Legal Defense & Education Fund, a
non-profit, public-interest law firm.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
