<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Blacks-Senate     10-18 0532</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Blacks-Senate,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Black Vote Less Critical In Senate Races</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD L. VERNACI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Black voters will be having less of a decisive
impact in this year's Senate races than two years ago, even though
two candidates are black, because few of the contests are being
held in the South.
   ``There aren't as many races in which the black vote is a
powerful bloc this time,'' said Tom Mason, a spokesman for the
National Republican Senatorial Committee.
   Two years ago, Senate elections were held in seven Southern
states, four of which have blacks comprising more than 20 percent
of their voting age population. In all seven states Democrats were
elected or re-elected to the Senate.
   That arithmetic was not lost on Jesse Jackson, who tried to
wring endorsements for his presidential campaign out of Southern
senators, saying they owed their jobs to black voters.
   This year, however, there are but three Southern races for the
Senate, Florida, Mississippi and Virginia, and in just one,
Mississippi, is there a high concentration of black voters. More
than 30 percent of Mississippi's voting age population is black.
   However, in that state neither Republican Trent Lott nor
Democrat Wayne Dowdy, both of whom are congressmen running to
succeed retiring Sen. John Stennis, has tailored his campaign
messages to make a special appeal to blacks, although both
acknowledge the importance of such a large bloc of voters, their
campaign spokesmen said.
   ``Our message is very simple: We are offering opportunity,'' Tim
Carpenter, campaign manager for Lott, said in a telephone
interview. ``We want to bring more and better jobs to Mississippi.''
   ``If you look all over our advertising, it's pretty monotone,''
he said.
   Lott's strategy to win black support is direct: ``We're
asking,'' said Carpenter. ``That sounds pretty simple, but we are.''
   ``We're not giving up any vote to Wayne Dowdy,'' he said.
   ``He's spending a lot of money,'' said Dowdy campaign spokesman
Dean Pittman. ``But basically what he's spending money on is
disguising his abysmal record on civil rights.''
   While polls show Lott leading overall in the Senate race, they
also indicate he has barely dented black support for Dowdy.
   An independent poll conducted in late September and early
October by Mason-Dixon Opinion Research showed Lott leading Dowdy
49 percent to 41 percent with 10 percent undecided. Among black
voters, though, the poll shows Dowdy with a 10-to-1 lead over Lott.
   The poll, which surveyed 812 likely voters, has a margin of
error of plus or minus 3.5 percentage points.
   Although there are two major-party black candidates running for
the Senate this year, Maurice Dawkins in Virginia and Alan L. Keyes
in Maryland, both are Republicans and are considered long shots in
races against popular Democrats, former Gov. Charles Robb in
Virginia and Sen. Paul Sarbanes in Maryland.
   Both Republicans and Democrats say the two black Senate
candidates are not tokens nominated to water down traditional
support for the Democrats.
   ``Dawkins ... was in no sense hand-picked,'' said Anita Dunn,
spokeswoman for the Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee. ``In
Keyes' case, he has fought any attempt to make it look like he is a
token black running.''
</TEXT>
