<1ST_LINE>r p PM-NBC-JournalPoll     10-18 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-NBC-Journal Poll,270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NBC-Journal Poll Finds Bush Ahead by 17 Points</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican presidential nominee George Bush held
a 17-point lead in a new national poll, and nearly three quarters
of the respondents said they expected him to win next month's
election.
   The NBC News-Wall Street Journal poll Monday put the race at
55-38 percent, Bush's biggest lead over Democrat Michael Dukakis
since the campaign began. The margin was considerably greater than
in surveys earlier this month.
   Told of the result, Dukakis campaign chairman Paul Brountas
said: ``I don't believe it.'' He said the campaign's own polls
indicated a smaller, unspecified deficit, with more undecided
voters.
   It was the first full-sized poll after Thursday's debate, in
which smaller overnight polls found Bush the winner. Bush led
Dukakis by 10 points in those polls, but they were conducted only
among debate viewers, a more Republican group. Bush led by five or
six points in most pre-debate polls.
   Said Brountas: ``If there has been an increase in the gap it may
be attributable to some of the stories about the debate.''
   The NBC-Journal poll was conducted Friday through Sunday among
1,378 likely voters and had a three-point margin of error. Almost
three-quarters of the respondents said they expected Bush to win
the election, including half of Dukakis' own supporters.
   Dukakis was rated favorably by 36 percent, down from 50 percent
a month ago. Bush was favorably rated by 55 percent, up from 50
percent. Bush led chiefly among men: They backed him by 64-30
percent, while the race among women was a nearly even, with Bush
ahead 48-44.
</TEXT>
