<1ST_LINE>r p AM-ChicagoMayoral     10-18 0272</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chicago Mayoral,0279</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Burke Joins Crowded Democratic Field</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alderman Edward Burke, a feisty onetime policeman
known as a political opponent of the late Mayor Harold Washington,
said Monday he would run for mayor and try to unite the city.
   Burke's entry is another in a crowded field of Democratic
candidates seeking to win a special mayoral election and serve the
final two years of Washington's four-year term.
   The city's first black mayor, who died suddenly last November,
considered Burke, who is white, one of his chief opponents in the
City Council.
   Burke, acknowledging his reputation might be tarnished among
blacks and some liberals by council battles against Washington
allies, said he should have acted differently.
   ``It takes humility to admit publicly that I have made mistakes,
and there are many things I would change,'' he said. ``But I would
be unfit for future government service if I did not have the
strength to admit my errors.''
   Burke, 45, said he would stay in the race ``if the money is
there, if I have support.''
   Burke has served in the City Council since 1969 when, at age 24,
he succeeded his late father, Alderman Joseph Burke.
   A week after Washington's death, aldermen installed Eugene
Sawyer as acting mayor. He is expected to run next year but has not
made an official announcement.
   Alderman Tim Evans also is expected to be a candidate, although
he has not made an official declaration. Rounding out the
Democratic field, Aldermen Danny Davis and Lawrence Bloom, former
parks boss Edmund Kelly and former Alderman Aloysius Majerczyk say
they will be in the February primary.
</TEXT>
