<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Obit-SuspendedAnimation     10-18 0181</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Suspended Animation,0186</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Who Was Put In Coma Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 76-year-old woman who had been in a coma
since surgeons placed her in ``suspended animation'' six week ago
to remove an egg-sized aneurysm near her brain has died.
   Cecilia Duffy of Pittsburgh died Monday, hours after she was
transferred to D.T. Watson Rehabilitation Hospital for therapy.
   She suffered cardio-pulmonary arrest, said John Righetti
spokesman at the suburban hospital.
   Duffy had been listed in fair condition before being transferred
from Allegheny General Hospital, said Allegheny General spokeswoman
Karen Long.
   Surgeons at Allegheny General put Duffy in a coma Aug. 31 and
stopped her heart 51 minutes so they could remove the aneurysm.
   During the operation, doctors reduced her body temperature by 40
degrees, drained her blood and placed her in ``suspended
animation,'' which lets surgeons cure high-risk aneurysms once
considered inoperable.
   Doctors said Duffy opened her eyes in late September for the
first time after the operation. She was transferred to D.T. Watson
so she could begin undergoing rehabilitative therapy designed to
help the injured brain heal.
</TEXT>
