<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--KosherMarketVandalized     10-18 0137</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Kosher Market Vandalized,0140</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jewish Business Vandalized</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A kosher meat market vandalized last year on the
anniversary of ``Kristallnacht'' was hit again by vandals who wrote
``stay away from the Jews,'' the store's owner said.
   ``We left there at 3:30 in the afternoon Friday, and between
that and Sunday morning, someone used a red marking pen to write on
the window,'' Melvin Plotsky, owner of Kosher Zion Meat Inc., said
Monday.
   In 1987, the market was one of 10 Jewish businesses and three
synagogues vandalized on the 49th anniversary of Kristallnacht, a
night of attacks against Jewish businesses in Nazi Germany.
   Kosher Zion's windows were smashed last year, Plotsky said.
   The 50th anniversary of Kristallnacht, which means ``the night
of broken glass,'' is next month.
   Police had no suspects, said Sgt. Raymond Callahan.
</TEXT>
