<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-88 0143EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ChristianCenterDeath 3rdLd-Writethru a0792 10-18 1082</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Christian Center Death, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0792,1106</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oregon Granted Custody of Children After Testimony About Beatings</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 7th graf, `The children ...' with 2 grafs to UPDATE with
arrest of Broussard's brother in Los Angeles; ADDS 4 grafs with
details.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PD1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. CRUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OREGON CITY, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State officials Monday were granted
custody of 55 hungry children taken from a farmhouse where an
8-year-old girl allegedly was beaten to death by staff members of a
California religious center.
   The girl, the daughter of Ecclesia Athletic Association founder
Eldridge Broussard Jr., was taken to a fire station Friday by four
adults connected with Broussard's group. She was already dead.
   Dayna Lorea Broussard had been beaten and whipped severely,
state Medical Examiner Dr. Larry Lewman said.
   Some of the other children bore marks and scars, said Bart
Wilson, Clackamas County branch manager of the state Children's
Service Division.
   ``We're led to believe that abuse had occurred,'' Wilson said.
``It's our recommendation that these children remain in protective
custody, at least for a period of time.''
   Clackamas County Circuit Judge Patrick Gilroy agreed, granting
custody of the youngsters to the state Children's Services Division
on grounds of neglect and improper care.
   In Los Angeles, meanwhile, Broussard's 25-year-old brother,
Alvin, posted $3,000 bail after he was booked Sunday for
investigation of child endangerment, said Los Angeles Police Cmdr.
William Booth. An arraignment was scheduled Nov. 10, Booth said
Monday.
   In Oregon, the children, ranging in age from 1{ months to 16
years, were sleeping on pillows on the floor of the sparsely
furnished four-bedroom house, Wilson said. They were placed in
state juvenile centers and foster homes over the weekend.
   ``They were quite hungry when they arrived. It seems that they
only had a tomato apiece on Friday,'' said Bill Carey, acting
director of client services for the state Children's Services
Division.
   According to authorities, the children were subjected to
systematic beatings with a paddle or electrical cord used to apply
up to 800 strokes in front of other children, who were required to
keep count. The trauma of receiving and witnessing such punishments
has caused psychological damage to the youngsters, the Clackamas
County Juvenile Department told the court.
   The department's director, Donald Welch, said the children ``had
been unfed for an extended period of time and were in need of
immediate nutrition. .. They ate voluminously when afforded the
opportunity.''
   Representatives of 15 of the 18 families involved, from
California, met with officials later in the day, and indicated they
knew their children were in Oregon, Wilson said. He said no visits
would be allowed immediately.
   Another, unrelated religious boarding home, the Bethel Home for
Children outside Lucedale, Miss., fell afoul of Mississippi
authorities in June because of alleged abuse of troubled or
neglected youths.
   Law enforcement officials clashed with the school's founder, the
Rev. Herman Fountain, a former heroin addict turned independent
Baptist minister. A grand jury next week will consider felony
assault charges against Fountain, but no abuse or neglect charges
were filed and the school is back in business.
   In another court hearing Monday, an attorney for Willie K.
Chambers, one of the four people charged in the death, asked that
the Broussard girl's body not be released pending an independent
autopsy.
   A murder charge against Chambers, 35, of San Diego, was reduced
to first-degree manslaughter, and the other defendants, who had
been held on murder charges, were charged with manslaughter.
   Bail was set at $250,000 apiece for Chambers, Brian James
Brinson, 30; Constance Zipporah Jackson, 37; and Frederick Paul
Doolittle, 28, all of Los Angeles.
   Clackamas County District Judge Steven L. Maurer set preliminary
hearings for Oct. 21 for Chambers and Oct. 24 for the other three.
   Alfred J. French III, a deputy Clackamas County district
attorney, said the charges were reduced because of difficulty in
proving intent. A grand jury will begin hearing evidence in the
case this week.
   Broussard attended the hearing, but declined to speak to
reporters.
   The onetime college athlete, also leader of the Watts Christian
Center in Los Angeles, was interviewed by Clackamas County
sheriff's detectives Sunday, but declined to address a news
conference. In a statement to a Portland television reporter, he
said the media had slanted stories about Ecclesia and portrayed him
as a ``crackpot.''
   ``Our whole group has been pressured into all manner of
activities we would not have had to do had we been understood a
little better,'' he told KATU-TV. He did not elaborate.
   Broussard, 35, was a star basketball player at Pacific
University in Forest Grove, Ore., in the 1970s. He founded the
Ecclesia Athletic Association in 1975.
   Last year, Ecclesia officials claimed to have established a camp
at the farm near Sandy to train children for the Olympics. But it
was unclear whether the children found Friday were in a similar
training program.
   The organization brought an estimated 70 to 100 men, women and
children from Los Angeles to the Sandy area in April 1987. They
returned to Los Angeles in June 1987 after neighbors opposed
Ecclesia's applications for zoning permits to allow 55 children and
45 adults to live in tents and use portable toilets and showers.
   Carolyn Van Brunt, a spokeswoman for Broussard, said Ecclesia no
longer exists in name but continues in spirit and concept.
   She said the group sometimes uses ``physical correction'' as a
form of discipline, but denied the punishment was cruel.
   Two other members of Broussard's group were held pending
$100,000 bail each on charges of hindering prosecution. They were
identified as Sherion Melinda Johnson, 32, and Josie Ruth Faust,
50, both of Los Angeles.
   In Los Angeles, Alvin Broussard was taken into custody at the
Watts Christian Center after five children, believed to have been
transported from Ecclesia, were found at the south-central Los
Angeles center Sunday afternoon.
   ``One of the boys had evidence that he was physically assaulted
while in Oregon,'' Booth said in Los Angeles. ``One of the boys
probably was physically abused here.'' The spokesman could not
release the names of the minors, only saying that the boys were 10
and 15 and three girls ranged in age from 10 to 17.
   The children were placed with the Los Angeles County Departent
of Children's Services. It was not immediately determined whether
the girls had been abused.
   The younger Broussard and the children were the only ones at the
Watts center at the time of the arrest, Booth said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
