<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-88 0225EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Argentina-Falklands     10-18 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Argentina-Falklands,0486</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ex President Galtieri Defends 1982 Decision To Invade Falklands</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICENTE F. LOPEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Gen. Leopoldo
Galtieri, on trial for mismanaging the 1982 war with Britain over
the Falkland Islands, says he would invade the territory again and
does not regret starting a war.
   ```Would I do it again? Given the same circumstances and
conditions, would I proceed in the same manner? The answer is yes.
I, Lt. Gen. Galtieri, would proceed the same way as I did,''
Galtieri said in Federal Appeals Court on Monday. ``What was done,
was done well.''
   Galtieri and two other members of the former ruling junta _ Adm.
Jorge Anaya and Brig. Gen. Basilio Lami Dozo _ were convicted in
May 1986 by the Supreme Council of the Armed Forces of military
mismanagement. All were sentenced to prison.
   On July 26, their appeal began in civilian court, along with
three officers who had been acquitted by the military's highest
tribunal: Vice Adm. Juan Jose Lombardo, Gen. Mario Menendez, and
Gen. Omar Parada.
   The issue is how the war was handled, including Galtieri's
decision to send about 12,000 troops to the islands, located 250
miles northeast of Tierra del Fuego off the southernmost tip of
South America.
   Prosecutor Luis Moreno Ocampo questioned the military's tactics
and strategy, including Anaya's decision, as head of the navy, to
virtually withdraw the fleet from combat after the cruiser General
Belgrano was sunk in early May by a British nuclear submarine.
   Argentine conscripts were ill-trained, inadequately supplied and
poorly led, witnesses said.
   The conflict began on April 2, 1982, and lasted 74 days. About
700 Argentines were killed along with 255 British troops.
   In his defense, Galtieri said the war for the islands that
Argentina calls the Malvinas was narrowly lost, so charges of
mismanagement are ill-founded.
   ``The battle for the South Atlantic, militarily, was lost by a
narrow margin,'' he said.
   Britain claimed the islands in 1833. Argentina claims it
inherited the islands from Spain upon achieving independence in
1810.
   The underpopulated, windswept islands are home to about 1,900
people, mostly sheep ranchers and fishermen. Also at stake are the
rights to potentially large deposits of oil and other natural
resources.
   For Argentina, nationalism is a factor. Every map calls the
islands the Malvinas. Every school child learns they were seized
from Argentina and should be returned.
   Galtieri, who was sentenced to 12 years in prison by the
military tribunal and who faces a stiffer, 20-year sentence if he
loses his appeal, was not repentant when he addressed the civilian
court.
   ``In 1982, destiny knocked at the doors of the nation,'' he
said. ``And the people, with dignity, decided to fulfill a
historical obligation'' and reclaim the islands.
   The court's decision was expected by early next week.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
