<DOCNO> AP881018-0033 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-88 0230EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-AIDSCampaign     10-18 0721</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS Campaign,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New AIDS TV Spots Avoid The `C' Word</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top federal official says Americans should
look to television networks and other news outlets if they think
the government should be more forthright in calling for use of
condoms to combat the spread of AIDS.
   A new wave of television spots unveiled Monday does not mention
what one reporter called ``the C word'' but leaves little to the
imagination of any viewer who has heard that condoms can help
prevent spread of the deadly disease.
   The 1987 series of television ads distributed to national
networks and thousands of individual stations contained direct
references to condoms in some spots that got little airplay despite
$18 million worth of free airtime devoted to less controversial
messages.
   Nonetheless, one of the 1988 ads features a tantalizing episode
in which a young man talks to the camera as he puts a sock on his
foot.
   ``If I told you I could save my life just by putting on my
socks, you wouldn't take me seriously,'' says the man, sitting in a
chair.
   ``Because life is never that simple,'' he adds.
   ``But watch ...''
   There are a few seconds of silence as he slips a sock onto his
foot.
   ``Okay, you're right,'' the man says. ``That wouldn't really
save my life. But there's something just as simple that could.''
   Questioned at a news conference, Dr. James Mason, director of
the Centers for Disease Control, said there was a simple answer to
why the government avoided specifically mentioning condoms in the
new round of television spots.
   ``We had a great deal of difficulty getting the television
stations to use that,'' he said, referring to 1987 spots that
specifically mentioned condoms. ``That one was selectively avoided
by the television stations.''
   Mason said designers of the 1987 ad campaign tried to be careful
to produce spots that would not be offensive to audiences even
though some of them did discuss condoms.
   But he said experience showed ``there was another level of
screening'' at networks and local TV stations that resulted in the
condom spots rarely being seen by a general audience.
   With more than a dozen cameras rolling, Mason was among several
officials who declined to answer directly when asked whether
television executives were engaging in irresponsible behavior in
public health by declining to run condom spots.
   Eventually, Stephanie Lee-Miller, the administration's top
public relations official in the Health and Human Services
Department who had been moderating the news conference, stepped
forward.
   ``I'll answer it,'' she said. ``No, they're not engaging in
responsible behavior.''
   She asked reporters to ``challenge the networks'' rather than
the health department.
   Indeed, the print ads and posters prepared for the new campaign
deals with condom use in a direct way likely to draw criticism from
conservatives.
   ``If He Won't Wear A Condom, Call For Help,'' says one suggested
newspaper ad.
   One of numerous posters features a still photo from the TV spot
where the man is putting a sock on his foot. ``Putting On A Condom
Is Just As Simple,'' says the headline.
   Another series of six posters feature photos of three different
men and three different women with the same headline on each: `What
Have You Got Against A Condom?'' The smaller print says, ``The
simple act of putting on a condom can save your life, if they're
used properly and every time you have sex. For more information
about AIDS and condoms, call 1-800-342-AIDS.''
   Another series features three different women all saying, ``If
he doesn't have a condom, you just have to take a deep breath and
tell him to go get one.''
   Many critics have said federal officials and Ogilvy & Mather,
the private advertising company hired to produce the campaign, went
too far last year in trying to get sexually active Americans to use
condoms. Others said the ads were not explicit enough.
   Mason said federal health officials have always said that
abstinence or a monogamous relationship with an uninfected partner
are the only two absolute ways to prevent sexual spread of AIDS.
   ``Condoms are third best,'' he said, adding it is nonetheless
important for health officials to recommend their use for those who
are not abstinent or in monogamous relationships with partners they
are certain are uninfected.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
