<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-88 0252EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Mexico-Economy     10-18 0363</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mexico-Economy,0372</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mexican Economic Program Extended into New Administration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS ANGELO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Labor and business leaders hailed
President-elect Carlos Salinas de Gortari's extension of an
inflation-fighting program for one month after he takes office.
   Citing progress under the 10-month-old plan and other economic
reforms, the U.S. Treasury and the U.S. Federal Reserve announced
in Washington on Monday they were preparing as much as $3.5 billion
in short-term ``bridge'' loans for Mexico.
   Under the Economic Solidarity Pact, Mexico's business, farm and
labor sectors and the government pledged last December to cooperate
in holding down wages and prices.
   The latest extension to Dec. 31, published in newspapers on
Monday, said recent measures taken by the government were helping
hold down inflation. It mentioned a new cut in government spending,
continued efforts to close or sell unprofitable and non-strategic
state companies, and maintenance of monetary and credit policies
that support price stability.
   ``We will not continue from crisis to crisis, but are going to
achieve growth without inflation,'' said Claudio X. Gonzalez,
former president of the Business Coordinating Council, in remarks
quoted by the Excelsior news service.
   Hector Hugo Olivares Ventura, leader of the National
Confederation of Campesinos, said the pact was not ``a
straitjacket'' on workers' salaries but rather ensured that wages
could be upwardly adjusted under the plan's freeze on official
prices.
   Under the reform pact, labor has foregone wage increases since
March, arguing that a small rise would give business a pretext for
price hikes _ thus causing workers to lose ground.
   Prices of basic goods are controlled, but subsidies on many
products have been gradually lifted to reduce the budget deficit.
   The monthly increase in consumer prices has been slashed from
15.5 percent in January to 0.6 percent in September under the plan.
The rate for the first nine months of the year was 45.5 percent.
When the accord was signed last December, inflation was rising to a
rate of 159.2 percent for the year.
   ``The recent trend in prices has been satisfactory since it
allowed the monthly rate of increase in September to reach the
lowest level in 12 years,'' the statement said.
</TEXT>
