<HEAD>Dollar Up, Stocks Slip</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar edged up agaisnt the Japanese yen
Tuesday, while share prices fell on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The dollar closed at 127.70 yen, up 0.50 yen from Monday's close
of 127.20 yen. Opening at 127.55 yen, the currency moved in a range
of 127.20-128.00 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 37.83-point
loser the previous day, lost 126.76 points Tuesday, or 0.46
percent, to finish trading at 27,141.98. The index lost 28.41
points shortly after the market opened, then fell at a slower pace.
   ``Participants were less motivated in investing, which resulted
in thin trading,'' said an analyst who noted that news about
Emperor Hirohito's health has affected the Tokyo market more than a
economic factors.
   Japan's 87-year-old emperor has been bedridden since Sept. 19
and recently underwent a blood transfusion.
   In foreign exchange, news reports said Bank of Japan Governor
Satoshi Sumita indicated the major central banks may intervene to
support the dollar if the U.S. currency continues to decline
sharply against the yen.
