<1ST_LINE>r w PM-PopulationAwards     10-18 0233</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Population Awards,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Population Reporting Awards Announced</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Population Institute named news
organizations around the world as winners of the ninth annual
Global Media Awards for coverage of population issues.
   The winners announced Monday, which included The Associated
Press, The Kansas City Star, the Milwaukee Journal and National
Public Radio, were selected from 850 entries.
   The awards will be presented by President Suharto of Indonesia
in ceremonies Dec. 2 in Jakarta, according to Werner Fornos,
president of the Institute, which works to draw attention to
population issues.
   Winners of the awards are:
   _Best team reporting: Milwaukee Journal series ``Empty Cradles:
The Global Tragedy of Infant Mortality.''
   _Best population editorials: The Kansas City Star.
   _Most conscientious news service: The Associated Press.
   _Best international daily: International Herald Tribune.
   _Best columnist: Pranay Gupte of Newsweek magazine.
   _Best radio program: Patricia Neighmond of National Public Radio
for coverage of population problems in India.
   _Best television documentary: Christian Science Monitor Reports,
``Exploding City: The Mexican Population Crisis.''
   _Best major daily: El Comercio of Peru.
   _Best combined media: coordinated radio, television and
newspaper coverage in the Ivory Coast.
   _Best individual reporting: Co-winners, Klaus Natorp of
Frankfurter Allgemeine and writer Nuraini R. S. Melialia of
Indonesia.
   _Best population-environmental reporting: Hugo Davenport of the
London Daily Telegraph.
   _Best population journal: Populii magazine, published by the
United Nations Population Fund.
   _Best periodical: The Economist.
   _Best cartoonist: Dik Browne.
</TEXT>
