<DOCNO> AP881018-0043 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-88 0329EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Philippines-BasesOutlook     10-18 0738</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines-Bases Outlook,0760</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Faces Sell Job, Disappointment Due To Excess
Expectations</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT H. REID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Corazon Aquino faces a hard
road in selling the newly concluded U.S. bases agreement to the
public and may be forced to harden her position on the thornier
issue of the installations' status after 1991.
   First reaction to the agreement, signed Monday in Washington,
was at best mixed. Major newspapers accused the government of
selling out by agreeing to allow the six bases to remain through
1991 in return for ``only'' $962 million in American aid.
   That was more than 2{ times the $180 million a year which
President Reagan pledged in 1983 over a five-year period to
now-ousted President Ferdinand Marcos.
   But the fact that the Philippines won far more U.S. assistance
was all but lost on the public and press due to the government's
having raised expectations which U.S. diplomats all along said were
unrealistic.
   Even before the talks began April 5, Manila newspapers quoted
unidentified government sources as saying the Aquino administration
would insist on $1.2 billion a year.
   Foreign Secretary Raul Manglapus never explicitly confirmed the
$1.2 billion demand but termed it ``reasonable.'' Manglapus aides
privately told Filipino reporters that the government would hold
fast to its demands.
   Manglapus himself said repeatedly that compensation was not the
only issue. But other issues he cited, such as confirmation of
nuclear weapons at the bases and expanded criminal jurisdiction
over U.S. troops, were not addressed in the new agreement.
   In Washington, Manglapus told reporters he was optimistic that
once the Filipino public understood the agreement, ``they will
accept it.''
   Indeed, one longtime bases opponent, Sen. Aquilino Pimentel,
said the results of the negotiations ``are certainly much better
than before.''
   But the absence of a detailed explanation by the government of
the benefits of the agreement opened the door to criticism from the
press and some lawmakers, who hope to make the bases an issue in
the runup to the 1992 national elections.
   Under the new Constitution, any extension after 1991 must be
approved by two-thirds of the 23-member Senate, where opposition to
the bases is strong.
   Several senators are widely assumed to harbor presidential
ambitions and are casting for an issue in the 1992 election, in
which Mrs. Aquino says she will not be a candidate.
   The fact that the latest agreement was hammered out in
Washington, and not Manila, raised charges that the government had
indulged in the same kind of secret diplomacy for which the Marcos
administration had been roundly criticized.
   Manglapus has been in the United States for nearly a month. When
asked whether Mrs. Aquino herself was fully aware of all aspects of
the final negotiations, her spokesman Teodoro Benigno replied ``I
don't think so.''
   Instead, Mrs. Aquino left details of the negotiations to
Manglapus, who has not entirely shaken off his longtime image as an
``Am-Boy,'' or ``American Boy,'' a derogatory term for Filipinos
who support U.S. interests.
   That strategy appeared designed in part to allow Mrs. Aquino to
escape personal political damage if the public found the agreement
unsatisfactory.
   The results of the just concluded talks were expected to
influence the government's decision on whether to negotiate a new
pact extending the bases beyond 1991.
   Such negotiations _ assuming they are held _ will be difficult.
   Recent surveys show a majority of Filipinos favor retention of
the bases but under favorable terms, including fixed rent. But
Communist rebels and a significant portion of the urban middle
class, including journalists and intellectuals, are strongly
opposed to the bases, regardless of the financial impact if they
were closed.
   ``We seem to have hung out a price tag on our sovereignty and
national dignity,'' wrote columnist Letty Jimenez-Magsanoc in the
Philippine Daily Inquirer. ``We are now selling out even when the
price isn't right.''
   In such a climate, issues which are viewed here as basic to
national sovereignty are likely to be raised. These include formal
notification of the presence of nuclear weapons as well as military
operations launched from Philippine soil.
   Filipino military officers are routinely barred from some
sensitive areas such as code rooms, even though the six bases are
nominally under Philippine command.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _
   EDITOR'S NOTE _ Robert H. Reid has been a foreign correspondent
for 11 years and has been chief of the Manila bureau of The
Associated Press since 1986.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
