<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-88 0352EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MafiaInformer     10-18 0342</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mafia Informer,0351</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Drops Drug Charges Against Mob Informant Tommaso Buscetta</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heroin smuggling charges have been dismissed
against a key Mafia informant who testified against his associates
at the ``maxi-trial'' in Sicily and the ``pizza connection'' drug
case here.
   The U.S. government officially dropped the six-count indictment
Monday, saying Tommaso Buscetta had ``fulfilled the terms'' of his
cooperation agreement with the U.S. and Italian governments.
   ``Buscetta has provided, and continues to provide, exhaustive
information concerning the activities of the Mafia here and in
Italy,'' said Assistant U.S. Attorney Thomas Rose in court papers.
   ``Moreover, largely as a result of Buscetta's testimony at
trials in the United States and Italy, hundreds of defendants have
been convicted of heroin trafficking and associated organized crime
activity.''
   The drug indictment against Buscetta was filed in 1973 in U.S.
District Court in Brooklyn. The order to dismiss the indictment,
which contained the only outstanding charges against Buscetta, was
signed by Judge Joseph McLaughlin.
   Its dismissal was included in a cooperation agreement Buscetta
entered with the U.S. and Italian governments in 1985.
   Rose said Buscetta had been a soldier ``of great respect'' in
the Sicilian Mafia, where his duties included settling disputes and
acting as an emissary between families.
   His testimony at the ``pizza connection'' trial helped convict
18 defendants of participating in a Mafia-backed drug racket,
operated in part through pizza parlors, that imported an estimated
$1.6 billion worth of heroin into the United States.
   He was the prosecution's first witness at the 17-month trial
that ended in March 1986, and he identified certain defendants as
members of the Sicilian Mafia.
   Buscetta also was among a dozen admitted Mafia members who
testified at the Italian trial, described as the largest Mafia
trial ever conducted. More than 300 defendants were convicted in
that case last year.
   Rose said Buscetta would remain in a witness protection program
administered by the federal Drug Enforcement Administration. He has
been given a new identity and is living in this country.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
