<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Hirohito 1stLd-Writethru a0433 10-18 0321</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hirohito, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0433,0326</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hirohito Receives Emergency Transfusion, But Reported Stable</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES with condition stable after emergency transfusions.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KOZO MIZOGUCHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emperor Hirohito lost a large amount of blood early
today but was in stable condition after being given emergency blood
transfusions, palace officials said.
   Doctors gave the frail 87-year-old monarch a total of 1.3 pints
of blood overnight to compensate for the bleeding, the officials
said. It was the largest amount of blood the emperor has lost since
he discharged close to 2.1 pints from his bowels on Oct. 1, news
reports said.
   Iwao Miyao, vice grand steward of the Imperial Household Agency,
said there had been no new discharge as of this afternoon, but
doctors were ready to administer more blood at any time.
   Hirohito has been in serious condition since Sept. 19 when his
internal bleeding, thought to be coming from his upper intestine,
caused him to vomit a large amount of blood.
   Doctors believe the discharge this morning came from blood that
had accumulated over time from his internal hemorrhaging, palace
officials said.
   Palace spokesman Kenji Maeda told reporters the world's oldest
living monarch was ``in stable condition and fully conscious.''
   He said Hirohito had eaten small amounts of porridge during the
past four days, the first food he has had since Oct. 1. Doctors
have been concerned about the emperor's declining nutritional
status caused by his intraveneous feeding, which is unable to
provide enough nutrients.
   Today's transfusions brought the total amount of blood Hirohito
has received since his condition worsened to 19.8 pints, reportedly
about twice the total amount of blood in his body.
   The emperor underwent an intestinal bypass operation a year ago
after an enlarged pancreas put pressure on his intestine, blocking
the passage of food. Imperial Household officials said then he was
suffering from chronic pancreatitis and no signs of pancreatic
cancer were found.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
