<DOCNO> AP881018-0047 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-88 0408EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SriLanka     10-18 0301</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sri Lanka,0307</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Six Civilians Killed in Violence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen wearing military-style uniforms
shot and stabbed six people to death in eastern Sri Lanka, an army
spokesman said today.
   The official, who cannot be identified under briefing rules,
said four Tamil and two Sinhalese men were shot and stabbed late
Monday in the village of Seyiliyamadu, about 175 miles east of
Colombo, the island's capital.
   The official said the slayings could have been done by either
militant Tamils fighting for a separate nation in the northeastern
province or extremist Sinhalese opposed to the government's peace
overtures to the Tamil rebels.
   Tamils, who are mostly Hindu, comprise 18 percent of the
island's 16 million people. Militant Tamils have been fighting
since 1983 for an independent homeland in the northeast.
   A peace accord aimed at ending the 5-year-old insurgency offered
Tamils limited automony in the region, and election of a provincial
council is scheduled for Nov. 19. In exchange, Tamil rebels must
surrender their weapons and end the fighting that has claimed at
least 8,500 lives.
   The most militant group, the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Ealam,
accepted the agreement after it was signed by India and Sri Lanka
in July 1987. They reneged three months later, saying it did not
meet enough demands, and India sent an estimated 47,000 troops to
the island to put down the rebellion.
   Radicals in the Sinhalese community, which makes up 75 percent
of the island's population and controls the government, also oppose
the peace accord. They claim it grants too many concessions to the
Tamils.
   They have vowed to kill anyone who supports the agreement and
have been blamed for more than 500 deaths in the past year,
including members of the governing United National Party.
</TEXT>
