<DOCNO> AP881018-0049 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-88 0418EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets     10-18 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0376</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Higher, Stocks Slip</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar edged up against the Japanese yen today
while share prices, affected by reports of Emperor Hirohito's
worsened condition, fell on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, which lost 27.83 points
Monday, shed 126.76 points today, or 0.46 percent, to close at
27,141.98. The index lost 28.41 points in its early trading and
continued falling at a slower pace. Monday's closing Nikkei was
27,268.74 points.
   News that the emperor received an emergency blood transfusion
today caused many buyers to wait on the sidelines, traders said.
   ``Obviously, it's because of the emperor's ... blood
transfusion,'' said an analyst with Nomura Securities, Japan's
largest brokerage, speaking anonymously.
   ``Participants were less motivated in investing, which resulted
in thin trading,'' he said, adding the news affected the Tokyo
market more than any economic factor. Volume traded on the first
section was estimated at 400 million shares.
   Emperor Hirohito, 87, received the transfusion after he passed a
large amount of blood overnight and Monday morning. The world's
longest-reigning living monarch has been bedridden since Sept. 19
when he vomited blood from internal hemorrhaging.
   On the foreign exchange market, the dollar closed at 127.70 yen,
up 0.50 yen from Monday's close of 127.20 yen. Opening at 127.55
yen, the currency moved slightly higher and ranged between 127.20
and 128.00 yen.
   The dollar recovered slightly when some investors bought the
currency ``in fear of the cental bank's intervention near the
126-yen level,'' said a dealer with Mitsubishi Bank, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   ``Most of the market players believed the Bank of Japan would
buy dollars if the rate kept falling,'' he said, adding
participants became more certain after the Bank of Japan inquired
about the dollar-yen rate Monday, which they took to mean the bank
was considering intervening.
   ``Some speculative investors also bought the dollar, and the
dollar-selling trend on the whole was still strong,'' the dealer
said.
   News reports said Bank of Japan Governor Satoshi Sumita
indicated this morning the central banks of major industrial
countires may carrry out concerted intervention to support the
dollar if it continues to decline sharply against the yen.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
