<1ST_LINE>u i PM-China-Dissident     10-18 0443</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Dissident,0458</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Denies Dissident Permission To Visit United States</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China has withdrawn permission for outspoken
dissident Fang Lizhi to visit the United States and accused him of
spreading falsehoods about Chinese leaders, Fang said today.
   Fang, an astrophysicist at the Beijing Observatory, denied the
accusations and said he was reapplying for permission.
   The Chinese Academy of Sciences gave Fang permission in May to
attend a symposium in Texas starting Dec. 12 and spend six months
at the Colorado Joint Institute for Laboratory Astrophysics.
   But he told The Associated Press today that the academy had sent
him a letter reversing its decision.
   The letter said ``relevant leaders were dissatisfied'' with
comments Fang made during a recent trip to Australia and Hong Kong,
he said. He spent three weeks in Australia in August and September
on an academic visit and spent a week in Hong Kong on his way back.
   Fang's wife, Li Shuxian, said the letter also accused Fang of
spreading rumors and said he should have gotten academy approval
for the stop in Hong Kong.
   Fang said he wrote to the academy denying its accusations and
reapplying to go.
   ``Whether leaders are happy or not should not affect normal
scientific exchanges,'' Li quoted him as saying in the letter.
   Fang confirmed that in an informal meeting with Chinese students
in Australia he mentioned rumors that many Chinese leaders and
their children maintain foreign bank accounts.
   The official Chinese news agency Xinhua challenged Fang to
defend his comments when he arrived in Hong Kong.
   But Fang said the rumors are ``very common, even among the
students I talked to in Australia,'' and that he made no public
accusations against officials.
   He said all his comments abroad were permitted under the Chinese
constitution, and denied Hong Kong press reports that he derided
the Chinese government's four basic principles: socialism,
leadership by the Communist Party, the dictatorship of the
proletariat and Marxism-Leninism-Mao Tse-tung thought.
   However, Fang said he stands by his comments both in China and
abroad criticizing Marxism and one-party rule.
   ``Everything has a beginning and an end. Even the ideology of
the Communist Party says that it (the party) will come to an end,''
Fang said.
   Fang became famous in China in 1986 after supporting democracy
in speeches to students at the University of Science and Technology
in Hefei in central China. Authorities said his speeches helped
incite students in Hefei and at major cities nationwide to join
pro-democracy demonstrations that were suppressed in early 1987.
   Fang was expelled from the Communist Party shortly later and
forced to resign as vice president of the University of Science and
Technology.
</TEXT>
