<1ST_LINE>r a PM-JewishLobby     10-18 0369</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jewish Lobby,0377</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Leaders of Three Jewish Groups Disagree With Pro-Israel Lobby</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of three mainstream Jewish groups have
charged Israel's chief lobbying organization in Washington is out
of step with ``the consensus of the organized Jewish community,'' a
newspaper reported today.
   The leaders of the three organizations made the charge in a
letter addressed to Edward C. Levy Jr., president of the American
Israel Public Affairs Committee, The New York Times said.
   The six signers of the letter, which was obtained by the
newspaper, are top officials of the American Jewish Committee, the
American Jewish Congress and the Anti-Defamation League of B'nai
B'rith.
   The letter, according to the Times, said Aipac did not represent
``the consensus of the organized Jewish community'' on important
Middle East issues.
   The six said they disagreed with Aipac's opposition to arms
sales to Kuwait; its efforts to shut down the Palestine Liberation
Organization's United Nations mission; and its effort to deny PLO
leader Yasser Arafat a visa to address the United Nations, the
newspaper reported.
   The letter says that the three organizations have established,
``a joint political committee for Israel in Washington'' to arrange
for the presentation of their testimony before congressional
committees and government agencies, the Times said.
   Abraham H. Foxman, national director of the ADL, said late
Monday, ``I think the letter is a desire on our part to better the
relationship between Aipac and the three agencies. The working
relationship with Aipac is good but we want it to be somewhat
better.''
   He noted that the three organizations, which have headquarters
in New York, already maintain offices in Washington so it was not
as if they were ``setting up anything new.'' It is not their
intention, he added, ``to set up as a competing group or to
duplicate what'' Aipac does.
   The three groups already are represented on Aipac's executive
committee, a policy-making body of about 150 people that meets four
times a year.
   A senior Aipac officer quoted anonymously told the Times: ``More
consultation is always desirable, but the establishment of a second
lobbying entity would undermine the effectiveness of the pro-Israel
community in presenting its case to public officials in Washington
and elsewhere.''
</TEXT>
