<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DoubleSuicide     10-18 0600</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Double Suicide,0620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Best Friends, Separated By Move, Commit Suicide Together</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SOUTH MILWAUKEE, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This community was in shock over
the suicides of two 15-year-old boys who police said shared a
hunting rifle to kill themselves out of despondency at being
separated when one of their families moved away.
   South Milwaukee High School Principal Norman S. Klein tried to
prepare teachers and staff members to deal with student suicide
threats and attempts, staging a ``simulation suicide exercise'' two
weeks ago to rehearse a proper response.
   ``Even though we were prepared, it was a shock,'' said Klein,
53, a principal 12 years.
   The bodies of Michael J. Kruczkowski of South Milwaukee and
William A. Bollis, who recently moved with his family 70 miles
north to Malone, were found by Kruczkowski's mother in the attic of
their home Sunday evening.
   ``They were best of friends and they had been separated,''
Police Chief Erick A. Slamka said. ``The kid from up north had come
down to visit for the weekend, and it was when the father came to
pick him up that the bodies were discovered.''
   Evidence showed both boys died from a single shot to the head,
and the wounds appeared to be self-inflicted, Slamka said.
Kruczkowski shot himself first, police said.
   According to the medical examiner's report, the boys left two
printed notes addressed to their parents.
   One note said they decided to end their lives because they could
no longer be separated from their friends and each other, the
report said. The second note instructed the parents to listen to a
tape recording that explained the decision, it said.
   Police declined to release the words of the notes or tape, which
Slamka said ran no more than a minute.
   ``This wasn't spontaneous,'' Slamka said. ``It was planned,
though I'm not sure how long it was pre-planned.''
   The bodies were discovered after Bollis' father came to the home
and met Kruczkowski's mother. She went to the attic of the
wood-frame house, where her son lived with his father, and found
the bodies, Slamka said. Kruczkowski's parents are divorced.
   The .30-06-caliber rifle was owned by the Kruczkowski's father,
who also had other rifles in the home.
   There was no evidence that the boys had used drugs or alcohol,
the chief said. ``In fact, I'm not aware of any problems with the
two of them.''
   Slamka said he could not recall another case of a multiple
suicide in his 25 years on the force.
   ``From time to time we have gunshot suicides and young people
are involved,'' he said. ``Each time it's especially tragic, and in
the event of a double suicide, it multiplies the loss and the
concern you have for these people.''
   Early Monday, Slamka sent his school liaison officer to the high
school to meet with the principal. The deaths were announced over
the public address system and students were told counselors were
available to help them.
   Similar steps were taken at New Holstein High School in Calumet
County, about 70 miles north of Milwaukee, where Bollis was a
student, officials said.
   Tim Schwaller, a social worker for the South Milwaukee School
District, said the guidance counselor office was ``hopping all
morning'' with students wishing to talk about the deaths. Teachers
were told about the shootings and were urged to be open with
students should they ask what happened, he said.
   Klein also had to inform students Monday of the death of a math
teacher, Dale Parkinson, 44, from a heart attack Saturday.
   Funeral services were scheduled for Kruczkowski on Wednesday
evening and for Bollis on Thursday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
