<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-88 0622EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PumpkinShortage     10-18 0422</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pumpkin Shortage,0434</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Customers May Find Fewer Big Jack-O'-Lanterns After Drought</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT LEE ZIMMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHAMPAIGN, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vana LaCost says her customers can get
the great pumpkin _ but they'll have to shop early. Drought has
reduced the number of jumbo jack-o'lanterns in her eight-acre patch
as in other areas of the Midwest.
   ``The decorative pumpkin crop is short and people (in the
Midwest) will be paying more than usual for large pumpkins,'' said
J. M. Gerber, a pumpkin specialist at the University of Illinois.
``The problem area is as wide as the drought.''
   Pumpkin growers in the East have a good crop, but shipping them
to the Midwest is expensive and adds to the price, Gerber said.
   Decorative pumpkins are grown on smaller plots, usually near
urban areas. And because farmers often cannot afford to irrigate,
the drought can cause significant damage.
   This year, seed failed to germinate in the sun-baked Midwestern
soil, and vines that did grow either failed to produce as many
pumpkins, or produced smaller fruit than in previous years.
   Gerber said many growers in the Midwest realized their crop
would be smaller when the vines started dying and uncovering the
fruit.
   ``It will be the late shopper who has problems. The last week
before Halloween could be tight,'' Mrs. LaCost, whose farm is near
Kankakee, predicted Monday.
   She said she has kept pace with demand so far and the quality of
her pumpkins is good, but the drought cut her volume in half. She
would not specify her prices, but said they are a little higher
than last year.
   Consumers won't have to worry about a shortage of canned
pumpkins for holiday pies, say officials in Illinois, which leads
the country with about 5,000 acres of the commercially canned
product.
   ``We had a super year,'' said Jack Rohrs, plant manager for the
Libby division of Carnation Co.
   Libby processes about 100,000 tons of pumpkins a year at its
Morton plant. Rohrs said the size of the pumpkins was smaller than
usual, but the amount of fruit available was excellent.
   He said Libby's variety was deep-rooted and survived the summer
drought well. However, about 40 percent of Libby's growers use
irrigation.
   ``Our pumpkins were the best they ever were,'' said Lewis
Friedrich, a Tazewell County farmer who raises 180 acres of
pumpkins for Libby on irrigated land. He said his yields ranged
from 33 tons per acre to nearly 41 tons per acre, and Libby paid
$17 a ton for the crop.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881018-0059 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-88 0639EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-OfficialEnglish     10-18 0665</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Official English,0685</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chairman, Chavez Quit U.S. English Group</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY LOPEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of a group that wants English to be
the nation's official language says he resigned to let voters focus
on the issue instead of on allegations about his ties to advocates
of forced sterilization.
   The controversy has ``come to center more around me in the last
week or 10 days,'' John Tanton said Monday. He said his resignation
from U.S. English, which he co-founded, would give him time to
fight accusations.
   His decision followed announcements by former White House aide
Linda Chavez and retired CBS newsman Walter Cronkite that they were
severing their ties with the organization.
   Ms. Chavez said Monday she was quitting because she had been
told that some major contributors to Tanton's other interests
advocated unusual views on population and immigration control,
including advocacy of forced sterilization.
   ``To me it is just not consistent with the views I hold,'' she
said.
   Cronkite resigned from the advisory board to U.S. English on
Oct. 6 after learning of a 2-year-old Tanton memo.
   That memo, distributed at a 1986 immigration conference, posed a
series of questions and depicted an America possibly doomed to
conflict between a minority of educated well-off English speakers
and a majority of uneducated poor people of other ethnic and racial
groups with faster population growth.
   Tanton on Monday described the memo as ``a compilation of
questions and views of many observers on complex and controversial
issues.''
   ``Our opponents have falsely charged that it reflects the views
of myself or U.S. English and its positions on these initiatives,''
he added. ``There is no connection between a memo I wrote in 1986
and the initiatives for the ballot in November 1988.''
   U.S. English backs measures in Arizona, Colorado and Florida
next month.
   Arizona's Proposition 106, if approved, would change the state
constitution to designate English as the state's official language
and limit government use of foreign languages in courts, meetings
and schools.
   Ms. Chavez said at least one major contributor to U.S. English
helped reprint ``an awful, awful book'' called ``Camp of the
Saints,'' which she described as ``a paranoid fantasy'' about
``undesirables of the Third World'' taking over developed nations.
   She said she had been told that Tanton's activities with
immigration and population-control groups involved some who may
have given money to ``groups that may be involved in eugenics
research.''
   She said one person favored forced sterilization but she did not
elaborate.
   Tanton said he did not know who the people Chavez was talking
about.
   U.S. English gets most of its funds from U.S. Inc., a Michigan
corporation run by Tanton, Tanton's wife and two Michigan men.
Records show U.S. Inc. gets most of its funds from direct-mail
solicitation but do not identify the contributors.
   ``We have never had any sort of a litmus test when somebody has
wanted to contribute,'' Tanton said in an interview, adding that
U.S. Inc. had 168,000 donors this year and 379,000 since it was
founded.
   He said he would continue to head U.S. Inc. as an ``incubator
for new ideas,'' and that U.S. English had been given mailing lists
and would be able to operate independently.
   Supporters of Proposition 106 say it would unify the state and
help minorities join the mainstream more quickly. Critics say it
would disrupt the operation of civil courts, English-proficiency
classes, and tourism and commerce with other countries.
   U.S. English, through its campaign-finance arm, has contributed
$160,603, or about 97 percent of total contributions in support of
Prop 106, according to the latest available records.
   Bill Meek, a spokesman for the Arizona opponents of Prop 106,
said he viewed the Tanton resignation as ``largely cosmetic''
because Tanton retained control of U.S. Inc. and because he was
being replaced as chairman of U.S. English by board member Stanley
Diamond of San Francisco, ``one of his strongest supporters.''
   U.S. English was founded in 1983 by Tanton and former Sen. S.I.
Hayakawa, R-Calif.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881018-0060 </DOCNO>
