<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     10-18 0502</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0515</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms Race Through Ohio Valley and Great Lakes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Storms swept into the Ohio Valley and Great Lakes today after
spawning a tornado that overturned a trailer in Indiana and
lightning that struck five people in Chicago and delayed hundreds
of flights at O'Hare International Airport.
   Thunderstorms developing ahead of a cold front produced severe
weather in Ohio, Indiana and Kentucky on Monday evening.
   In Indiana, a tornado touched down in Vermillion County,
overturning a trailer and injuring a husband and wife inside. The
tornado also blew down a barn.
   Thunderstorms on Monday produced golf-ball-sized hail at Colfax
and Le Roy, Ill. Elsewhere in Illinois, five people were struck by
lightning during a storm that delayed more than 200 flights at
Chicago's O'Hare and dumped more than 3 inches of rain. There were
no reports of serious injuries.
   But in San Francisco, beaches were crowded Monday during a
heatwave that pushed the mercury to 92 degrees for a second
record-breaking day.
   Early today, showers and thunderstorms extended from southern
Illinois and western Kentucky through the upper Ohio Valley and the
lower Great Lakes region into Ontario.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms moving
from eastern portions of the upper Great Lakes and lower Ohio
Valley across the northern and and central Appalachians to New
England; cloudy with rainshowers scattered over parts of the
Northwest; and cloudy to partly cloudy over the northern Plains and
upper Mississippi Valley.
   High temperatures were forecast in the 40s for the upper
Mississippi Valley and northern parts of the upper Great Lakes; the
50s for Maine and Washington state, from the northern Plains and
Nebraska across Iowa and northern Illinois to the Ohio Valley and
southern parts of the upper Great Lakes; the 80s from the southern
two-thirds of Texas across the Gulf Coast to Florida, southern
Georgia and the eastern Carolinas. Temperatures in the 80s were
also expected for the southern half of the southern Rockies and
much of Arizona and California; in the 90s over the desert
Southwest and California's inland valleys; in the 60s and 70s
elsewhere.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 26
degrees at Hibbing, Minn., to 79 at Phoenix.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 60 fair; Boston 55 drizzle; Buffalo 61 rain;
Charleston, S.C. 57 fair; Cincinnati 65 showery; Cleveland 64
showery; Detroit 61 cloudy; Miami 72 fair; New York 60 foggy;
Philadelphia 54 partly cloudy; Pittsburgh 67 showery; Portland,
Maine 54 drizzle; Washington 60 partly cloudy.
   _Central: Bismarck 34 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth 73 fair; Denver 49
partly cloudy; Des Moines 46 partly cloudy; Indianapolis 67 cloudy;
Kansas City 50 windy; Minneapolis-St. Paul 37 fair; Nashville 69
windy; New Orleans 68 foggy; St. Louis 60 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 58 fair; Anchorage 30 cloudy; Las Vegas 69
fair; Los Angeles 65 foggy; Phoenix 79 fair; Salt Lake City 54
partly cloudy; San Diego 65 partly cloudy; San Francisco 61 fair;
Seattle 46 foggy.
   _Canada: Montreal 61 partly cloudy; Toronto 59 rain.
