<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Firmer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose in calm European trading today.
Gold prices also firmed.
   Foreign currency dealers predicted the dollar would trade within
a tight range for the next several days.
   They said the market was unlikely to test the currency's lower
limits following reported remarks by Bank of Japan Governor Satoshi
Sumita. He was quoted in Tokyo as indicating central banks of major
industrial countries may carrry out concerted intervention to
support the dollar if it continued to decline sharply against the
yen.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends as Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 0.50 yen to close at 127.70 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted at 127.25 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Monday:
   _ 1.8138 West German marks, up from 1.8120
   _ 1.5335 Swiss francs, up from 1.5295
   _ 6.1890 French francs, up from 6.1790
   _ 2.0485 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0390
   _ 1,351.50 Italian lire, up from 1,348.50
   _ 1.2030 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2047
   In London, one British pound cost $1.7450, down from late
Monday's $1.7530.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $412.60 a troy ounce, up
from $412.25 bid late Monday. At midmorning today, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $413.05.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $412.50, up from $412.30 bid late
Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $1.99 to close at a bid $416.05.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $6.44 a troy
ounce, little changed from Monday's $6.43.
</TEXT>
