<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-88 0841EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-DrugMoney     10-18 0402</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drug Money,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Investigators Expect More Money Laundering Indictments</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal investigators are looking into the
affairs of 40 banks across the country and expect to turn up ``a
couple'' more that have engaged in money laundering for drug
dealers, Customs Commissioner William Von Raab said today.
   ``It's just amazing what happens when you turn over a rock as
big as this,'' Von Raab said on NBC-TV's ``Today'' show.
   ``We've got our agents in 40 banks around the country, as well
as this bank in Miami. There are British agents in London, French
agents in Paris, and there's just voluminous material, all of which
is more or less bearing out what we expected to find,'' he said.
   ``We expect to see a lot of indictments coming out of this,'' he
said.
   The indictment last week of a bank holding company has not
halted such money handling, Von Raab said. ``We're looking at as
much as $50 billion a year that is laundered overseas. So this
bank, at best, could have laundered only a hundredth of that.''
   ``We haven't put a stop to it yet,'' he said. But the indictment
of the Florida-based Bank of Credit and Commerce International is
``a very important part of a cure.''
   ``No doubt there are other banks like this,'' Von Raab went on.
``There is $50 billion that someone has to launder, one bank can't
do the job. As to whether there are other banks that know they're
doing this and are doing it intentionally, I really can't give you
that answer.
   ``We've got a lot of investigations; we'll probably turn up a
couple.''
   The charge in this case is that the bank knew what it was doing,
that it knew it was dealing with drug money and that it was
intentionally laundering the proceeds, he explained.
   Why would a bank do that, he was asked.
   ``Banks want the money,'' he observed.
   Altogether, 85 defendants have been indicted in the
investigation. Indictments were returned in Tampa, Fla.; New York;
Chicago; Detroit; Philadelphia, and Houston. In addition, arrest
warrants were issued in Miami, Los Angeles, London and Paris in the
case involving the laundering of money for the powerful Colombian
drug cartel.
   Money laundering is the process of transferring money obtained
illegally between businesses or banks in order to obscure its
origin and to make it appear to have been earned in a legal manner.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
