<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Philippines-MacArthur     10-18 0328</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines-MacArthur,0343</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vandalized Statue Of MacArthur Reconstructed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALBERTO MARQUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PALO, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Laborers working round-the-clock today
finished piecing together a statue of Gen. Douglas MacArthur four
days after vandals blasted it with dynamite.
   World War II veterans have arrived in this coastal village on
Leyte island for a ceremony Thursday marking the day when the
American general led U.S. troops in liberating the Philippines from
Japan on Oct. 20, 1944.
   The Americans landed on Leyte, about 300 miles southeast of
Manila. The island is among the poorest in the Philippines, and
communist guerrillas have been active in the region for years.
   Police said today they believe the blast may have been the work
of vandals under the influence of alcohol or narcotics. But they
added that they were not ruling out communist rebels as suspects.
   Damage was so extensive that the reconstructed concrete figure
of the general has an disproportionately large left shoulder,
giving it the appearance of tipping over. The quick repair job also
eliminated the imperial air of the late American four-star general
depicted by the original sculpture.
   Workers reinforced the steel frame of the 10-foot statue to
minimize damage in case of a second attack.
   The statue shows MacArthur, flanked by Filipinos and American
soldiers, wading ashore on Leyte.
   ``I think (the vandalism was) immoral,'' said Alfredo
Mescallado, 75, a naturalized American of Filipino descent. ``Maybe
(the vandals) didn't know that MacArthur liberated the Philippines
... They don't know their history.''
   Mescallado, a doctor from New York City, served under MacArthur
during World War II.
   Sandy Valerio, 64, an Italian-born American from New York, said
communist New People's Army guerrillas may have attacked the statue
to protest the American military presence in the Philippines.
   ``I don't feel anything bad about (the blasting),'' Valerio
added. ``Everybody has his own ideology.''
   Dozens of former Japanese soldiers visited the site today, most
of them posing for photographs in front of MacArthur's statue.
</TEXT>
