<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Germany-Jews 2ndLd-Writethru a0528 10-18 0574</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Germany-Jews, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0528,0587</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bronfman Indicates East Germany Will Pay Reparations</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 12 grafs to UPDATE with additional Bronfman
quotes. Picks up 4th graf pvs `There was no...' Edits thereafter to
trim. </NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   World Jewish Congress President Edgar M. Bronfman
today indicated Communist East Germany will pay reparations to
Holocaust victims and their families.
   He also said he hoped for improved contacts between East Germany
and Israel. The two countries never have had diplomatic relations.
   ``I have been given the understanding that serious consideration
is being given to some renewal of relationship between the two
countries and I hope that will happen in the not-too-distant
future,'' Bronfman said.
   Before his meeting Tuesday with East German leader Erich
Honecker, Bronfman said he expected his three-day visit to East
Berlin would lead to a reparations agreement for Jewish victims.
East Germany had said it would provide unspecified humanitarian aid
to Holocaust victims.
   At a news conference in East Berlin at the end of his trip,
Bronfman declined to be specific on exactly what compensation he
expects.
   ``I have had very good, clear meetings here,'' Bronfman said.
   ``I am totally satisfied on two counts. The first is the one
that concerns me the most. That is the moral position that East
Germany is taking on its responsibilities on the Holocaust. The
second point is payment to the sufferers and survivors.''
   Bronfman also referred to an international claims conference
backed by the World Jewish Congress that has handled reparations
issues for Holocaust victims.
   ``I understand that the negotiations that took place between the
government and claims conference have been completed,'' he said.
``They will be lived up to and the details and communications will
be worked out and reported.''
   ``I am completely satisifed with the results,'' Bronfman added.
``I have nothing further to say on the payments question. It is not
my responsibility to discuss the details.''
   Toward the end of the news conference, a reporter called out a
question about West German Jewish leaders' statements that East
Germany would pay up to $100 million to Holocaust victims.
   ``The 100 million was not part of my mission,'' Bronfman
responded.
   There was no immediate statement on the reparations issue from
the official East German news agency ADN. The news agency has been
providing extensive coverage of Bronfman's visit.
   ADN said Monday the talks were ``open and constructive'' and
added that Honecker told Bronfman of East Germany's efforts to
educate its young people about the Holocaust.
   ``The struggle against racism and anti-Semitism belongs to the
anti-fascist tradition of East Germany,'' Honecker said Monday.
   ``We will never forget that many Jews, together with communists
and Social Democrats ... were active in the struggle against the
Nazi dictatorship,'' Honecker said, according to ADN.
   Bronfman has said that an admission of shared responsibility for
the Holocaust was as important as financial contributions to
victims, and that the money was a ``token thing.''
   ``What is at stake here is moral culpability,'' he said.
   More than 6 million Jews were killed during Adolf Hitler's Third
Reich. However, East Germany has argued that it bears no
reponsibility for Nazi atrocities because the nation was created
after World War II ended.
   In 1952, West Germany signed an agreement with the World Jewish
Congress to compensate Holocaust victims and families. Since then,
West Germany has paid more than $48 billion to Holocaust survivors.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
