<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BhopalLawsuit     10-18 0285</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bhopal Lawsuit,0292</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Dismisses $1 Billion Lawsuit In 1984 Bhopal Accident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEAUMONT, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state judge dismissed a lawsuit against
Union Carbide that sought $1 billion in damages for victims of the
1984 toxic gas leak in Bhopal, India, that killed more than 2,000
people.
   State District Judge Gary Sanderson's one-page ruling Monday
said only that it was his opinion that a motion to dismiss the
lawsuit should be granted. Sanderson had heard arguments to dismiss
the lawsuit from Union Carbide on Sept. 28.
   Houston attorney Benton Musslewhite, who filed the lawsuit in
1985 and later amended it to include almost 2,000 plaintiffs, said
he plans to appeal and he also will ask Sanderson for more detail
on his reasoning for rejecting the suit.
   ``The only place these poor people can get justice is in
Beaumont, Texas,'' Musslewhite said.
   The lawsuit claimed that a Texas statute allows lawsuits over
incidents that happened in foreign countries to be filed in state
district courts.
   Attorney John Bissell, who represented Union Carbide in the
case, had argued that the case clearly should be tried in India.
   ``The accident happened in India; it was an Indian subsidiary of
Union Carbide; all of the evidence is in India,'' he said.
   Several federal lawsuits involving the accident, which occurred
when a cloud of toxic gas escaped from the Union Carbide chemical
plant in Bhopal, have been consolidated and sent to an Indian
court. Others are pending in Connecticut, Union Carbide's home
state, Musslewhite said.
   Musslewhite said he filed the lawsuit in Beaumont because Texas
has statutes allowing for punitive damages in such cases and has
many potential jurors acquainted with the hazards of living near
chemical plants.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
