<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Court-AxMurders     10-18 0309</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Court-Ax Murders,0315</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Orders Youth Tried As Adult In Ax Murders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY R. SANDOK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Minnesota Court of Appeals today
ordered a youth to be tried as an adult on charges that he murdered
four members of his family with an ax last February when he was 16.
   The unanimous ruling by a three-judge panel reverses the
decision last spring of District Court Judge Gerard Ring, who said
David Brom should be tried as a juvenile.
   Brom, who turned 17 on Oct. 3, faces four counts of first-degree
murder for the slayings of his parents, Bernard and Paulette Brom,
both 41; sister Diane, 13; and brother Ricky, 11. The family
members were found slain in their home north of Rochester on Feb.
18. An older son who had moved out of the home earlier was not
there when the slayings occurred.
   Brom, a high school sophomore at the time of the slayings, has
been undergoing treatment at the Oaks Treatment Center in Austin,
Texas, a facility for severely disturbed children and adolescents.
Psychiatrists at hearings earlier this year described him as
severely depresssed.
   If he had been tried as a juvenile and convicted, he would be
released on his 19th birthday. If convicted in adult court, he
faces an automatic life sentence, with eligibility for parole after
17{ years.
   ``The brutal murders of these four family members has had a
major impact on society,'' the Appeals Court wrote. ``Retention of
the alleged murderer within the criminal justice system for less
than three years would constitute an excessively minimal response.''
   The Appeals Court disagreed with the trial court's contention
that the state had failed to show that Brom was not amenable to
treatment or that the public safety was not served by retaining him
in the juvenile court system.
</TEXT>
