<HEAD>Jackson Defends His Campaign Efforts for Dukakis</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson said today that Michael Dukakis has
the support of black voters and can beat Republican George Bush in
the Nov. 8 election if other Democrats work as hard for the ticket
as Jackson has.
   In an interview on ``CBS This Morning,'' Jackson disputed any
suggestion that he has not worked hard enough for Dukakis, the man
who beat him for the Democratic nomination at the party's Atlanta
convention in July.
   ``The fact is, since Atlanta I've traveled more miles, spoken to
more people and registered more voters for this ticket than any
Democrat has,'' Jackson said.
   ``What ought to happen now is that the other Democratic team
that made commitments in Atlanta ought to pull their weight and
together we can win,'' he said.
   Jackson said he has campaigned more widely for the
Dukakis-Bentsen ticket than any governor or member of Congress. ``I
now appeal to other Democratic leaders in their congressional
sphere, in their state sphere, to match that record,'' he said.
``We can win this campaign.''
   In the campaign in general, he said, ``my concern is that we're
missing issues of substance.''
   When Dukakis proposed a national health care plan for the 37
million Americans who do not have medical insurance, ``that needs
more projecting,'' he said.
   When Bush attacks Dukakis over his membership in the American
Civil Liberties Union and on health insurance and civil rights
issues, Jackson said, ``we have both a challenge in Mr. Bush and an
opportunity in Mr. Dukakis.''
   As for black support, Jackson said Dukakis ``should be able to
count on blacks because our civil rights are threatened. ... He
should be able to count on a broad cross-section of American
people. In my judgment, he has earned it.''
