<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-88 1030EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-France-Allais     10-18 0472</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-France-Allais,0488</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Laureate Says Economics `A Way of Helping People'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Nobel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY DUNPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maurice Allais, described as the man who shaped
thinking about economics and the state in postwar France, said
today he had given up hoping he would win the Nobel Memorial Prize
for Economic Science.
   ``I've been mentioned so many times before I just didn't think I
would get it,'' Allais, 77, said at his apartment in the suburb of
St. Cloud.
   Colleagues said Allais, trained as an engineer, changed fields
to economics after a visit to the United States during the
Depression, when he saw factories idled and men out of work.
   ``My motivation when I was young was an idea of being able to
improve the conditions of life, to try to find a remedy to many of
the problems facing the world,'' Allais told a group of reporters.
``That's what led me into economics. I saw it as a way of helping
people.''
   Allais was working at his home when he received the news he had
won.
   ``It was completely unexpected. It was just mindboggling,'' he
said.
   The Royal Swedish Academy of Sciences, which awards the prize,
said Allais was chosen ``for his pioneering contributions to the
theory of markets and efficient utilization of resources.''
   Although little-known outside France, Allais was extremely
influential at home, where senior officials in key government
ministries and state-owned industries have enormous economic power.
   Jacques Levy, director of the Ecole Nationale des Mines _ from
which Allais officially retired nine years ago, while continuing
his research and writing _ said the new laureate had a decisive
effect on economic thinking for more than two decades.
   ``He was the mentor for everyone involved in the economy in
postwar France between 1945 and 1968, all the people who were in
charge of the biggest enterprises and of the state planning
apparatus,'' Levy said.
   Within the world of French economic thought after World War II _
in which leftists and rightists agreed the state should play a
major role in the economy _ Allais established a place for reliance
on market forces.
   He worked on ``a system of definition of prices which would
permit the economy to function at its best,'' Levy said.
   Allais's work provided ``a very strong base for those opposed to
government direction of the economy,'' said Jacques Lautman,
scientific director for human sciences at France's National Center
for Scientific Research.
   Allais said he hoped the Nobel Prize would allow him to continue
his work, even though he is past the official retirement age.
   ``I'm happy to have the Nobel Prize to show how absurd this
situation is,'' he said. ``It's amazing that politicians think it's
normal that they should not retire, while they think it's normal to
push scholars into retirement.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
