<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ScotusRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0421 10-18 0589</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0421,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court to Consider If Flag-Burning a Crime</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts graf 7, The Supreme Court agreed.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court will determine whether
states may make it a crime to burn the American flag as a symbolic
protest, with a potentially far-reaching ruling on freedom of
expression expected in 1989.
   The justices announced Monday that they will review a Texas
statute that bans desecration of the flag. The case involves a
demonstrator who was sentenced to prison for burning a flag in a
protest during the 1984 Republican National Convention in Dallas.
   The Texas branch of the American Civil Liberties Union urged the
justices not to review a ruling that permitted the flag burning.
The ACLU said state officials were trying to ``create a sense of
legal uncertainty'' where none exists.
   While flag-burning generally has not been a hot issue since the
days of Vietnam War protests, the case may attract considerable
attention because of the emphasis on patriotic values during the
current presidential campaign.
   Vice President George Bush, the Republican nominee, has attacked
his Democratic opponent, Gov. Michael Dukakis of Massachusetts, for
vetoing a law requiring teachers to lead the Pledge of Allegiance
in that state's public schools. Dukakis vetoed the bill after
receiving an advisory opinion from the Massachusetts Supreme Court
saying the measure was unconstitutional.
   In the Texas case, a state appeals court last April threw out
the flag-burning conviction of Gregory Lee Johnson, who had been
sentenced to one year in jail and fined $2,000.
   The Supreme Court agreed to consider reinstating Johnson's
conviction.
   Johnson was arrested on Aug. 22, 1984, while participating in a
demonstration against the Reagan administration and the Republicans.
   The protest culminated with a rally in front of Dallas City Hall
that included political chants and the flag burning.
   Johnson was convicted by a jury of violating a state law banning
the desecration of a veneraed object.
   The state appeals court said, ``The act for which (Johnson) was
convicted was clearly `speech' contemplated by the First
Amendment.''
   The state court said the Texas law against flag desecration is
too broad because it seeks to curb expression likely to cause
``serious offense.''
   Seriously offending someone is not the same as inciting to riot
_ an activity that permits restraints on free speech, the state
court said.
   It also rejected arguments by law enforcement officials that the
anti-desecration statute legitimately preserves the flag ``as a
symbol of unity.''
   ``Recognizing that the right to differ is the centerpiece of our
First Amendment freedoms, a government cannot mandate by fiat a
feeling of unity in its citizens,'' the state court said.
   In other action, the Supreme Court:
   _Agreed in a potentially important libel case to review a
$200,000 award won against an Ohio newspaper. The justices will
examine how closely appeals courts must scrutinize jury findings of
``actual malice'' when a public figure sues for libel.
   _Said it will hear a Reagan administration appeal aimed at
making it easier for the government to conduct tax-fraud
investigations. The court will use a California case involving the
Church of Scientology to settle a dispute over Internal Revenue
Service powers.
   _Let stand the espionage and theft convictions of former U.S.
intelligence analyst Samuel Loring Morison for giving secret
satellite photographs to a British magzine.
   _Agreed in a case from Ohio to decide whether states may give
larger retirement benefits to public employees based on the age
when they are forced to quit work.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
