<HEAD>Fire Forces French Tourists Off Soviet Cruise Ship</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout with passengers resuming cruise on second
ship, other details. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>VALLETTA, Malta (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 500 French passengers stranded
after fire disabled their Soviet liner have resumed their
Mediterranean cruise on another Soviet ship, the shipping agents
said today.
   The passengers boarded the Leonid Brezhnev, which set out for
the Greek island of Rhodes on Monday night, said a spokesman for
the agents, S. Mifsud and Sons Limited.
   The cruise ship Shota Rustaveli was about 50 miles off Malta
when a fire started in the auxiliary engine room Friday, the Soviet
news agency Tass said in a dispatch from Moscow. It said the blaze
was put out by the crew and there were no injuries.
   Representatives of the tour operating company, Trans Tours of
Paris, said in Valletta that passengers aboard the Shota Rustaveli
were roused at 5 a.m. and spent several hours on deck wearing life
jackets. The ship arrived in Malta Saturday, pulled by tugboats.
   Tass said the tourists were offered sightseeing trips around the
Mediterranean island while awaiting the arrival of the second
passenger liner.
   Tass said the crew of the Shota Rustaveli would repair the fire
damage and the ship would return to the Soviet Union.
</TEXT>
