<DOCNO> AP881018-0077 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-88 1044EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BarricadedNuns     10-18 0411</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Barricaded Nuns,0420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Five Nuns End Talks With Vatican Envoy, Vow To Continue Seclusion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MORRIS TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A priest who tried to negotiate an
end to the two-week standoff between five conservative nuns and
their reform-minded diocese has returned home with his mission
unfulfilled.
   One of the nuns, Sister John of the Cross, who has acted as a
spokeswoman for the group, said the nuns would not budge from their
Roman Catholic monastery, where they have locked themselves in the
infirmary, until they hear directly from the Vatican.
   ``We are all united here. There's no division among the five,''
she said in a telephone interview Monday from the Monastery of the
Most Blessed Virgin Mary of Mount Carmel, located about 30 miles
west of New York City.
   The Rev. Kevin Culligan, dispatched by the Vatican to try to
persuade the nuns and the Diocese of Paterson to resolve their
differences, returned home to Wisconsin on Monday night.
   The Carmelite friar said he will submit a report to Cardinal
Jerome Hamer, an official of the Congregation for Religious and
Secular Institutes, an arm of the Vatican.
   ``After receiving my report within the next several days, the
congregation in Rome will make whatever decisions it judges
appropriate,'' Culligan said in a statement.
   The nuns, members of the Order of Discalced Carmelites, oppose
what they say are efforts by the monastery's new prioress, Mother
Teresa Hewitt, to modernize the order with the introduction of
television, candy and newspapers. The order traditionally has
stressed prayer and seclusion.
   The prioress spoke briefly Monday evening to reporters, saying
the protesting nuns would not cooperate with Culligan's efforts
even though ``we are all very impressed at (his) fairness and
sensitivity in handling the situation.''
   The sisters, who received official dismissal warnings in June,
say they retreated to the infirmary fearing they would be evicted
for their dissident views. Four locked themselves in the infirmary
Oct. 4 and a fifth joined them a day later. Eight other nuns live
at the monastery.
   Paterson Diocese officials say the nuns had earlier agreed to
leave. They also say the dispute amounts to a lack of obedience by
the nuns and that they could be relieved of their vows.
   The group broke off talks with Culligan on Saturday when
Culligan refused to discuss whether Paterson Diocese officials were
working to oust the nuns, Sister John said. But two of the nuns met
with him again on Monday, she said.
</TEXT>
