<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-88 1104EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru a0441 10-18 0908</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0441,890</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Vows to Reverse Trade Deficit in Four Years</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede COLUMBUS</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 17 grafs new with Dukakis speech, other developments;
picks up pvs 6th graf bgng, ``I can;'' DELETES pvs grafs 11-19
bgng, The community meetings, to tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KALAMAZOO, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis, striving to
regain the initiative in the closing weeks of the presidential
campaign, pledged today that during his first four years as
president ``we'll turn that trade deficit back into a trade
surplus.''
   Dukakis reminded his audience at Western Michigan University
that Wednesday is the first anniversary of Oct. 19, 1987, stock
market crash.
   ``And remember why it happened?'' he asked. ``The trade deficit
had soared. Republican policies of borrow and spend and borrow and
spend had done the damage.
   ``Interest rates were going up to attract the foreign bankers we
needed to buy our massive federal debt and the speculative bubble
burst _ as it always does.''
   Campaigning in the industrial Midwest, Dukakis was fighting to
overcome the impression that Republican rival George Bush was
surging to an insurmountable lead and that their race was virtually
over.
   Dukakis and his top aides disputed a new national poll which
said Bush has a 17-point lead over the Massachusetts governor.
   Campaign chairman Paul Brountas called reporters' attention to
another poll published in the Boston Herald which showed Dukakis
trailing Bush by seven points.
   In his Kalamazoo speech, Dukakis stressed the differences he
perceived between the vice president and himself.
   ``George Bush wants to help the people who already have it
made,'' he said. ``I want to make every American a full shareholder
in the American dream....
   ``George Bush cares about the people on Easy Street. I care
about the people on Main Street. He's on their side. I'm on your
side.''
   The Democratic nominee said that in the year since the stock
market fell by 500 points, neither Bush nor the Reagan
administration had done anything to correct the underlying causes.
   ``We've got to end the Republican rainbow coalition of red ink
for our children, pink slips for our workers, greenmail for sharp
operators on Wall Street and golden parachutes for top corporate
executives,'' he said.
   Dukakis said that in its first four years, the Reagan
administration ``turned two generations of trade surpluses into the
world's largest trade deficit _ and cost our workers 5 million jobs.
   ``In the first four years of the Dukakis-Bentsen administration
we'll turn that trade deficit back into a trade surplus and reclaim
those jobs for American workers,'' he said.
   ``That's our goal _ to eliminate the trade deficit in four
years. It'll take hard work. We have to reduce the budget deficit.
We'll do it.''
   Monday night in Columbus, Ohio, Dukakis told a predominantly
black audience that the Democrats have just three weeks to 21 days
to ``mobilize our forces ... to reach out to our neighborhoods''
before the Nov. 8 election showdown.
   Earlier in the day, Dukakis learned of the new NBC News-Wall
Street Journal survey giving Bush a 17-point lead, and said ``this
business of polls is really having a terrible effect'' on the
campaign.
   ``I can only tell you that there are other polls that say very
different things about where we are and where the race is,'' the
Democratic nominee said.
   Conceding that he is the underdog, Dukakis was campaigning in
the industrial Midwest, telling voters that he would fight to
create new jobs and describing Bush as indifferent to the region's
problems.
   Dukakis said Bush ``sat on his hands while America's industrial
heartland has been fighting for its life.''
   With only 21 days left in the long presidential campaign,
Dukakis picked up the pace of his activity.
   He was in Ohio all day Monday, touring a plant on the edge of
Cleveland and then addressing workers; visiting a bowling alley in
Dayton and meeting with local residents to discuss their problems
with housing, education and drugs; then flying to Columbus for
another community meeting and then a speech at a rally.
   At rallies, he implored supporters to get out and do the
precinct work he hopes will result in an upset on Nov. 8.
   ``Those phone calls you make, the doors you knock on'' can make
the difference he told them.
   There was obvious concern among Dukakis and his aides that his
precinct workers will become discouraged by polls and by reports
that he is trimming his efforts to the bare minimum of states that
would provide the 270 electoral votes needed for election.
   Aides vehemently denied a report on Sunday that he was
concentrating on 18 states with 272 electoral votes.
   But long gone was the memory of those days when national polls
said Dukakis was 17 points ahead of Bush.
   The new NBC-Journal poll said 55 percent of the 1,378 likely
voters surveyed favored the Republican vice president and 38
percent backed Dukakis.
   The survey also said that 36 percent had a favorable opinion of
Dukakis, down from 50 percent a month ago, while 55 percent had a
favorable opinion of Bush, up from 50 percent.
   Bush's held a commanding lead among men, 64-30 percent, and a
slight edge among women, 48-44 percent.
   Dukakis said the poll numbers had ``absolutely no relationship
to anything that we have or other people have.''
   He said polling ``really drives the process to a degree ... and
everybody is doing them.''
</TEXT>
