<2ND_LINE>PM-Drug Helicopters,150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pentagon OKs Copter Sale to Colombia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon notified Congress today it had
approved the sale of three UH-60 Blackhawk helicopters to Colombia
for use by that South American nation in fighting drug trafficking.
   Assuming there are no congressional objections, the Defense
Department said it would sell the three copters along with support
equipment, spare parts and pilot training services for $26 million.
   ``The sale will enhance the ability of the government of
Colombia to interdict the flow of narcotics which make their way to
the United States,'' the Pentagon said.
   ``The primary use of these helicopters will be to transport
Colombian soldiers or police in air mobile operations against
narcotics traffickers and insurgent forces. These three Blackhawks,
in addition to five already in Colombia, will provide Colombia
security forces with a significant tactical capability.''
   The Pentagon said that the U.S. Army would be responsible for
overseeing the transaction and that the prime contractor would be
Sikorsky Aircraft of Stratford, Conn.
