<HEAD>Ohio Governor Asks Closing of Fernald Uranium Plant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN NOLAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Richard Celeste said today he is asking
President Reagan to shut down a federally owned uranium porcessing
plant until the government takes steps to ensure it no longer
threatens the environment with radioactive pollution.
   He said he is sending Reagan a letter today demanding that the
U.S. Department of Energy, which owns the plant, provide for an
independent evaluation of plant employees and area residents to
assess the impact of its operation on their health.
   Referring to testimony last week about problems at the plant,
Celeste said in the letter to Reagan that ``This admission of
deceit and mismanagement confirms and emphasizes what we have known
in Ohio for a long time: This facility is an environmental disaster
threatening the health and safety of thousands of Ohioans.''
   Appearing at an airport news conference, Celeste also demanded
that the Energy Department treat and stabilize radioactive thorium
to reduce the threat of fire that could spew the material into the
atmosphere, and begin a final cleanup of radioactive waste stored
in two deteroirating concrete silos.
   He also wants the department to start identifying the contents
of 200,000 containers of waste that has accumulated as a result of
what the governor said is the department's negligent management of
the 1,050-acre site about 18 miles northwest of here in Fernald.
   Celeste noted testimony Friday at a congressional committee
hearing in Washington, which he said made it clear that the Energy
Department has known of dangerous environmental problems at the
Feed Materials Production Center since the plant opened  they said
they are concerned about more than three decades of radioactive
emissions into the atmosphere around the plant, and into thade progress
at the plant
with a decade-long cleanup costing more than $500 million.
   The plant processes uranium for the nation's production of
nuclear weapons.
   Neighbors of the area around the plant fear that the plant
already has polluted their land, water and air.
   In Columbus, Democratic presidential nominee Michael Dukakis
today met with two families who live near the plant and heard their
concerns about the plant's safety.
