<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Haiti 1stLd-Writethru a0482 10-18 0479</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Haiti, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0482,0492</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Security Tight After Coup Attempt And Arrests Of Soldiers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to recast and add details of coup attempt.
Picks up 8th graf pvs, `The Tonton Macoutes...</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ Authorities foiled a military coup
attempt, but several soldiers were wounded, officials said.
   The government said Monday it averted the planned coup Sunday by
a group of army officers against Lt. Gen. Prosper Avril, who came
to power in a military takeover a month ago.
   Government spokesman Frantz Lubin said the plot against Avril
was led by Sgt. Patrick Frantz Bochard, who headed a government
lottery, and former Col. Samuel Jeremie, a convicted murderer who
had escaped from prison.
   Radio Soliel said ``several soldiers were wounded'' and 30 were
arrested in the attempted takeover.
   Lubin said some soldiers were arrested, but he gave no figure
and said he could not confirm the radio report indicating there
might have been shooting.
   ``Certain other officers have been discharged,'' Lubin said.
``They had maneuvered to stage a coup'' against Avril.
   He said he had no further information.
   Hubert de Roncery, a conservative politician, called Jeremie ``a
pillar'' of the Duvalier dictatorship and said there could be ``an
alliance in the works between the soldiers and the Tonton
Macoutes.''
   The Tonton Macoutes were tcceeded his father. The dictatorship
ended when the younger Duvalier fled to France in 1986 during
anti-government violence.
   Lt. Gen. Henri Namphy headed a three-man junta until general
elections in January. Namphy staged a coup in June, ousted
President Leslie Manigat and took power. A month ago, the
50-year-old Avril deposed Namphy and declared himself president.
   About 6,000 people demonstrated Monday near the National Palace
to protest a directive by the Roman Catholic Church that would
transfer the Rev. Jean-Bertrand Aristide out of Haiti.
   Among the causes of last month's coup was an attack on
Aristide's church in the capital. Men armed with guns, machetes and
clubs burst into the church during Mass, killing 12 people,
wounding 70 and setting the building on fire. Aristide was not
injured.
   The Haitian priest said Oct. 10 that he was told by his
superiors in Rome to leave Haiti and that they set Monday as the
deadline for his departure. He did not elaborate, but a friend said
Aristide had been told to report to a parish in Montreal.
   Another friend said Aristide was still in Haiti on Monday.
   Aristide is an advocate of liberation theology and has said the
church must take an active role against social justices. Some
church leaders have criticized Aristide for his stand.
   Catholic-run Radio Soleil said the situation was too
``explosive'' for Aristide to leave now and his transfer could
create more unrest.
</TEXT>
