<2ND_LINE>PM-Quayle, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0442,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle Sees `Future of America' Shaped By GOP Election Win</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede GAYLORD</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 8 grafs new with Quayle speech, other developments; picks
up pvs 4th graf bgng, While lambasting; DELETES last 8 grafs to
tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican vice presidential candidate
Dan Quayle said today that the Nov. 8 election will mark ``an
American turning point'' that only a George Bush administration can
navigate.
   ``Every one of these changes I have projected is going to
happen,'' said the Indiana senator. ``The question is not whether
they happen, but whether we will shape the world through them.''
   Quayle spoke at Eastern Illinois University as he embarked on a
day-long bus tour of downstate Illinois. He also crossed paths and
spoke briefly with GOP nominee Bush, who was headed for campaign
appearances in Missouri.
   Quayle aides said the two discussed foreign policy and
scheduling for a few months, and that Quayle expressed the hope
they could campaign together sometime.
   Demonstrators favoring and opposing Bush's youthful running mate
paraded noisily around the floor of the gymnasium where Quayle
spoke. The GOP forces cheered lustily when police officers formed a
line in front of anti-Quayle protesters.
   The day was described by campaign aides as full of ``controlled
spontaneity,'' with plans for folksy, colorful stops at farms and
schools as the bus caravan, nicknamed ``the Illini Express,'' made
its way toward Chicago on a cool and blustery fall day.
   Quayle was joined by Illinois Gov. James Thompson, who himself
was mentioned as a potential vice presidential running mate before
the GOP convention in New Orleans last August.
   Quayle toured Michigan all day Monday, telling audiences that
``us Midwesterners have to stick together'' against ``that man from
Massachusetts.''
   While lambasting Democrat Michael Dukakis, Quayle painted the
GOP ticket as a perfectly balanced one.
   ``With George Bush, you get experience,'' Quayle said. ``With me
you get the future, the future of America.''
   That was a theme he returned to throughout a day of campaigning
in increasingly soggy weather, and he expanded on it speaking with
reporters on his campaign plane.
   ``Hopefully, I have a few years left, I'm only 41,'' Quayle
said. ``That's something they (voters) will think about, but I
don't believe it will be a decisive factor. They vote for the top
of the ticket.''
   Most polls have shown the GOP ticket with a small but persistent
lead in the polls, and Quayle said Republicans need to guard
against overconfidence.
   ``We're not the least bit overconfident because there are still
three weeks left in this campaign,'' he said.
   Quayle wrapped up his campaign day Monday with outdoor events in
a steady and cold drizzle, and tried to turn that to his advantage.
   ``Dukakis, his favorite colors are gray and dark gray,'' Quayle
said. ``What we're having today is Dukakis weather.''
   Along the way, Quayle shrugged off a decision by the Teamsters
union to endorse Bush while at the same time pointedly declining to
back the Indiana senator.
   Quayle insisted the endorsement is ``good news for me'' because
the union is again backing a Republican.
   ``I hope that all the Teamsters, people who follow their
endorsement, rush out and vote,'' Quayle said. ``It's going to be
important to have their votes. The fact is, I'm delighted they
endorsed George Bush.''
   Other than hitting Dukakis, Quayle's focus of the day was
economics. He said Republicans have solved a series of pressing
economic woes, falling short only on budget deficits.
   ``We have, on every one of those issues, except for the budget
deficit, solved them in a very positive manner,'' Quayle said. ``We
will also meet the challenges of the budget deficit in the next
administration.''
</TEXT>
