<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MyersonTrial     10-18 0476</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Myerson Trial,0487</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cross-Examination Begins of Star Witness in Myerson Bribery Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONALD POWERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bess Myerson's lawyer hammered at the star
witness against the former Miss America, pointing out
inconsistencies in her testimony and getting her to admit that she
had received electroshock treatments that may have affected her
memory.
   The cross-examination of Sukhreet Gabel, the daughter of the
judge Miss Myerson is charged with trying to bribe, began gently
Monday with the defense lawyer drawing a picture of Ms. Gabel as a
brilliant college student.
   But the lawyer, Frederick Hafetz, soon had the witness visibly
shaken, and she did not disagree when he told her that electroshock
treatments ``made your memory selective, like a Swiss cheese with
holes in it.''
   Repeatedly, Hafetz gave the jury examples of discrepancies that
have appeared during the numerous times Ms. Gabel has given
testimony _ during an appearance before a grand jury, during
depositions to the prosecution and during the trial.
   Miss Myerson, 64, her boyfriend Carl ``Andy'' Capasso, 43, and
former state judge Hortense Gabel are charged with a bribery
conspiracy in which the younger Ms. Gabel was given a city job in
return for her mother's decision to slash Capasso's alimony and
child-support payments in a divorce case before her.
   Miss Myerson was the commissioner of the city's Department of
Cultural Affairs. Ms. Gabel was hired in 1983 as her $19,000-a-year
special assistant.
   At one point during Monday's cross-examination in Manhattan
federal court, Ms. Gabel said she could not remember what she had
told a reporter on Sunday or what she had testified during the
previous week.
   ``My memory for events that took place in 1983 is better than
for some events that took place yesterday,'' Ms. Gabel said,
looking around the courtroom nervously. Ms. Gabel said she always
testified to the ``best of my recollection.''
   Earlier Monday, under questioning by one of the prosecutors,
Assistant U.S. Attorney David Lawrence, Ms. Gabel testified that
during the time a grand jury was investigating the alleged dealings
in 1986, Miss Myerson ordered her to keep quiet.
   ``What Bess said to me was, `Listen, I'm worried. You know
Andy's been before a grand jury,''' she said.
   ``She said, `We've got to get our stories straight. The trouble
with you is you remember too much. You've got to learn to forget
more. I've forgotten more than you'll ever know,''' Ms. Gabel
testified.
   However, under cross-examination, Ms. Gabel admitted she was
uncertain of the year she had had that alleged conversation with
Miss Myerson and also said that she had a series of 15 electroshock
treatments, quite likely during one month in the spring of 1986.
   Ms. Gabel, who now takes antidepressant drugs, agreed with
Hafetz when he told the jury she had earlier testified that the
shock treatments adversely affected her memory.
</TEXT>
