<1ST_LINE>u a PM-PTL     10-18 0459</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-PTL,0472</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>Former Board Member Says Bakker Deserved Money</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By TRIP DuBARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former member of PTL's board of
directors said today that Jim Bakker deserved every bonus he
received while at the helm of the television ministry and religious
theme park.
   Evelyn Spencer, testifying in PTL's $52 million lawsuit against
Bakker, his wife, Tammy, and former top aide David Taggart, said
she and other board members consistently voted unanimously in favor
of bonuses for Bakker.
   ``If a bonus came up, I voted for it,'' said Ms. Spencer, pastor
of The House of Truth Church in Oakland, Calif.
   According to IRS figures presented in court today, Bakker
received $278,000 in salary in the fiscal year ending in May 1987,
plus $1,167,000 in bonuses.
   Under cross-examination, Ms. Spencer could not recall the
precise salary of Bakker while she was on the board from November
1985 to March 1987.
   Bakker was expected to testify later today. The trial began in
bankruptcy court in September and was adjourned for about a month
before resuming Monday before U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Rufus Reynolds.
   In his opening statement Monday, Bakker attorney Ryan Hovis told
the court the case against the Bakkers boiled down to allegations
they mismanaged the PTL television ministry, which went into
bankruptcy three months after Bakker resigned in March 1987 amid a
sex-and-money scandal.
   But Hovis said he would show that the Bakkers' salaries were
authorized by the ministry's board, the benefits they enjoyed
properly donated by the ministry, and the cash advances they were
given reimbursed.
   Salaries and benefits received by the PTL founders, he said,
were not only legal and properly approved but also earned.
   But because the ministry's records are now dispersed among other
legal actions, including bankruptcy court, Hovis said he may be
unable to provide precise documentation.
   ``A lot of the records are simply not available,'' he said.
   In a separate hearing Monday morning on PTL's bankruptcy case,
Reynolds said he wants to see how the proposed sale of the PTL
ministry shapes up before considering whether to liquidate the
troubled television ministry and its Heritage USA theme park near
Fort Mill.
   Reynolds postponed until Nov. 16 consideration of several
motions by creditors to move the ministry from Chapter 11
bankruptcy to Chapter 7. If those motions are granted, it would
mean Heritage USA and other ministry assets would be sold by an
immediate auction rather than by an arranged sale.
   The judge said at a hearing last month he would hear the motions
to convert to Chapter 7 if no buyer were found for Heritage USA.
Canadian businessman Stephen Mernick has since signed a contract
with PTL Trustee M.C. ``Red'' Benton to buy Heritage USA for $115
million.
</TEXT>
