<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--SAfrica-Pistol     10-18 0159</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--SAfrica-Pistol,0164</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First Locally Made Pistol Unveiled</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRETORIA, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A weapons manufacturer Tuesday
unveiled the first South African-made pistol, a result of the
government's campaign to negate the effects of an international
arms boycott.
   The 9mm pistol, called the Z88, was developed for the South
African police by a subsidiary of the state arms corporation.
   South Africa had been able to import pistols despite the arms
embargo implemented by the United Nations in 1977, but officials
said prices were excessive and delivery times often slow.
   Law and Order Minister Adriaan Vlok said the new pistol ``stood
head and shoulders above'' foreign-made models.
   Since the embargo was imposed, the weapons industry has
developed into South Africa's most lucrative manufacturing sector,
despite attempts by the United Nations to discourage members from
buying South African arms.
   Jane's Defense Weekly, the respected British military
publication, estimated that South Africa earned $900 million last
year exporting arms to 23 countries.
</TEXT>
