<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Food     10-18 0225</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Food,0233</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>English Cooks Spoil Parliamentary Broth, Politician Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The catering staff of Britain's House of Commons
should be sent to the French National Assembly and other European
capitals to become ``civilized'' about cooking, a lawmaker said
Tuesday.
   Teresa Gorman, a Conservative member of Parliament, said that
European parliamentary chefs should also be sent to London to
transform the ``grizzly'' cuisine in Parliament.
   ``They (English chefs) are serving up all this sausage and beans
and plum duff (a rich dessert) which is supposedly what we like,''
Mrs. Gorman said.
   ``But we get no option. There is a monopoly in the catering
service in the Commons and we should break it.''
   ``The only way to do that is to arrange an exchange scheme
whereby our entire catering staff go to Paris, Rome and then Bonn
with their catering teams coming to Westminster in rotation,'' she
said.
   ``The food we get at Westminster is pretty grizzly ... all these
steaming pots of horrible lumps of meat that have been in the
steamer for about 10 hours.''
   Mrs. Gorman said she believes French chefs ``would civilize''
the English chefs ``in the art of cooking.''
   ``Our catering staff should be shifted around Europe, preferably
not coming back,'' she said.
   ``They will start putting arsenic in my soup if I go on like
this,'' she added.
</TEXT>
