<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MissingCats 2ndLd-Writethru a0567 10-18 0399</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Missing Cats, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0567,0406</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mutilation Of Cats Leaves Neighborhood In Fear</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to CORRECT that Surrey Hills a
neighborhood of Oklahoma City, not a nearby community; and to
restore dropped time element in 3rd graf. Picks up 4th graf pvs,
`Police department...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CASEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The disappearances and mutilations of up to
30 cats have distressed residents in a city neighborhood, but
police suspect that ``crazy kids'' rather than a cult are
responsible.
   ``It really has bothered us,'' said Vicky Lusk. ``We don't want
children finding mutilated animals.''
   Twenty-five to 30 cats have disappeared since late spring, said
Mrs. Lusk, one of about 300 residents of the Surrey Hills
neighborhood who attended a special town meeting Monday night. ``My
cat has been missing since July and my sister has one missing.''
   Police department Capt. Bob Jones said 12 cat carcasses have
been found.
   Parts of dismembered cats appear to have been left in places
where they will be spotted easily, Mrs. Lusk said.
   Residents are ``finding parts of them on open land, in the park,
on the golf course,'' she said.
   ``It definitely is not a coyote or other animal ... the heads
have been cut off or they have been cut in half,'' she said.
``Somebody has been doing this.''
   Lynda Powell, director of Volunteers For Animal Welfare, said
she has received several calls from pet owners in Surrey Hills who
reported their cats missing. Her organization has posted a $500
reward for information leading to the arrest and conviction of
those responsible, she said.
   Oklahoma City Police Det. Bob Smart told the residents at the
meeting there was no evidence to link the disappearances and
dismemberings to any cult or to suggest that the culprits could
attack people.
   ``We haven't seen ... (or) heard of children being approached,''
Smart said.
   But Mrs. Lusk remained unconvinced.
   ``We can't prove any rituals are involved,'' she said.
``Everybody knows there are cults that do use cats. The parts of
the bodies have been placed in different ways. They weren't just
thrown out of a car.''
   Police spokesman Lt. Charles Owen said authorities ``didn't know
about it until about three this afternoon.''
   ``It happening in the warm months makes me think it's a bunch of
crazy kids going around doing some weird stuff,'' he said.
</TEXT>
