<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Rust     10-18 0236</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rust,0241</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>West German Pilot Wants to Come Back to Moscow For a Visit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mathias Rust, who landed his small plane on Red
Square last year, wants to return to Moscow, ``but this time with a
ticket,'' a Soviet official said Tuesday.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady Gerasimov made it clear,
however, that the West German will find the welcome in Moscow no
warmer than it was the first time around, when he was sentenced to
four years in prison for malicious hooliganism, violating
international flight rules and illegally entering the Soviet Union.
   Rust was freed in August by a special act of the Supreme Soviet,
the national legislature, and expelled to West Germany after more
than a year in prison. But Gerasimov noted the criminal case
remains, ``and he can expect some difficulties if he wants to come
back.''
   Rust was arrested on landing in Red Square and spent the next 14
months in Moscow's Lefortovo Prison. He was driven directly from
the prison to Sheremetyevo Airport when he was expelled.
   The young pilot evaded Soviet air defenses before buzzing the
Kremlin and landing on before a startled crowd on Red Square on May
28, 1987.
   The flight also prompted the Soviet Union to fire its defense
minister and the air defense chief, and to treat Rust as a criminal
rather than the peace advocate he claimed to be at his trial.
</TEXT>
