<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Liberia-Treason     10-18 0300</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Liberia-Treason,0310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ten Convicted of Treason in Liberia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONROVIA, Liberia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ten people, including a former
presidential candidate and a judge, have been sentenced to 10-year
prison terms after being convicted of plotting to overthrow and
kill President Samuel K. Doe.
   Judge George Tulay sentenced the defendants Monday after
rejecting their request for a retrial filed last week on the
grounds of jury tampering by government officials.
   The convicted included Gabriel Kpolleh, Liberia Unity Party's
presidential candidate in 1985, and Cpehas Mbandi, a former
associate judge.
   All the defendants said they would appeal against the sentences.
   A jury unanimously returned a verdict of guilty Oct. 7 after an
eight-week trial that featured 21 prosecution witnesses and 10
defense witnesses.
   The defendants were among 14 indicted by a grand jury in March
on charges of plotting to assassinate Doe and replace his
government with a People's Reorganization Council.
   The prosecution said four of the 14 could not be found. During
the trial, witnesses said one of them, Joseph Robert Kaipaye,
committed suicide by jumping out a window at the Executive Mansion,
Doe's official residence.
   Prosecution witnesses said the defendants met several times
since 1986 to discuss their plans and had a cache of arms,
including grenades, rifles and ammunitions to use in the takeover.
   Doe has been the target of several assassination plots and coup
attempts. An abortive Nov. 12, 1985 coup attempt, after elections
oppositions leaders said were rigged, resulted in more than 600
deaths.
   In July, Doe said a 12-man invading force led by his former
second in command, Maj.-Gen. Nicholas Podier Jr., was intercepted
at the border with Ivory Coast, Liberia's eastern neighbor.
   Podier and four companions died in a gunbattle with Liberian
security men. Two Americans have been charged with treason in the
Podier plot.
</TEXT>
