<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Reagan-Summit     10-18 0381</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Summit,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>No Fifth Superpower Summit, Fitzwater Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan's spokesman on Tuesday
dismissed speculation of a fifth superpower summit in the waning
days of the administration, saying the idea is ``completely ruled
out.''
   Spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the White House generally
hesitates to make flat statements about future plans, but in the
case of another summit, ``We have to say no possiblity.''
   No plans are under way for Reagan to meet with Soviet leader
Mikhail Gorbachev before the president quits office in mid-January,
Fitzwater said. ``Yes, I think it is completely ruled out,'' he
said in response to a reporter's question.
   The superpower leaders have held four summit since they first
met in Geneva, Switzerland, in November 1985. Other summits were
conducted in Iceland in October 1986, in Washington in December
1987 and in Moscow last May.
   In Washington, the two men signed a treaty eliminating their
countries' intermediate-range nuclear weapons.
   Fitzwater also said that comments made over the weekend by
Deputy CIA Director Robert M. Gates were ``totally consistent''
with the administration's views on what is happening inside the
Soviet Union.
   Gates, in speeches Friday and Saturday, gave a gloomy assessment
of current events in the Soviet Union, and said Moscow has stepped
up its spying activities against Americans since Gorbachev came to
power.
   He said Gorbachev's reforms have not brought about economic
improvements and, ``I would even say it is doubtful that Gorbachev
can rejuvenate the Soviet system.'' Moreover, the Soviet system is
threatened by ethnic disturbances, he said.
   While the administration might not agree with the CIA on every
point, Fitzwater said, Gates' comments ``quite correctly point out
the things that we need to be very concerned about in dealing with
the Soviet Union.''
   He said Reagan and Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci have pointed
out that the United States wants to see the Soviet Union reduce its
defense budget to underscore a commitment to world peace.
   ``We feel we do have better relations with the Soviet Union and
the president has good relations with Secretary General
Gorbachev,'' Fitzwater said.
   ``But the system is the same, the country is the same and the
threat is the same and we need to be quite aware of that,'' he said.
</TEXT>
