<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--ScaffoldingRescue     10-18 0166</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Scaffolding Rescue,0169</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Workers Rescued After Dangling from Scaffold</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two construction workers, left dangling 140 feet
above a Manhattan street when their scaffolding collapsed, were
rescued unharmed Tuesday after 45 minutes in midair, the Fire
Department said.
   The men were working on a building at the Columbia-Presbyterian
Medical Center when a motor on the scaffold gave out, dumping both
men from the platform on the 15th floor, said Fire Chief Michael
Loghran.
   ``When we arrived, the scaffold was hanging straight down and
the workers were about 140 feet above the ground,'' said Loghran.
The men were both suspended from safety ropes attached to the top
of the building, he said.
   Firefighters moved a construction shed to allow a 100-foot
rescue ladder in at the workers, Loghran said. Because the building
is on a slope, the 100-foot ladder was able to reach the men,
Loghran said.
   Firefighters loaded the men into the ladder bucket and brought
them down uninjured, said Loghran.
</TEXT>
