<1ST_LINE>r a AM-StrandedWhale     10-18 0209</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Stranded Whale,0213</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Whale Towing Delayed By Winds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAMPTON BAYS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Plagued by high winds in the
Shinnecock Inlet, officials on Tuesday postponed plans to tow a
stranded whale from Peconic Bay to the open ocean. They said they
may try Thursday.
   The adolescent minke whale wandered into Peconic Bay last week,
according to Sam Sadove, the director of the Okeanos research
foundation. He said the whale is emaciated from lack of food and
disoriented, but is behaving normally.
   Pat Logan, an administrative assistant at the foundation, said
winds in the inlet forced researchers to cancel the towing attempt
and will likely force a postponement until Thursday.
   When conditions improve, divers from the foundation will attach
a rope to the whale's tail and then put the animal in a harness and
remove the tail rope, according to Sadove.
   The whale will then be attached to two Coast Guard boats and
towed into the Atlantic.
   The whale was first discovered by boaters in Sag Harbor two
weeks ago, and then moved into shallow waters of peconic bay.
Sadove says the whale is 17 feet long and weighs five tons. This is
the first whale sighted in Peconic Bay, according to Okeanos's
records, which go back to 1880.
</TEXT>
