<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-88 1306EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CityEconomy     10-18 0286</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-City Economy,0294</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: City Economy Survived Crash</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For Release 6:30 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city's economy fared much better than
expected in the year after last October's stock market crash,
according to a report released Tuesday by state Comptroller Edward
V. Regan.
   ``While the securities industry clearly was hurt by the crash,
the impact has been far less severe than originally forecast,''
Regan said. ``Furthermore, the rest of the city's economy has been
little affected.''
   The report predicted that the city will gain 35,000 jobs this
year, despite post-crash predictions of job losses ranging from
10,000 to 47,000.
   The projected 1988 loss of 7,000 security industry jobs will be
more than offset by an increase of 30,000 service jobs, according
to the report. Even businesses closely tied to finance, such as law
and printing, have shrugged off the impact of the crash.
   The report listed these signs of economic vitality:
   _The city unemployment rate fell to 4.1 percent in the second
quarter of the year, the lowest since 1970.
   _The ``gross city product,'' a measure of economic output,
posted its strongest annual growth in 20 years: 3.4 percent for the
12 months ending with June.
   _Retail sales and tourism are up, and the welfare caseload is
down.
   But the report warns that the city faces problems. The
securities industry could lose an another 7,000 jobs next year, and
there also may be a slowdown in employment in the real estate and
banking industries.
   The report also noted that the 35,000-job increase for 1988 is
smaller than the figure for each of the four previous years, and
that many of those still employed in the security industry have
taken pay cuts.
</TEXT>
