<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0450 10-18 0889</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0450,870</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Says America Must Stand Tough Against Soviets</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede SKOKIE</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 13 grafs new with Bush speech; picks up pvs 4th graf
bgng, Bush later; DELETES last 2 grafs to tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FULTON, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush, speaking where
Winston Churchill gave his famed ``iron curtain'' speech 42 years
ago, declared today the barriers surrounding the Soviet bloc are
rusting but that America must still stand tough against the Soviet
Union.
   Bush invoked the British statesman's memory in remarks prepared
for delivery at Westminster College, where Churchill popularized
the phrase ``iron curtain'' in 1946 to describe the barrier of
self-imposed isolation and secrecy that enclosed the Soviet Union
and Eastern Europe after World War II.
   Noting his widening lead over Democratic rival Michael Dukakis
in pre-election polls, the Republican nominee said both Churchill
and former President Truman knew that ``no election was over until
it was really over.`
   ``There are undecided voters out there,'' Bush said. ``The race
is close in many states. No votes can be taken for granted, and I'm
not taking any votes for granted. I will continue to campaign as an
underdog.''
   Bush did not include any attack or mention of Dukakis in his
speech today, which quoted at length from Churchill's speech at
Fulton.
   ``The iron curtain still stretches from Stettin to Trieste. But
it's a rusting curtain,'' Bush said.
   The vice president said ``there is a new hope of change'' in
Eastern bloc countries, but it would be wrong to conclude that the
Soviets were deterred from aggression by their preoccupation with
economic troubles.
   ``The Soviets are restrained by their own troubles, But they are
also restrained by our strength, our ability to deter aggression,
the unity of the democracies,'' Bush said.
   He said U.S. military strength made possible the signing last
year of the treaty calling for destruction of all U.S. and Soviet
medium-range nuclear missiles.
   Bush said similar reductions aimed at balancing U.S. and Soviet
convention arms in Europe ``will be a high priority for me.''
   On Monday in Skokie, Ill., the vice president stumped for Jewish
votes in the heavily Jewish suburb of Chicago that was wrenched a
decade ago by a battle over a neo-Nazi march.
   Speaking in a driving rain at an outdoor memorial to Holocaust
victims, Bush said the Nazi slaughter of 6 million Jews in world
War II was ``an evil far more vast than any in human history.''
   But he said the memorial offers ``hope for the persistence of
Jewish dreams and for the promise of Jewish lives yet unlived.''
   Bush later had time to comment on his surge in the polls,
including a new NBC News-Wall Street Journal poll showing him ahead
of his Democratic opponent by 55 percent to 38 percent.
   ``We have three weeks to go from this very minute,'' he told a
rally at the College of Du Page in Glen Ellyn, Ill. ``And I am
running as if I were 10 points behind. I'm not going to let up.''
In Columbia, Mo., where he spent the night, Bush said: ``Run like
you're 17 points behind.''
   Today Bush was traveling to Westminster College in Fulton, Mo.,
for a foreign policy speech. Westminster College is where the late
British Prime Minister Winston Churchill introduced the phrase
``iron curtain'' to refer to the Soviet bloc countries in 1946.
   Continuing attacks on Dukakis as weak on foreign affairs and
defense, the Bush campaign was planning to air a new ad using
footage from a Dukakis campaign appearance that backfired on the
Democrat: his test ride in a tank.
   An ad that was released over the weekend suggested Bush would be
best able to deal with Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev. ``This
is no time to train somebody in how to meet with the Russians,''
the ad says.
   Bush spokeswoman Sheila Tate had no information on a Washington
Post report today that the campaign was tentatively planning to
spend more than $15 million of its $30 million-plus advertising
budget in three states. The three states are California, New Jersey
and Ohio, the Post said.
   While in Skokie, Bush did not mention the turmoil that occurred
10 years ago when a neo-Nazi group planned a march in the
community. The American Civil Liberties Union successfully fought
efforts by the community to block the march, but the white
supremacists decided to hold it in a Chicago park instead.
   The Bush campaign gave reporters no chance to get close enough
to Bush to ask him his views on that case or the ACLU involvement.
   Bush has been relentless in attacking Dukakis as a member of the
ACLU, a group Bush faults for far-left positions.
   Ms. Tate said that in a longer speech that was cut short because
of the rain, Bush had intended to mention the controversy, in which
he agreed with the Skokie government. But she said he had not
intended to mention the ACLU.
   In remarks pared down to just a few minutes, Bush said he was
``committed to the survival of Israel.''
   ``We must keep that strategic partnership, and then we must
maintain that deterrent that comes of military and diplomatic
resolve,'' he said.
   In his earlier defense speech, Bush pledged to reform the
Pentagon procurement system to cut waste.
</TEXT>
