<1ST_LINE>r w AM-JewishGroups     10-18 0455</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jewish Groups,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israeli-American Lobbying Group's Hard Line Comes Under Challenge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three prominent American Jewish groups are
charging that hard-line lobbying for Israel is out of step with
``the consensus of the organized Jewish community.''
   The attack on the American Israel Public Affairs Committee, an
influential Washington lobbying group, surfaced in a letter
published Tuesday by The New York Times and verified as accurate.
   A senior official of the committee told The Associated Press
``this whole episode is bound to confuse members of Congress.''
   The committee is the principal pro-Israel lobbying group in
Washington and concentrates its efforts on Congress.
   The attack came from leaders of the American Jewish Committee,
the American Jewish Congress and the Anti-Defamation League of
B'nai B'rith.
   They disagreed in the letter with AIPAC's opposition to a U.S.
missile sale to Kuwait, an oil-rich Arab country; the lobbying
group's attempt to force the closing of the Palestine Liberation
Organization's mission to the United Nations; and the committee's
campaign to deny a visa to PLO Chairman Yasser Arafat in the event
he tried to appear before the U.N. General Assembly.
   An AIPAC official who spoke on condition of anonymity from Los
Angeles, where the group was holding a board meeting Tuesday, said
``more consultation is always desirable'' among Jewish groups.
   He said leaders of the committee would meet in Washington with
the critics on Nov. 3.
   The Kuwaiti arms sale was modified but was not blocked by
Congress. A court in New York, agreeing with the State Department,
ruled the PLO office should stay open despite a congressional vote
to close it. So far, Arafat has not indicated he wanted to address
the United Nations.
   AIPAC is one of the most effective lobbying groups in Washington
and organizes support for House and Senate members it finds
friendly to Israel. The committee has nurtured U.S. arms sales to
Israel and the strategic cooperation agreement with the Jewish
state. At the same time, the committee has played a leading role in
persuading Congress to block or trim a number of arms sales to Arab
countries not at peace with Israel.
   The letter called for closer consultation with the American
Jewish Committee, the American Jewish Congress and the
Anti-Defamation League, which already are represented on AIPAC's
executive committee.
   The letter said in part: ``We believe such consultation and
coordination will help avoid situations in which AIPAC pursues
policies that are at variance with the consensus of the organized
Jewish community, as occurred most recently with respect to the
Kuwaiti arms deal and the PLO mission to the United Nations, and
threatens to occur again with respect to Arafat's possible
forthcoming visit to the United Nations.''
</TEXT>
