<HEAD>Former Governor Takes up San Francisco Residency</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Gov. Jerry Brown has rented an
apartment in the city's Pacific Heights neighborhood so he could be
eligible if he decides to run for chairman of California's
Democratic Party.
   ``I've been in touch with a number of people throught the state
who are encouraging me and who support my candidacy,'' Brown said
earlier this week. But the former governor said he thought it was
premature to formally announce his candidacy now.
   Under the rules of the state's Democratic Party, the
chairmanship switches from Southern California and Northern
California every four years. The current party chairman, Paul
Kelly, is a lawyer in Southern California. His two-year term
expires early in 1989.
   To be eligible to succeed Kelly, Brown had to change his voter's
registration from Southern California to Northern California. He
did that on Oct. 11, the last day to register before the Nov. 8
election.
   Brown was elected governor twice, in 1974 and 1978. In 1982, he
lost a Senate race to Republican Pete Wilson.
