<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-88 1323EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Court-Peyote     10-18 0377</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Court-Peyote,0388</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Peyote Use OK in Indian Ceremonies, Oregon High Court Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALEM, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The use of the hallucinogenic drug peyote in
Indian religious ceremonies is protected by the federal
constitution's guarantee of religious freedom, the state Supreme
Court ruled today.
   The decision involves two former Douglas County drug counselors
who were fired and denied jobless benefits for using peyote during
Native American Church religious ceremonies.
   In today's ruling, the high court expanded its 1986 decision in
which it said denying jobless benefits to the two men violated
their constitutional rights to freely practice their religion.
   The state had appealed the earlier ruling to the U.S. Supreme
Court, which sent it back to the state court for a definitive
ruling on whether peyote could be legally used in religious
ceremonies in Oregon under state criminal law.
   Peyote is a cactus that contains mescaline, a hallucinogenic
drug that's illegal in Oregon. Possession of the drug is a felony.
   Deputy Attorney General Bill Gary, in oral arguments before the
state Supreme Court earlier this year, said the state has
constitutional authority to impose a ban on all uses of peyote.
   Gary also argued that to permit religious use of that drug would
open the door to all kinds of religious drug exemptions to be
claimed in criminal trials.
   The Supreme Court, in today's decision, noted that Oregon laws
against the possession of controlled substances, including peyote,
``make no exception for the sacramental use of peyote.''
   At the same time, the court said that the ``outright prohibition
of good faith religious use of peyote by adult members of the
Native American Church would violate the First Amendment directly
and as interpreted by Congress.''
   The ruling involved Alfred Smith and Galen Black, who were fired
from their jobs with the Roseburg-based Douglas County Council on
Alcohol and Drug Abuse Prevention and Treatment for using peyote at
religious ceremonies.
   Smith and Black were denied unemployment benefits on grounds
that they lost their jobs because of misconduct. The council's
rules forbid the use of alcohol or illegal drugs.
   Sueanne Lovendahl, a Roseburg lawyer representing the two men,
argued that the use of peyote in the Indian church is tightly
controlled and that its use outside the church is a sacrilege.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881018-0109 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-88 1345EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GiantShrimp     10-18 0464</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Giant Shrimp,0475</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Giant Shrimp Found In Waters From S.C. To Florida</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUNSWICK, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scientists and shrimpers are closely
watching to see how some giant shrimp that escaped from a South
Carolina research facility will affect the native crop.
   The shrimp, scientifically called the Penaeus monodon but
carrying nicknames such as the giant tiger, have been found in
commercial nets from Georgetown, S.C., to St. Augustine, Fla.
   ``This will be very interesting to watch,'' said Dr. Sheldon
Dobkin, a professor of biological sciences at Florida Atlantic
University. ``But certainly it is not desirable for exotics to be
loosed on nature, even though this is a nice shrimp.''
   The exotic shrimp, native to the waters of Australia, India and
southeast Asia, weigh up to one-quarter pound each and reportedly
taste good. But some shrimpers are concerned that they might eat
native shrimp and carry contagious diseses.
   Leonard Crosby, a commercial shrimper who manages the Bryan
County Fisherman's Coop on the Georgia coast, said boats docking at
his facility have landed about 15 of the giant tigers since August.
   Crosby said he notified researchers with the University of
Georgia's Marine Extension Center in Brunswick because he wanted
more information about the alien shrimp.
   Officials of the Waddell Mariculture Center in Bluffton, S.C.,
from which the shrimp escaped, said the giant tigers were certified
disease-free by the Hawaiian hatchery that supplied them.
   Paul Christian, a biologist with the Marine Extension Center who
began documenting catches and doing research on the giant tigers in
August, said the imported shrimp are not as inclined to eat their
own kind as native white shrimp.
   Manager Steve Hopkins said the Waddell center imported more than
700,000 quarter-inch tiger shrimp this spring and used them to
stock three artificial ponds on the South Carolina coast, including
a pond at the Bluffton facility, where researchers conduct
mariculture experiments.
   Although the center and private mariculture operations have
successfully raised imported Pacific ocean shrimp in their ponds in
past years, this was the first year any of the giant tiger shrimp
were brought to the Atlantic coast, he said.
   At the Bluffton center, fine-mesh screens were installed in the
floodgates of dikes surrounding the pond to prevent the shrimp from
migrating to tidal waters, Hopkins said.
   ``But the shrimp apparently went around the screens,'' he said.
Hopkins said he has no idea how many of the 100,000 shrimp
initially stocked in the center's pond found their way to open
waters.
   Hopkins first realized that some of the giant shrimp had escaped
when a few showed up in a drainage canal leading from the pond to a
tidal waterway, he said.
   ``Then we got a call in late July from a shrimp boat captain who
said he had an odd-looking shrimp,'' Hopkins said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881018-0110 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-88 1345EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-ToxicInitiatives     10-18 0683</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Toxic Initiatives,0700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Voters in Washington State To Decide Rival Toxic Waste Measures</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HAL SPENCER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OLYMPIA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Environmentalists are dueling with
business and the Legislature in Washington state over rival ballot
measures that each side claims is the best way to clean up toxic
waste sites.
   Environmental groups back Initiative 97 which would give the
state Department of Ecology unilateral authority to order a site
cleaned up, impose stiff fines and pursue criminal sanctions
against polluters who balked.
   But rival ballot measure 97B, backed by the business community
and most state legislators, would allow polluters time to negotiate
a clean-up plan.
   Supporters say 97B's strength is it permits the state and
industry to clean up sites together, with industry bearing most of
the expense. If 97B passes, it will affirm a toxic waste cleanup
statute enacted a year ago.
   Initiative 97 would raise an estimated $63.4 million to $68
million through a seven-tenths of 1 percent tax on toxic
substances, including gasoline and other refined oil products.
   Measure 97B would raise an estimated $51 million to $56 million
by means of a eight-tenths of 1 percent tax on hazardous
substances. This tax also would apply to refined oil products, but
unlike Initiative 97, would exempt refined products exported to
other states.
   The bulk of revenues generated by either measure would go
towards pay overhead, administration and enforcement of the law,
state officials said.
   Backers of each measure, which will be on Nov. 8 ballots, claim
that theirs is tougher on polluters.
   ``The 97B proposal creates a set of bureaucratic hoops through
which liable persons can make DOE jump before it can get a site
cleaned up,'' said William Ryan, a Boston-based specialist on toxic
waste clean-up laws. ``No other state (with toxic waste clean-up
laws) has such a convoluted response as that of the 97B proposal.''
   But supporters of 97B argue that the law's cooperative approach
is its strength and the reason that, ultimately, it is tougher than
97.
   Sen. Mike Kreidler, D-Olympia, who helped draft the measure
before it became law at a special legislative session a year ago,
said 97B envisions that polluters themselves will pay more than 70
percent of negotiated clean-up costs, while only a small part of
the cost will come from the law's special tax on possessors of
hazardous substances.
   Initiative 97, meanwhile, would rely on a similar tax as its
primary source of clean-up funding, Kreidler contended, even though
expected revenues would not begin to cover the estimated $1 billion
to $2 billion needed to cleanse as many as 400 waste sites in the
state.
   Initiative 97, Kreidler said, assumes that the Department of
Ecology will ``use the (tax) fund for clean up, and then litigate
to recover the costs.'' He said litigation to recover the balance
would mean costly delays at best and possibly no money at the end.
   David Bricklin, a main spokesman for the Initiative 97 campaign
and president of the Washington Environmental Council, countered
that Initiative 97 ``also relies heavily on voluntary clean-ups. It
is just that ours has a significant stick attached to it to ensure
that responsible parties step forward to clean up the sites without
forcing the state to go to court.''
   Supporters of 97B, led by aerospace, oil and timber interests,
have raised $800,000 for their highly visible campaign featuring
billboards, mass mailings and TV advertising.
   Initiative 97 backers, meanwhile, have raised only $196,000, and
campaigners acknowledge that 97B's greater financial resources put
their initiative at a disadvantage.
   Despite the heated debate, some here believe that either measure
would leave the state with a sound toxic waste policy.
   ``We are not at a crossroads in state environmental policy,''
said Jeffrey Goltz, a Seattle lawyer and former head of the state
Ecology Division of the attorney general's office.
   ``What is left for voters to decide this November are relatively
minimal modifications of the approach the legislature already
adopted,'' he said. ``Either the initiative or the alternative
would establish a sound, pro-environment toxic waste policy for the
state, without undue burden on industry.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
