<1ST_LINE>r p AM-BRF--WestVirginiaPoll     10-18 0198</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--West Virginia Poll,180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Wipes Out Dukakis Lead in West Virginia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis' lead in West
Virginia has vanished as Vice President George Bush gains support
among young voters and Democrats, according to a poll released
Tuesday.
   Bush, the Republican nominee, had trailed Dukakis in the state
by 13 percentage points in a poll released the week of Labor Day.
   But the latest poll shows Bush with a 44 percent to 40 percent
lead over his Democratic rival, with 16 percent undecided. Bush's
lead falls within the 4 percent margin of error, meaning the race
could be even.
   Bush's lead is biggest _ 57 percent to 29 percent _ among voters
18 to 24 years old. Dukakis fares best among voters 45 to 54, where
he leads the Republican nominee 46 percent to 35 percent.
   Bush was supported by 27 percent of the self-identified
Democrats polled, up from 19 percent in the Labor Day poll.
   The West Virginia Poll was conducted for The Associated Press,
Charleston Daily Mail and WSAZ-TV by Ryan-Samples Research Inc.
Results are based on telephone interviews conducted Oct. 11-13 with
485 likely voters selected at random.
</TEXT>
