<HEAD>People In The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Jackson fans can get something to remember
the rock superstar by when he comes here in December, a jewelry
firm said Tuesday.
   Ginza Yamazaki will put 54,000 platinum, gold and silver
commemorative medallions on sale Oct. 31, a company spokesman said.
They cost $37 to $1,958.
   ``This is said to be Michael's last concert tour, so we wanted
to give fans who can't go to the concerts a chance to have a memory
of the tour,'' said Yoshio Yamamoto.
   Jackson's manager, Frank Dileo, said in Tokyo last month the
singer might retire from the concert circuit after his nine Tokyo
performances Dec. 9-26.
   Ginza Yamazaki, Japan's largest maker of gold jewelry, produced
500 one-ounce and 3,000 five-gram platinum medals, 500 one-ounce
gold medals, and 50,000 15-gram silver medals, Yamamoto said.
   They contain a profile of Jackson, his signature and the words
``Let's be friends.'' Yamamoto said the design was personally
approved by Jackson.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Amazing Kreskin, a nightclub performer
and mentalist, is promising to re-create the fictional War of the
Worlds during the 50th anniversary celebration in the location
named in Orson Welles' broadcast.
   Kreskin said Monday he is working out the details, but he
promised the re-creation will not stir up the kind of panic that
followed the original 1938 Mercury Theatre broadcast.
   ``I'm going to recreate the War of the Worlds and make it really
happen,'' Kreskin said. ``People will experience the War of the
Worlds as it was experienced years ago.''
   Kreskin said his performance would be Oct. 29 during a four-day
celebration of the broadcast's anniversary. A bronze relief will be
dedicated at Grover's Mill, the hamlet where Orson Welles' invading
Martians supposedly landed.
   Planned events for the weekend include panel discussions on such
subjects as Earthlings and travel to Mars, planetarium and laser
shows, and fireworks.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Queen Elizabeth paid homage to Spanish war
dead, addressed parliament and accepted the keys to the capital
Tuesday during a busy second day of her five-day visit to Spain,
the first ever by a reigning British monarch.
   The Queen told a joint session of parliament the two countries
would play important roles in the future development of Europe and
praised Spain for 10 years of democracy following nearly four
decades under the authoritarian regime of Gen. Francisco Franco.
   In her speech, which received a standing ovation, the Queen did
not mention the British colony of Gibraltar, the only major
political dispute between the two countries.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Developer Donald J. Trump is selling the St.
Moritz Hotel in Manhattan to Australian billionaire entrepreneur
Alan Bond, winner of the 1983 America's Cup sailing race and owner
of the world's fourth-largest brewery.
   Trump and a Bond representative said Monday the selling price
was $180 million. Trump said he bought the hotel on the south end
of Central Park for $31 million in 1985.
   Trump, whose net worth was estimated last week by Forbes
magazine at $1 billion, said the St. Moritz made him an average
yearly profit of $12.5 million.
   Sale of the 775-room elegant hotel comes on the heels of Trump's
agreement last week to buy the Eastern Air Shuttle for $365 million.
   But the developer said he was not selling property to raise cash.
   ``I don't want to have two hotels on the same block,'' he
explained. He bought the Plaza Hotel down the street from the St.
Moritz earlier this year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American actor-director Charlton Heston,
playwright Herman Wouk and an all-Chinese cast got a standing
ovation Tuesday night at the Chinese debut of Wouk's play ``The
Caine Mutiny Court Martial.''
   ``I am very, very happy tonight and very grateful,'' said a
beaming Heston, who used a translator and sign language to direct
the Chinese cast at the People's Art Theater of Beijing.
   Wouk added his thanks to ``the Chinese people who have taken my
work to their hearts.'' His Pulitzer-winning novel on which the
play was based recently was translated into Chinese.
   The play depticts the World War II court martial and acquittal
of a U.S. Navy officer, Stephen Maryk, who mutinied against his
tyrannical and mentally unstable commander, Captain Queeg. The
audience of more than 1,000 Chinese and foreigners frequently
interrupted with applause.
   The role of Queeg was played by one of China's leading actors,
Zhu Xu, who last played China's last emperor, Pu Yi, in a 28-year
television series. Heston played Queeg in more than 250
performances of the ``Caine Mutiny'' in the United States.
   Heston said the play will run in Beijing ``as long as people
will come to see it.''
</TEXT>
