<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-88 1407EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TV-Burke     10-18 0482</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-TV-Burke,0494</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CBS' News Chief Says Media and Public to Blame for Election
Coverage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coverage of the presidential election by sound
bite isn't serving the public, but what the news media is dishing
out appears to be what the public wants, new CBS News President
David Burke said Tuesday.
   Burke, appearing before television critics for the first time
since he moved over from ABC News in July, said he did not know how
to steer the public's attention, and thus the news media's, away
from glib quotes and flashy images and onto important issues.
   ``I sort of sense an unwanting to know among the public. I mean,
the public is buying the flag factories and Pledge of Allegiance
and card-carrying this and card-carrying that,'' said Burke.
   ``I suppose we haven't done our job well if we don't keep
beating on them that they shouldn't be paying attention to that,
they should be paying attention to other things.
   ``I fault us, I expect, for being members of this same public
and not being willing to put on the hair shirt and say, `Sit down,
we're going to talk to you about the federal deficit.'''
   Burke, 52, is the first outsider to head CBS News. He had been
at ABC News for 11 years and had served as executive vice president
since 1986. Before entering the news business, Burke worked in
Democratic politics, as secretary to former New York Gov. Hugh
Carey in the 1970s, and in the 1960s as administrative assistant to
U.S. Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass.
   Burke said he supported ``CBS Evening News'' anchor Dan Rather's
decision not to serve as a panelist on the second presidential
debate, calling the forum ``contrived.''
   ABC's Peter Jennings was a panelist on the first presidential
debate in September and NBC's Tom Brokaw was one of the questioners
for the vice presidential debate earlier this month.
   Burke said the League of Women Voters was right to withdraw its
sponsorship of the second presidential debate because of the
numerous restrictions insisted upon by each candidate.
   ``Those debates were a contrivance,'' Burke said. ``... He
(Rather) was uncomfortable with it, I was terribly uncomfortable
with it. ... I think it was the right decision, absolutely the
right decision.''
   As far as CBS News' regular programming, Burke indicated strong
devotion to ``CBS This Morning,'' the 11-month-old morning talk
show, and to ``48 Hours,'' a prime-time documentary series that
premiered last season.
   He hedged on the future of ``West 57th,'' the on-again,
off-again newsmagazine that has languished in a Saturday night time
period since last season. But the news division has no alternative
time period to suggest, and the network is not anxious to replace
it with more expensive entertainment programming, Burke said.
   ``It's not in stone,'' he said. ```48 Hours' is in stone. The
morning is in stone.''

</TEXT>
</DOC>
