<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>50 Reported Dead Or Missing In Flooding Caused By Hurricane Joan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Flooding caused by Hurricane Joan left
about 50 people dead or missing in a northern town in Colombia, an
official with the state of Bolivar said Tuesday.
   Water roared down three gullies in the town of Carmen de Bolivar
on Monday as the hurricane passed over northern Colombia, the
administrative assistant for the state government, Victor Leon
Mendoza, said in a broadcast interview.
   Carmen de Bolivar is 360 miles north of the capital of Bogota.
   ``Preliminary reports from the mayor's office indicate that
about 50 persons are dead or missing'' in the town, Leon Mendoza
told the Colombian radio chain RCN.
   The weather service said the storm buffeted northern Colombia
with heavy rain and winds of about 65 mph on Monday before heading
northwest into the Caribbean toward the island of San Andres and
the coast of Nicaragua and Honduras.
