<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ReptilesReturned     10-18 0283</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reptiles Returned,0290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rustled Reptiles Return to Roost</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eight snakes snatched from their zoo cages were
returned unharmed in cloth sacks, but the reptile rustlers who kept
them over the weekend slid into hiding, police said.
   Juveniles were apparently keeping the two boa constrictors and
six pythons from the Dallas Zoo at a house in a Dallas suburb,
authorities said. But before police could follow up on a tip, the
snakenappers left the dwelling.
   Jim Murphy, a curator, said he was at the zoo Monday evening
when a father and son came into the office and said the boy had
something he wanted to return. The snakes, worth an estimated
$8,000, were in cloth sacks, he said.
   No arrests have been made in the case.
   ``We're just relieved they're back,'' said Murphy, referring to
the six pythons and two boas.
   Zoo director Warren Iliff said the snakes were taken from their
cages in a work area at the zoo between 5 p.m. Friday and 11 a.m.
Saturday. Workers found no signs of forced entry, and lids still
covered the snakes' cages, some of which were found latched.
   ``I don't know how they could have gotten them,'' Iliff said.
``We have to make sure it doesn't happen again.''
   Iliff said none of the snakes is poisonous, but whoever took
them would have needed some knowledge of reptiles to pull off the
heist.
   The snakes did not appear to have been abused or neglected,
Iliff and Murphy said.
   The theft of the boas especially worried zoo officials, said
spokeswoman Victoria Furber. The two snakes came from Madagascar
and are listed as an endangered species because their forest
habitat is being destroyed.
</TEXT>
