<1ST_LINE>r p AM-WestoverMayor     10-18 0301</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Westover Mayor,0310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>No New Mayor After 231 Votes</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Lottie in graf 8 is cq</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WESTOVER, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They cast 231 ballots trying to elect a
mayor, but the acting mayor and City Council finally gave up early
Tuesday and went home to bed.
   ``I think the people of Westover deserve better than what we're
providing,'' said Councilman Thomas Talerico before the five-member
City Council and Acting Mayor Mary C. Koon gave up trying to elect
a replacement for former Mayor Francis Teter Sr., who resigned last
month.
   The council and Koon adjourned their meeting early Tuesday after
failing to break a 3-3 deadlock between Koon and Donald Roderick, a
town Sewer Board member.
   Koon, 53, and Roderick, 57, were among eight applicants for the
job.
   During the nearly six-hour meeting, Koon and Talerico had a
showdown over Koon's right to vote for herself.
   State law says that ``no member of the governing body of any
municipality shall vote upon any ordinance, order, measure,
resolution or proposition, in which he may be interested other than
as a citizen of such municipality.''
   Citing the statute, Talerico said Koon should not be able to
vote because she would receive a hefty pay increase if elected
mayor. Koon is paid $1,500 annually as the town's recorder. The
town's mayor receives $10,000 annually.
   ``I contend that you, Lottie Koon, have an $8,500 interest in
who becomes mayor of Westover,'' said Talerico, who drew a chorus
of groans, hoots and catcalls with the statement.
   Koon said the Secretary of State ruled she had a right to vote.
Talerico argued that only the state attorney general could make
such a ruling. Koon countered that she had consulted with that
office, too.
   The council and Koon will try to break the deadlock next Monday
night.
</TEXT>
