<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-88 1434EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-WorldWeapons     10-18 0716</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-World Weapons,0738</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Predict Chemical Weapons Spread, Including Syria, Libya</HEAD>
<HEAD>Embargoed For Release 4 p.m. EDT _ Time Set By Source</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq's effective use of chemical weapons against
Iran is likely to encourage other countries to acquire them, and
Libya and Syria probably have already done so, according to a
report released Tuesday.
   The International Institute for Strategic Studies said Israel
and Egypt may also have secret arsenals of nerve agents and other
chemical weapons.
   In its annual survey, the London-based institute also said
Soviet conventional forces remain poised for swift attack, with no
sign of a winding down or switching to defensive positions despite
talk of change since Mikhail S. Gorbachev took office.
   In the past year, the numerical superiority of the Warsaw Pact's
conventional forces over those of the NATO alliance has, if
anything, increased, the survey said.
   But the institute said a raw count of weapons and manpower _
including a 2-1 Warsaw Pact advantage in main battle tanks _ was
too simplistic to judge which side really has the edge.
   The report refused to offer any overall judgment of the state of
the NATO-Warsaw Pact conventional balance.
   In long-range nuclear weapons, a six-percent increase by both
superpowers to some 14,600 American and 11,700 Soviet warheads left
them equally matched. ``Despite this numerical disparity, we judge
that equivalent strategic parity remains,'' said institute deputy
director Col. John Cross.
   The survey was gloomiest about chemical weapons.
   It said the Soviet Union could attack the entire NATO area with
chemical and biological weapons sprayed from aircraft or delivered
by missiles, free-fall bombs or artillery shells.
   It also indicated that Iraq's use of mustard gas and other nerve
agents likely served as an advertisement, particularly in Third
World countries, for the weapons, which have been condemned
internationally as inhuman.
   ``The role of chemical warfare in the Iran-Iraq war ... is more
likely to be seen as an encouragement to the future use of chemical
weapons in other regional conflicts, than as a discouragement,''
the survey said.
   Institute director Francois Heisbourg said unless an
international conference in Paris next year bolsters a 1925
protocol banning chemical weapons in any war, more countries will
acquire them.
   The protocol has been undermined by use of chemical weapons in
the Persian Gulf war and by Iraq using them against Kurdish rebels
this year.
   Attempts to get a global ban on such weapons are stalled.
   ``Unless the authority of the protocol is internationally
reaffirmed ... I suspect that other countries which theoretically
could produce chemical weapons will be tempted to do so,'' said
Heisbourg.
   ``Syria and Libya are strongly suspected,'' he added. ``Egypt
has used chemical weapons against North Yemen in 1966 so there is a
presumption there, while Israel is closing no options ... with the
perceived Syrian threat.''
   Only the United States and the Soviet Union acknowledge having
chemical weapons.
   But the institute said up to 20 more countries, including
France, were suspected of stockpiling or preparing to produce the
weapons.
   The Soviet Union says it has a 50,000-ton chemical weapon
stockpile _ one-sixth of the total estimated by Western analysts.
   The institute supported the United States' resumption last year
of production of binary weapons _ separate agents that are lethal
only when combined, saying that without a global ban ``deterrence
is the only policy for NATO to follow.''
   On Warsaw Pact-NATO conventional forces, the survey showed the
main disparity in battle tanks: 22,200 NATO tanks deployed from the
Atlantic to the Urals, facing 53,000 of the Warsaw Pact. Globally
NATO had 33,600 tanks and the Warsaw Pact 68,900, compared with
30,500 and 68,300 the previous year.
   Soviet conventional forces exceeded defense needs and were
``configured and deployed in a fashion which favors high-speed,
short-warning, offensive (or counteroffensive) operations.''
   Meanwhile, with only France, West Germany and Italy increasing
defense spending in Western Europe, NATO may be hard-pressed to
maintain its present forces, the survey said. ``Any significant
response to U.S. calls for increased European burden-sharing seems
unlikely,''
   The institute also said Argentina and Brazil may now be able to
make nuclear weapons. Four other officially non-nuclear powers _
India, Pakistan, South Africa and Israel _ have long been suspected
of having atomic weapons or being able to produce them.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
