<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-88 1436EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Teen-ageHero     10-18 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Teen-age Hero,0419</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>15-Year-old Rescues Blind Man From Burning Trailer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAND O' LAKES, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A blind, 75-year-old man says a
teen-ager saved his life by rushing into his burning mobile home
and pulling him to safety.
   ``I couldn't get out on my own,'' said Manuel Dennis. ``For one
thing, I'm blind and for another, there was too much heat.''
   Witnesses called the boy a hero, saying that only moments after
the pair escaped, the mobile home burst into flames and blew out
the windows.
   Gary Roy Lawrence, 15, said he doesn't understand all the fuss.
   ``I saw the smoke. I knew he was in there so I got him out. He
was yelling for help,'' said the youth.
   The high school junior, barefoot and shirtless, heard the man's
cries Saturday afternoon while he was walking through 41 Pines
Trailer Park. He saw smoke coming from the trailer where Dennis
lived alone.
   Lawrence said he went to the front door, found a fire
extinguisher and doused the flames in the living room. The
teen-ager could hear the man yelling, but couldn't see him because
of the thick smoke.
   He called for Dennis to come to him, but there was no response.
   Lawrence went to a rear door. It was locked. He punched out a
window, unlocked the door and went back into the trailer.
   ``I grabbed him by the arm and pulled him out,'' Lawrence said.
``He kept saying he wanted to get his shoes, but it was too far
gone to let him back in there.''
   The only injury reported was a minor cut to Lawrence's foot.
   Land O' Lakes Fire Chief Ross Wright said fire trucks arrived
just as the teen-ager came out of the trailer with Dennis. The
blaze was started by careless smoking, Wright said.
   The youth said he learned a little about firefighting from his
father and two of his uncles, all of whom have been volunteer
firefighters.
   ``He did what anybody with common sense would do. He went in
there and got the old boy out,'' said the teen-ager's proud uncle,
Ernest Pearl, a volunteer firefighter at Land O' Lakes.
   Dennis, resettled in another trailer, has another pair of shoes
the teen-ager gave him to replace those he lost in the fire.
   The elderly man is grateful to the youth. ``I knew him when he
was just a little kid; he's always around there somewhere. That
kid's OK.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881018-0127 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-88 1419EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-RIGovernor Bjt   10-18 0700</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-RI Governor, Bjt,0715</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ethics Charges Make R.I. Governor's Race Close</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Bruce G. Sundlun was reluctant
to take on Republican Gov. Edward D. DiPrete again after losing to
him in a landslide two years ago. But now a costly battle over
ethics has turned the race for governor in the nation's tiniest
state into a surprising cliffhanger.
   Sundlun, a multimillionaire communications executive who lost by
a 2-to-1 margin in 1986, has capitalized on news stories about
DiPrete family land deals, about DiPrete administration handling of
a major unfinished bridge project, and about state contracts for
trash hauling and engineering services awarded to DiPrete campaign
contributors.
   Sundlun, who said early private polls showed him as much as 50
points behind, has drawn even and surged ahead in some recent
surveys.
   A telephone survey of 400 likely voters conducted for local
radio and television stations after an Oct. 10 debate between
DiPrete and Sundlun showed the race too close to call, with Sundlun
receiving 40 percent support and DiPrete 38 percent, well within
the poll's 5 percent margin of error. A week earlier, Sundlun had
an 11 percentage point lead.
   ``What I've noticed is that neither candidate has made much of
an inroad into the 15 percent undecided,'' said Sundlun's campaign
manager, Kenneth Haupt. ``From what I've seen, the undecideds break
fairly heavily for the challenger. They want a change. ...
   ``I expect finally, the last week, people will start choosing
sides.''
   Sundlun's support, moreover, remains soft. One poll showed that
about two-thirds of those surveyed said they were voting more
against DiPrete than for Sundlun.
   DiPrete is striking back at Sundlun while trying to steer the
campaign focus to jobs, the economy and education, all areas where
he claims to have brought progress to Rhode Island.
   Sundlun said the state has prospered because of New England's
general economic boom. DiPrete responded that his administration
positioned the state to take advantage of that boom.
   The Nov. 8 election will be ``a referendum on the job I have
done during the past four years,'' DiPrete, who seeks his third
two-year term, said in closing Monday night's second debate between
the pair.
   DiPrete still is considering an offer of a third televised
debate. On Tuesday, he received the endorsement of American
Federation of State, County and Municipal Employees, which
represents about 9,000 state workers. The union cited his fairness
and accessibility.
   Sundlun's campaign has hammered at ``the $2 million Cranston
land deal.'' DiPrete, former mayor of Cranston, denied any
wrongdoing after Cranston officials rezoned a piece of property for
apartments and DiPrete's family firm then bought it and sold it the
same day for a $2 million profit.
   But DiPrete launched a television ad in late September, telling
viewers: ``I sense that some of you may believe that I've let you
down. If this is true, then I'm sorry.''
   DiPrete ads charge that Sundlun, chairman of Outlet
Communications Inc., mismanaged that company to a loss; ``ran
(Outlet Stores) into the ground'' before selling it to a company
that later closed the chain; and was involved in the Executive Jet
Aviation scandal of the 1970s that led to the downfall of the Penn
Central Railroad.
   Sundlun denies those charges. ``I have seen my reputation sought
to be destroyed in 30 seconds _ 30-second spots,'' he said.
   The barrage of ads and counter ads is costly. Recent campaign
finance reports show that in September, Sundlun spent $577,000,
incuding about $90,000 per week for televison and radio.
   Sundlun lent his campaign $495,000 during that period and has
provided most of the $1.4 million in loans outstanding, Haupt said.
The campaign had about $10,000 left, but Sundlun was prepared to
loan more, Haupt said.
   From July through mid-October, DiPrete's campaign reported
spending more than $1 million, including more than $100,000 per
week in television and radio ads beginning in September. Most of
his money came from individual and corporate contributions, along
with a $200,000 bank loan.
   Observers agree the race is one of the most expensive in memory
in this state, which has a population of just under 1 million and
is geographically the nation's smallest.
</TEXT>
