<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-Pauling     10-18 0295</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Pauling,0305</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nobel Prize Winner Cites Small-Town Beginnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CONDON, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nobel Prize-winning scientist Linus Pauling
traces his scholarly triumphs to his childhood years in Condon, a
small north-central Oregon community where his father ran a drug
store.
   ``I may very well owe a lot of my understanding of the nature of
the world to the introduction I received in Condon,'' Pauling, 87,
said at the dedication of an airport that bears his name.
   About 200 people huddled out of the wind in a hangar at newly
named Condon State Airport-Pauling Field on Saturday to hear
Pauling speak.
   The Gilliam County Historical Society presented Pauling with a
brick from the walkway in front of Herman Pauling's Red Cross Drug
Store. A red cross and nickel are imbedded in the brick.
   Pauling, who was 5 when his family moved to Condon from Portland
in 1906, said he remembered the brick, especially the nickel,
because, ``I could never get it out.''
   He reciprocated with a cut glass bowl saved from the drug store
by his sister in a 1908 fire. Historical society president June
Kamerrer said the bowl would be displayed in the society's museum.
   Pauling's father was a manufacturing pharmacist who prescribed
and mixed medicines and salves on a marble slab in his store.
   Fifty-six years ago, Pauling published ``The Nature of the
Chemical Bond,'' a book regarded today as a science classic.
   He won his first Nobel Prize in 1954 for chemistry, and won the
1962 Nobel Prize for peace for efforts to ban nuclear testing. His
nuclear test ban petition was signed by more than 9,000 scientists
in 44 countries.
   Condon's airport, originally built in the mid-1940s by local
businessmen, underwent a $1 million renovation, including a new
3,500-foot lighted runway.
</TEXT>
