<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Dukakis-Field     10-18 0477</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis-Field,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Hopes New Infusion Of Bodies Into Field Will Bolster
Effort</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis is trying to bolster his
organization in vital states by sending dozens of aides from his
national headquarters into the field and backing them up with more
than 1,300 new volunteers from Washington, aides said Tuesday.
   Jack Corrigan, director of operations for the Democratic
campaign, said about 60 percent of the workers at the Boston
headquarters are being assigned to target states for the final
three weeks of the campaign. He could not provide a specific number.
   Among the senior Dukakis aides assisting with the drive is
Marcia Hale, who since the Democratic National Convention in July
has been working on plans for a transition to a Dukakis presidency.
   Hale, a South Carolina native, has temporarily delegated her
transition duties to a deputy and now is focusing, from Boston, on
Southern states in which the Democrats believe they are still
competitive, principally Georgia and Louisiana.
   Joining the Boston operatives being assigned to field operations
will be more than 1,300 new volunteers from Washington, said Wendy
Sherman, who runs Dukakis' headquarters there. That group consists
of congressional aides who have taken leaves, numerous attorneys
with ties to Democratic politics and college students from area
campuses, Ms. Sherman said.
   ``It's a pretty encouraging sign, I think, about how strong we
are going to be in the field on Election Day,'' Corrigan said. ``We
have a very strong grass-roots organization. It got us through the
primaries and it is one of the things that is going to pull us
through on Election Day.''
   Volunteers, depending on their prior election experience, will
be assigned tasks ranging from political work in target precincts
to helping with phone banks and distributing leaflets, Ms. Sherman
said.
   Some of the congressional aides, most of whom have worked on
prior campaigns, are being sent back to their home states but many
also are being assigned to key states, she said.
   ``Our state party offices are quite capable of running a very
effective get-out-the-vote effort but you need bodies to do that,''
she said Tuesday in a telephone interview. ``This will give us the
influx of people we need to win on election night.''
   The congressional recess also will allow the Dukakis campaign to
schedule more appearances by members of Congress who have
volunteered to serve as surrogates for the Democratic ticket,
Corrigan said.
   Recent polls have shown Dukakis well behind Bush, but Ms.
Sherman said party officials calling her office to request more
volunteers have been relaying a far more optimistic picture.
   ``State party chairs will call and say, `I know I can win my
state but I'm worried about this state or another state,''' she
said. ``We're very encouraged by what we're seeing in the states.''
</TEXT>
