<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ScaldingDeath     10-18 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Scalding Death,0369</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prosecutor To Ask Grand Jury To Review Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. AUGUSTINE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A grand jury will be asked to review
the scalding death of a deaf 9-year-old girl at a state-run school
because a prosecutor said he's not convinced her death was
accidental.
   Jennifer Driggers died last Thursday from first- and
second-degree burns she suffered in a hot shower, according to a
preliminary report issued by Medical Examiner Robert McConnell. He
ruled the death an accident.
   However, Assistant State Attorney Steve Alexander has taken
testimony from three paramedics and subpoenaed medical records from
Flagler Hospital and the doctor who treated the girl.
   ``You can say accidental, accidental, accidental, but I've not
been convinced,'' Alexander said Monday.
   Officials of the Florida School for the Deaf and Blind said new
statements from witnesses show the girl slipped in the shower and
hit her head before being scalded to death.
   Jeanette Gadson, 29, the staff member supervising Jennifer, was
placed on leave with pay, school officials announced Monday.
   The girl's mother, Robin Driggers, said she doesn't believe her
daughter entered the shower on her own because she was terrified of
hot water and questioned why she didn't get out of the way of the
hot water.
   McConnell said there was no evidence that anyone else was
involved in the death, although Mrs. Driggers said she thinks her
daughter may have been held under the water.
   Earlier, school officials reported that the girl ran into the
shower after becoming ill in the bathroom. But on Monday Assistant
Principal Danny Hutto said it appeared the girl slipped and banged
her head when she was hit by the scalding water.
   McConnell said he found a bump on the back of the girl's head
while conducting the autopsy.
   ``The question still remains, why did she go into the shower,
and when the water hit her, why did she fall back rather than get
out of the water?'' Hutto said.
   Mrs. Driggers said the child had twice been previously injured
at the school. The girl was assaulted by a roommate last year and
fell in the shower at the school in November 1986.
</TEXT>
