<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-88 1538EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Unrest     10-18 0664</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Unrest,0683</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trial in Ethnic Rioting Begins in Moscow</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three Azerbaijanis went on trial Tuesday on murder
and arson charges in riots that killed 32 people and highlighted
ethnic tensions.
   The defendants were flown in from the Azerbaijani capital of
Baku and taken to the Soviet Supreme Court building in Moscow in
three unmarked gray trucks. About two dozen Armenians stood
silently outside the building holding copies of death certificates
for the victims, many of whom were their relatives.
   The group later was allowed into the courtroom.
   Azerbaijanis went on a rampage Feb. 28 in Sumgait, an industrial
city on the Caspian Sea about 20 miles north of Baku. They burned
and looted buildings, hunted down Armenians and killed them,
official and unofficial reports have said. Of the 32 victims, 26
were Armenians and six were Azerbaijanis, officials said. Official
reports had said more than 200 people were injured, but a Tass news
agency dispatch Tuesday gave a figure twice as high.
   Some Armenians say the death toll was much higher and have cited
Sumgait as a national tragedy they will never forget.
   Armenia's Communist Party chief, Suren Arutyunyan, said Oct. 8
that Sumgait was ``an unhealed wound in people's souls.''
   The rioting was sparked by a massive Armenian campaign for
control of the Nagorno-Karabakh district of Azerbaijan. In addition
to violence, the dispute over the mostly Armenian district has
triggered strikes in the southern republics of Azerbaijan and
neighboring Armenia.
   The two ethnic groups, of the Soviet Union's more than 100
nationalities, differ in culture and religion.
   Foreign reporters who waited outside the Supreme Court building
were not allowed to attend the trial. Court officials told the
reporters they need the permission of the Soviet Foreign Ministry,
but the spokesman for that agency, Gennady I. Gerasimov, said the
trial was not open to correspondents. Gerasimov did not say why
reporters were barred.
   A court official, speaking on condition of anonymity, identified
the defendants as ethnic Azerbaijanis and gave their names as Ahmed
I. Akhmedov, Ilgam A. Ismailov and Yavar G. Dzhafarov. The official
said each was accused of participating in the murder of one person.
   Tass said they were charged with ``organizing and and taking a
direct part in mass disorders accompanied by pogroms, acts of arson
and murders.''
   Tass quoted a court official as saying dozens of witnesses would
testify and that the indictment was more than 100 pages long.
   The death certificates held by Armenians bore pictures of the
victims and descriptions of how they were murdered. Many in the
group wore black and displayed buttons of Armenia's national flag.
   Moving the trial to Moscow represented a victory for Armenian
activists who had complained that previous legal cases stemming
from the rioting were biased because they were conducted by
Azerbaijanis on their territory.
   On July 8, the Soviet Supreme Court and prosecutor's office
shifted the cases to the Russian federation, an Armenian demand.
Tuesday's trial in Moscow, the capital of the federation, was the
first in an unknown number of cases the Supreme Court will hear in
the rioting.
   Before the change of venue, Azerbaijan's Supreme Court on May 15
convicted an Azerbaijani metalworker of pre-meditated murder in the
rioting and gave him the maximum sentence of 15 years in prison.
Officials have said more than 80 people have been charged in the
unrest.
   Twenty-five people already have been sentenced, Radio Moscow
reported Tuesday, but the official press has carried little on the
cases, and even Arutyunyan, the Armenian party first secretary,
complained.
   ``We see how the obviously delayed investigation reopened old
wounds, how people are shaken by the fact that the legal
examination is being conducted in various cities of the country and
that no information is coming into the republic about who was
punished, what the sentence was,'' Arutyunyan said Oct. 8.
   He said the most serious of the cases would be heard by the
Supreme Court in Moscow.
</TEXT>
