<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SoybeanOil     10-18 0336</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soybean Oil,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soybean Oil May Provide Claimed Benefits of Fish Oil</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Healthy people on a typical American diet may
have to look no further than their salad dressing for benefits that
some people are seeking from fish oil capsules, Agriculture
Department scientists said Tuesday.
   Chemist Edward A. Emken of the department's Agricultural
Research Service said the human body rapidly converts a part of the
soybean oil used in some ordinary food products into the same kinds
of fatty acids found in fish oil.
   Two men in a preliminary study consumed the soybean oil
component, linolenic acid, and within a few hours their bodies had
coverted it into the same omega-3 fatty acids found in fish and
marine oil, Emken said.
   ``Think of it this way: the body can naturally make its own fish
oil omega-3 fatty acids from the linolenic acid in soybean oil,''
he said in a report released by the USDA agency.
   The report said capsules of fish and marine oils have been
``touted by advertisers and debated by nutrionists'' as dietary
supplements. In any case, the capsules, it said, have become
popular with any consumers hoping to ease or prevent conditions
ranging from heart disease to rheumatoid arthritis.
   Emken led the study at the agency's Northern Regional Research
Center at Peoria, Ill., and was helped in the work by St. Francis
Medical Center in Peoria.
   ``Our study is the first to show that linolenic acid is rapidly
converted to omega-3 fatty acids found in marine oil,'' Emken said.
``The study also provides direction for further research to learn
which dietary fatty acids, including those in fish and soybeans,
best meet human nutritional needs.''
   Soybean oil is the only major domestic vegetable oil that
contains much linolenic acid and makes up 79 percent of the
vegetable fats in the average U.S. diet, the report said. The fats
are in such foods as shortening, margarine and cooking oil as well
as in salad dressing.
</TEXT>
