<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Iran-Military     10-18 0506</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Military,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Revolutionary Guards Predicted No Victories Over Iraq For Five
Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of the decisive factors in Iran's decision
to accept a cease-fire with Iraq was a prediction by the radical
Revolutionary Guards that they could not achieve any victory over
the Iraqis until 1993, according to a document released Tuesday.
   The Peoples' Mujahedeen of Iran, a group seeking to overthrow
the government of Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, released what it
said was a transcript of a July 17 meeting at which the decision to
adopt a cease-fire was announced to the senior Iranian leadership.
   The detailed transcript sheds light on the Iranian decision,
which has not been publicly explained and has led to much
speculation.
   The authenticity of the document could not be independently
verified, but previous documents released by the organization have
proved generally reliable.
   ``Now that our military officials ... openly admit that the Army
of Islam will not achieve any victories whatsoever in the near
future ... I accept the cease-fire,'' said Khomeini in a message to
the gathering read by his son Ahmad.
   The ailing leader did not take part in the eight-hour meeting,
which was attended by some 40 people including Parliament Speaker
Hashemi Rafsanjani, President Ali Khamenei, Prime Minister Hussein
Musavi and senior military officers.
   In his message, Khomeini cited specifically ``the shocking
letter of the Guards Corps commander'' Mahsen Rezaij, who sought to
continue the eight-year war.
   ``We won't have any victories in the next five years,'' Khomeini
reportedly quoted the commander as saying. ``After 1993, if we have
250 brigades, 2,500 tanks, 3,000 armored personnel carriers, 300
aircraft and 300 helicopters, we believe, God willing, we will be
able to launch offensives,'' the letter reportedly said.
   Diplomatic sources have said Iran, chronically short of money
and isolated by an international embargo, was suffering severe
shortages of combat aircraft, tanks, radar and other weapons.
   Khomeini also said his government's bank accounts ``are below
zero'' and ``the people have no desire to go the fronts ...''
   In his address to the Iranian people on July 20 announcing the
cease-fire, Khomeini did not explain his reasons for what he said
was a ``very bitter and tragic issue for everyone.''
   In a series of Iraqi offensives earlier this year, Iran lost
virtually all the territory it had captured in the eight-year war.
   Rafsanjani described to the participants several Iranian losses,
citing the battle on Majnoon Island in which he said Iranian forces
retreated without suffering any casualties, leaving 70 boats for
the enemy. He said supplies were so low that Iranian forces didn't
even have sandbags.
   Other officials spoke of confusion within the military, the
deterioration of the economy and an energy shortage. The transcript
also recorded a harsh exchange between Khomeini's son and Interior
Minister Ali Akbar Mohtashami, who criticized the cease-fire
decision.
   But Khomeini's son defended his father. ``One day he said war.
Now he says peace. Tomorrow once again he might advocate war.
There's no contradiction in this.''
</TEXT>
