<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Germany-Jews     10-18 0515</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Germany-Jews,0528</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Talks on Reparations Completed; No Details Released</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Nazi Asylum Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of the World Jewish Congress said
Tuesday the East Germans have agreed to accept moral responsibility
and pay reparations for the Nazi extermination of 6 million Jews,
but he would not give specifics.
   Edgar M. Bronfman also said he hoped for better relations
between East Germany and Israel, which have never recognized each
other diplomatically. ``I have been given the understanding that
serious consideration is being given to some renewal of
relationship,'' he said.
   Bronfman, 59, spoke to reporters at the end of a three-day visit
to East Germany that included meetings with Erich Honecker,
president and Communist Party chief; Foreign Minister Oskar
Fischer, and other officials.
   Before meeting Honecker, Bronfman said he expected a reparations
agreement. East Germany had said it would provide unspecified
``humanitarian aid'' to Holocaust victims.
   ``I have had very good, clear meetings here,'' Bronfman told the
news conference in East Berlin. ``I am totally satisfied on two
counts. The first is ... the moral position that East Germany is
taking on its responsibilities on the Holocaust. The second point
is payment to the sufferers and survivors.''
   He also referred to an international Claims Conference supported
by the World Jewish Conference, which in the past has handled
reparations issues for Holocaust victims.
   ``I understand that the negotiations that took place between the
(East German) government and the Claims Conference have been
completed,'' Bronfman said. ``They will be lived up to and the
details and communications will be worked out and reported.
   ``I am completely satisifed with the results. I have nothing
further to say on the payments question. It is not my
responsibility to discuss the details.''
   Bronfman was asked about a statement by Heinz Galinski, a West
German Jewish leader, that East Germany would pay up to $100
million, and replied: ``The $100 million was not part of my
mission.''
   East Germany has a chronic shortage of hard currency and has not
been expected to make substantial payments, but any offer of
reparations would be a major change from its previous policy.
   It has claimed since its founding in 1949 that it bears no
responsibility for Hitler's atrocities because it was created after
World War II, and has stressed that Communists also suffered under
Nazi persecution.
   West Germany has paid more than $48 billion to Holocaust victims
and their relatives since it signed a compensation agreement with
the World Jewish Congress in 1952.
   In recents months, East German official media have reported
government efforts to improve relations with practicing Jews in
East Germany, who number only 450-600.
   About East German pledges to renovate and maintain Jewish
synagogues and cemeteries, Bronfman said Tuesday: ``I'm very
satisfied with the symbolic arrangements.''
   The official East German news agency ADN covered the visit
extensively and reported Bronfman's remarks on the talks between
the Claims Conference and Honecker's government. A front-page story
in the Communist Party daily Neues Deutschland was accompanied by a
photograph of Bronfman and Honecker shaking hands.
</TEXT>
