<1ST_LINE>u i AM-UN-Korea Bjt   10-18 0569</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Korea, Bjt,0589</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Korea's President Calls For Summit With North</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY103</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Roh Tae-woo of South Korea
called Tuesday for a summit meeting with North Korean's president
to sign a non-aggression pact and said his country ``will never use
force first against the North.''
   In the first address by a Korean leader to the General Assembly,
Roh said such a summit should ``resolve all the problems raised by
either or both sides with regard to disarmament, arms control and
other military matters.''
   North Korea has said it only would accept a summit meeting after
42,000 U.S. troops pull out of the South.
   Roh also proposed the two Koreas meet with United States, the
Soviet Union, China and Japan to lay the groundwork for peace,
prosperity and security in Northeast Asia.
   Seoul's allies, including the United States, should ``contribute
to the progress and opening of North Korea by engaging Pyongyang in
expanding relations,'' the president told the 159-member world body.
   Roh also called for a Korean trade and cultural center on the
38th Parallel dividing North and South, where divided families
could visit in a ``city of peace.''
   Western diplomats hailed Roh's speech, which drew prolonged
applause, but there was no immediate comment from North Korea, the
Soviet Union or China.
   Ambassador Pak Gil Yon of North Korea was present in the
assembly chamber, but left without speaking to reporters.
   In Pyongyang, President Kim Il Sung accused South Korea and the
United States on Tuesday of ``maneuvering'' to perpetuate the
division of the Korean Peninsula, the official Korean Central News
Agency said.
   The agency, monitored in Tokyo, said Kim spoke at a banquet
several hours before Roh's U.N. speech. Kim again urged peace and
the removal of U.S. troops.
   Roh, in his speech, said improved relations and trust between
the two Koreas could ultimately lead to the reunification of the
peninsula, divided since World War II.
   ``Even before a non-aggression declaration is made with the
Northern side, the Republic of Korea will never use force first
against the North,'' Roh said.
   ``We must do everything possible to hasten the coming of the
springtime for peace and reconciliation on the Korean Peninsula,''
he said.
   U.S. Ambassador Vernon A. Walters, the permanent U.N.
representative, praised the speech as ``one of the most historic
and statesman-like speeches I have heard in this hall.''
   Japanese Ambassador Hideo Kagami said ``we hope very much that
today's speech will contribute to dialogue, reduction of tensions
and reconciliation.''
   On Wednesday, North Korea's deputy foreign minister, Kang Sok
Ju, will address the world body.
   The appearance of the South Korean president and North Korean
deputy foreign minister is the result of a compromise. The United
States, Japan, Canada and other nations proposed last summer that
South Korea should speak on the 40th anniversary of its 1948
founding.
   China, the Soviet Union and other socialist nations opposed the
idea, saying a speech to observe one national day only would fan
tensions since the Korean Peninsula was divided.
   It later was decided both sides would speak separately on the
question of reconciliation and dialogue.
   The two Koreas hold U.N. non-voting observer status because
their peninsula is divided and they still technically are at war.
The 1950-1953 Korean War ended in an armistice and no peace treaty
was signed.
   On Thursday, Roh meets President Reagan in Washington.
</TEXT>
