<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Southeast-Japan     10-18 0246</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Southeast-Japan,0255</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nearly 1,000 Expected For Southeast-Japan Conference</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The governors of seven states and about
1,000 business and government leaders from Japan and the Southeast
will meet here this week to talk about doing business with each
other.
   They are delegates to the joint annual meeting of the Southeast
United States-Japan Association and its Japanese counterpart, the
Japan-Southeast United States Association.
   The groups, which foster business investment and trade between
Japan and the Southeast, held their first meeting in 1976.
   They alternate their yearly sessions between Japan and the
United States. This is the first time they've met in South Carolina.
   ``Japanese interest is acute in the Southeastern United
States,'' said Curt Cottle, spokesman for the South Carolina
Development Board.
   ``A two-day meeting won't solve the trade imbalance,'' but it
has the advantage of giving leaders a chance to talk face-to-face,
he said.
   Alabama, Florida, Georgia, North Carolina, Tennessee and
Virginia are the other states represented in the association.
   While the states are usually in keen competition for industrial
investment, for the meeting ``we need regional cooperation to pull
it off. One state alone couldn't stage a conference like this,''
Cottle said.
   Cottle said there's been extensive Japanese investment in the
Atlanta area, but this year has brought some good news for South
Carolina, as well.
   Since the first of the year, Japanese investment in the state
has totaled more than $127 million, he said.
</TEXT>
