<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-88 1805EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Greece-Education     10-18 0190</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Greece-Education,0196</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students Take Over American College, Burn U.S. Flag</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist students occupied the downtown
campus building of an independent U.S.-affiliated college Tuesday
to protest private education.
   ``Education isn't for sale, it's for everyone!'' chanted the
more than 1,000 students, who also burned a U.S. flag from the
balcony of the building housing a department of Southeastern
College.
   ``No private university should be allowed to operate here ... we
must struggle to safeguard the public character of our education
system if we want to strengthen our studies,'' the protesters said
in a statement.
   All levels of education in Greece, including books and
accomodation are state-funded, although more than 100 private
primary and secondary schools also operate.
   Some independent higher education institutions also exist, but
degrees gained at private colleges are not recognized by the
socialist government.
   ``These people feel that private American education doesn't have
the right to exist in Greece because they complain that it creates
a kind of elite,'' said Achilles Kanellopoulos, dean of
Southeastern College.
   ``They're wrong as many of our students who cannot afford the
fees receive financial aid, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
