<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Reagan-Cambodia     10-18 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Cambodia,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Signs Call for Vietnamese Withdrawal From Cambodia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan on Tuesday signed with
reservations a House resolution calling for the withdrawal of
Vietnamese troops from Cambodia and establishment of a free and
independent government in that country.
   Reagan said he welcomed ``this clear statement of principles''
on Cambodia, but he disagreed with certain clauses which he feared
could complicate efforts to ensure that Khmer Rouge rebels never
again attain power.
   The House resolution stipulates that the Cambodian people be
protected from the return of a Khmer Rouge, who, under Pol Pot in
the late 1970s, are thought to have slaughtered as many as 2
million people.
   Reagan did not specify his reservations, but a White House
official said the president's main problem was language in the
resolution which didn't conform exactly to U.S. policy.
   The United States wants a withdrawal of Vietnamese troops in the
context of an ``overall settlement'' in Cambodia, said the
official, speaking on condition he not be named. The resolution did
not mention the overall settlement, he said.
   Reagan, however, said he signed the non-binding resolution
because it ``makes clear that the United States will continue to do
everything possible to assure that the Vietnamese occupation of
Cambodia is brought to an end and that effective guarantees are put
into place to prevent the Khmer Rouge from ever again taking
control of Cambodia.''
   Vietnam, which has installed a puppet government in Cambodia,
announced earlier this year that it would withdraw its 120,000
troops from the nearby country by 1990.
   The withdrawal, however, will leave a vaccuum. The United States
provides non-lethal assistance to two non-communist groups,
including one headed by Prince Norodom Sihanouk, the former chief
of state. Sihanouk met last week with Reagan.
   Pol Pot's Khmer Rouge receives support from China and Thailand.
</TEXT>
