<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FactorytoMuseum     10-18 0394</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Factory to Museum,0402</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Renowned Architects Win Competition To Turn Factory into Art
Museum</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORTH ADAMS, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Architects Robert Venturi and Frank
Gehry were picked Tuesday to design a plan to turn a 19th century
factory into the world's largest contemporary art museum.
   The two architects joined with two other firms _ Bruner-Cott &
Associates of Cambridge and Skidmore, Owings & Merrill of New York
_ in their submission for the renovation of the huge Sprague
Electric Co. plant into a museum to house major collections of 20th
century art.
   Their team was chosen by a panel of international art experts
and local businessmen and politicians after a two-day study of 23
proposals for revamping the factory.
   Joseph Thompson, the director of the museum's executive planning
group, said the architects were chosen because of their reputation.
Gehry designed the temporary building housing the Los Angeles
Museum of Contemporary Art, called the ``Temporary Contemporary,''
and Venturi is working on a wing to the National Gallery of Art in
London.
   Both men are known for their odd contemporary designs. Venturi,
for example, once designed a building painted in paisley swirls.
   Thompson, however, said the architects have ``a proven
reputation for sensitivity to the context of a project and have
shown sympathy for the industrial setting of the site itself.''
   The setting for the planned Massachusetts Museum of Contemporary
Art is a 28-building factory in an industrial city in the state's
remote northwest corner.
   Among the proposals submitted was a design from Coop Himmelblau
of Los Angeles for a giant contemporary sculpture of straps and
metal above the factory. Gae Aulenti of Milan, Italy, submitted an
inch-thick book of photographs of her projects, including the Gare
D'Orsay, a Paris museum created from a train station.
   Architect Resources of Cambridge suggested a glass tower and
Cesar Pelli & Associates of New Haven, Conn., proposed a large
contemporary tower in a courtyard to contrast with the factory's
clock tower.
   The winning team did not submit a specific design proposal.
Thompson said the team will begin working on design and engineering
prototypes, and cost and market analyses for a $1.7 million study
on the project's feasibility.
   The study will be turned over to the state Office of
Administration and Finance, which must approve it before releasing
$33 million in funds earmarked by the Legislature for the
renovation.
</TEXT>
