<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Iran-Iraq     10-18 0357</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Iraq,0366</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rafsanjani Says Iran Has New Weapon to Deter Iraq</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Iranian leader said Tuesday that the
Persian Gulf war could resume, but that Iran has a new mystery
weapon with which to deter Iraq from resuming attacks on cities.
   Tehran radio quoted Hashemi Rafsanjani, speaker of the Iranian
parliament and military commander-in-chief, as saying the
``probability exists'' that the 8-year-old war with Iraq could
break out again.
   He said Iran considers itself ``neither in a state of war nor a
state of peace,'' despite a U.N.-sponsored cease-fire that took
effect Aug. 20.
   Rafsanjani said Iran had acquired a ``device'' to deter Iraq,
but did not describe it.
   President Saddam Hussein of Iraq claimed on Sept. 27 that his
country had developed a weapon only two other countries possessed.
He did not elaborate, but said it was not a chemical device.
   Iran and Iraq each has sought in some degree to develop nuclear
capability. Israel bombed a French-built nuclear plant west of
Baghdad in 1981 to curb Iraq's potential.
   Western military analysts dismissed the possibility that
Rafsanjani was referring to a nuclear device. Some military
analysts consulted by The Associated Press said the Iranians may
have a new medium-range missile capable of hitting Iraqi cities.
   Most found it more likely that Rafsanjani was engaging in a game
of bluff with Iraq, which demonstrated during the last round of the
``war of the cities'' earlier this year that it had a greater
supply of effective missiles.
   The radio said Rafsanjani commented after a three-day tour of
Iran's devastated western region.
   It quoted him as saying: ``We must not forget that our enemy
might have the same motives of the past, although it will not
easily welcome the danger of resuming the war because of the
situation it has encountered. But the possibility exists.''
   Peace talks between Iran and Iraq stalled almost as soon as they
began in Geneva five days after the cease-fire date. Iraq insists
on sovereignty over the entire Shatt-al-Arab waterway, which forms
the southern border and is its only outlet to the sea.
</TEXT>
