<DOCNO> AP881018-0165 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-88 1939EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SchlesingerLibrary     10-18 0617</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Schlesinger Library,0634</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Women's Library Reopens After $3.4 Million Renovation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the years after it was founded in
1943, Radcliffe College's Arthur and Elizabeth Schlesinger Library
on the History of Women in America was a sleepy place with few
visitors, curators say.
   But with its official reopening Tuesday after a $3.5 million
renovation, the library is sleepy no longer. After its humble
beginnings in two small rooms in the basement of a building on the
Radcliffe campus, the library now occupies the entire structure.
   Because of the interest sparked in women's studies by the
feminist movement, the number of visiting researchers now numbers
about 5,000 per year.
   The library, the only one of its kind in the nation, collects
materials on women's roles and contributions from 1800 to the
present. It includes a collection so varied that one can study
aviatrix Amelia Earhart's papers, research the early women's
suffrage movement, peruse 5,000 cookbooks or review former first
lady Eleanor Roosevelt's ``Book of Common Sense Etiquette.''
   The red-brick building in Radcliffe Yard houses rooms for
visiting scholars, film and videotape viewing rooms for oral
history projects, photography exhibits, 500 women's
interest-periodicals, a planned wooden relief by sculptress Louise
Nevelson and the 5,000-volume Julia Child Study Area, named for the
famed chef.
   ``It's like a quantum jump in the recognition that real women's
issues and history are here to stay,'' said Eva Moseley, curator of
manuscripts, who has been at the library since 1971.
   Alongside oil portraits of Lydia Pinkham, who marketed a
well-known patent remedy for women's illnesses, and stained glass
artist Sarah Wyman Whitman, visitors can examine more than 30,000
books that concern women. On exhibit are memorabilia from the
women's suffrage movement: rattlers shaken by women in suffrage
parades, banners and placards reading ``Keep Cool! There Will Be
Nothing to Worry About After we Get VOTES FOR WOMEN!''
   Elizabeth Shenton, assistant to the library director, said the
library was almost a closet when she began work there 21 years ago.
   ``We were in two little rooms,'' she recalled. ``It was such an
event when one researcher came that we offered them tea. But the
women's movement increased interest in us so much. It just
ballooned.''
   The library was launched in 1943 as the Women's Rights
Collection using papers donated to the college from suffragist Maud
Park Wood, a member of Radcliffe's class of 1898.
   The collection opened to the public in 1949 with 300 books and
1,156 manuscripts. In 1965, the library was renamed to honor
Harvard history professor, Schlesinger, and his wife, who was a
historian of women and active in the League of Women Voters. Their
son, historian Arthur Jr., has said that his mother ``raised my
father's consciousness.''
   In later years, the library began to focus on the contributions
women have made to domestic life. An exhibit of etiquette books,
such as ``No Nice Girls Swear,'' is on display.
   One of the most unusual collections consists of cookbooks from
the 1800s to the present, stacked in shelves near a huge, blown-up
photograph of Child. Her papers are also part of the library.
   Gina DeAngelis, 25, a third-year student at Boston University
Law School, was at the library Tuesday researching women's unions
in the 1940s for a legal history class.
   ``This is the only library where I could find this material,''
she said.
   Museum staffer Nancy Falk said that for years women studying at
colleges in the area were unaware of the library's existence.
   ``All of sudden, though, women are a legitimate field of
study,'' she said.
   The renovation of the existing 1908 building was financed by
more than 3,500 gifts and grants.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881018-0166 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-88 1940EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SpacecraftDamage 2ndLd-Writethru a0673 10-18 0662</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Spacecraft Damage, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0673,0672</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Flash Fire Damages Magellan Venus Probe</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with fire caused by human
error; quotes; picks up 8th graf pvs, `Atlantis' astronauts...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HOWARD BENEDICT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Aerospace Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A technician who plugged a connector
into the wrong receptacle caused a flash electrical fire that did
minor damage to the $216 million Magellan Venus probe being readied
for a space shuttle launch next year, NASA reported Tuesday.
   Smoke and a 2-to-3-inch flame spurted from a spacecraft battery
when the worker tried to insert the cable connector into the wrong
slot Monday night, Magellan project official Vince Wirth said.
   ``Technicians on the scene quickly put out the fire within a
minute with a halon fire extinguisher,'' Wirth said. ``But by then
the damage was done. It resulted in a short that damaged the
battery and wire harness and insulation blankets near the battery.''
   He termed the damage minor and estimated it would take five to
seven days to get spacecraft preparation back on schedule. He said
there would be no impact on the April launch date aboard the
shuttle Atlantis.
   Wirth played a videotape made Tuesday that showed some soot
damage around the battery area. The battery, he explained, was
being used to run routine power system checks in the spacecraft's
forward equipment module and is not part of the flight hardware.
   He said the fire deposited ``some soot, grease and grime'' on
parts of the spacecraft and that it would have to be cleaned up. He
said Magellan, because of its planetary mission, has to be kept
extremely contamination-free and that cleaning experts were being
flown in from NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory in Pasadena, Calif.,
and from Martin Marietta in Denver, where the craft was built.
   Because an electrical short was involved, Wirth said engineers
were checking to make certain there was no damage to other
electrical components such as the spacecraft signal processor.
   In Washington, NASA administrator James C. Fletcher told
reporters, ``Apparently the wrong plug was put in the power supply
... I don't know whether you ever tried to put a multipronged plug
into a socket, but it's hard to do. It wouldn't fit, so he pushed
it a little bit and it shorted out the battery.
   ``We shouldn't allow this kind of stuff,'' Fletcher added.
``It's a human error ... we'll have an investigation and take some
steps so it won't happen in the future.''
   Wirth said the technician who made the mistake worked for Martin
Marietta, which delivered Magellan here on Oct. 8. The spacecraft
is being assembled and checked in a processing building. When fully
assembled, the craft will stand 21 feet tall and weigh 7,800 pounds.
   Wirth said because of the recent delivery, many electrical
components still had not been installed, reducing the possibility
of more damage, and several protective shipping covers were still
in place, cutting down on the spread of soot.
   Atlantis' astronaut crew is to release the spacecraft from the
cargo bay to start it on a 446-day trip to Venus. While Magellan
orbits the planet, its advanced radar will peer through the
constant clouds and map the surface.
   Before that mission, Atlantis has another flight assignment. It
is being readied here for a late November launch in which it is to
carry a classified Defense Department payload into orbit. A problem
with an actuator that controls the left wing flap has delayed for a
few days its transfer from a processing facility to an assembly
building where it will be joined with its two solid fuel booster
rockets and external fuel tank.
   A firm launch date will not be set until a flight readiness
review scheduled Nov. 9 and 10.
   The flight will be the second for the shuttle program since the
Challenger explosion in January 1986. Discovery completed a highly
successful mission on Oct. 3 and is now being groomed for a
February launch.
</TEXT>
