<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Swindall     10-18 0387</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Swindall,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Indicted Congressman Prepares Defense After Reagan's Birthday
Greetings</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-House Races-Scandal Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Pat Swindall worked Tuesday on his
defense for next week's trial on 10 federal counts of perjury, even
as he celebrated his 38th birthday with a letter of congratulations
from President Reagan.
   Swindall, a second-term Republican who represents a suburban
Atlanta district, was indicted Monday on charges of lying to a
federal grand jury that was hearing evidence gathered during a
nationwide money laundering ``sting'' operation by the Internal
Revenue Service.
   Reagan did not mention the indictment in his birthday letter to
Swindall, which read in part, ``May your special day be filled with
joy and may the year to come bring you every happiness.''
   Swindall, who was granted an expedited trial after saying he
wanted to clear his name before the Nov. 8 election, said he has
received calls from several attorneys offering their assistance but
still intends to act as his own lawyer during the trial.
   Reminded of the adage that an attorney who represents himself
has a fool for a client, Swindall replied, ``We'll find out the day
after the jury comes back.''
   During an hour-long interview with two reporters, Swindall
appeared upbeat and relaxed, frequently joking in response to
questions about criminal charges that could send him to jail if he
is convicted.
   Asked if he intended to call any members of Congress or the
Reagan administration as character witnesses, Swindall said he
might, then quipped, ``I think everybody already knows I'm a
character.''
   Sitting at a desk covered with cassette tapes and transcripts
from conversations recorded during the IRS operation, Swindall
acknowledged that he has not tried a criminal case in seven years.
In fact, he said, he has tried only four criminal cases in his
entire career as an attorney, and in all of those he was assisted
by another lawyer.
   Still, Swindall said he will be ready Monday when jury selection
begins and will base his case on ``the ol' innocent defense.''
   The perjury charges against Swindall stem from his grand jury
testimony about discussions he had last year with Atlanta
businessman Charles LeChasney and Michael Mullaney, an undercover
IRS agent posing as a money broker, about an $850,000 home
mortagage loan he was seeking.
</TEXT>
