<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Brazil     10-18 0330</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Brazil,0339</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Praises Democratic Trends in Latin America</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev on Tuesday welcomed
what he said was a trend toward democracy in Latin America and
cited a plebiscite in Chile as the latest example, Tass reported.
   The Soviet news agency said Gorbachev made the remarks in a
speech at a Kremlin dinner for President Jose Sarney of Brazil.
   ``Brazil's turn for democracy has been welcomed in the Soviet
Union,'' Tass quoted Gorbachev as saying. ``It has represented a
powerful factor in a general tendency typical of Latin America over
recent years.''
   Tass said Gorbachev then noted the Oct. 5 plebiscite in Chile
and said it was part of the trend toward democracy in Latin America.
   ``The decisive popular `no' to the dictatorship in Chile has
reflected it graphically,'' Gorbachev told Sarney, according to
Tass.
   In the Chilean plebiscite, more than 3.9 million people voted
against the proposal that President Augusto Pinochet remain in
power until 1997. The ``yes'' vote was 3.1 million. Gen. Pinochet,
the army commander, has ruled Chile with a military government
since leading a 1973 coup that overthrew the government of elected
President Salvador Allende, a Marxist.
   Sarney became Brazil's first civilian president in 1985 after 21
years of right-wing military rule. From 1964-85, Brazil shunned
high-level contacts with the Soviet Union but maintained trade and
diplomatic ties.
   Sarney, who arrived Monday for a three-day stay, is the first
Brazilian head of state to visit the Soviet Union.
   In his dinner speech, Gorbachev said Brazil and the Soviet Union
should work together to preserve their vast forests. He said that
maintaining the great wooded areas of Siberia in the Soviet Union
and the Amazon River basin in Brazil ``is our common duty both
before the people of our countries and before mankind.''
   The Soviet leader also called for increased economic and
cultural ties and joint work in space.
   In his speech, Sarney called for increasing political, trade and
cultural ties.
</TEXT>
