<1ST_LINE>r w AM-JerusalemPatriarch 1stLd-Writethru a0634 10-18 0570</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jerusalem Patriarch, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0634,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Catholic Patriarch Urges Dialogue With PLO</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 3rd graf pvs, bgng, `The president,'
and ADDS 2 grafs at end to add Nobel laureates' plea for
negotiations; NO pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Roman Catholic patriarch of Jerusalem
appealed to President Reagan on behalf of Palestinians in
Israeli-occupied territories Tuesday and told U.S. officials he
hoped for official recognition of the Palestine Liberation
Organization.
   Archbishop Michel Sabbah, the first Palestinian to hold the
Latin patriarch post, said he told Reagan at a 10-minute meeting
that ``the Jewish people are enjoying their human rights, the
Palestinians are not. Since 1967 they have been living under
Israeli military occupation.''
   The president said in response that he hopes for an end to
violence and peace in the area through negotiations, Sabbah told
reporters.
   Meanwhile, 17 past winners of Nobel prizes sent letters to the
leaders of Egypt, Israel, Jordan, Syria and the United States
urging negotiations to resolve the Israeli-Palestinian dispute.
   The letters said: ``Negotiations can lead to a settlement which
embraces renunciation of terrorism and aggression and the
protection of minorities within a self-governed Palestinian
homeland.''
   ``All parties must at long last realize that they cannot have
peace without compromise and that there will be no chance of peace
without negotiation,'' said the Nobel laureates' letters.
   Sabbah said he had earlier conveyed to Secretary of State George
Shultz the Palestinian people's hopes that the PLO eventually will
be accepted as their spokesman.
   ``I mentioned that our representatives are the PLO ... we hope
that some day the Palestinians will have their rights and their
representatives,'' he said. Sabbah said the brief meeting did not
allow him to broach the PLO topic with Reagan.
   The U.S. and Israeli governments reject dealings with the PLO
because of its terrorist activity.
   Sabbah, whose diocese includes Israel, Jordan and Cyprus, is on
a month-long pastoral visit to the United States.
   Emphasizing that he spoke as a clergyman rather than politician,
he said, ``There are two peoples living in the Holy Land, the
Jewish people and the Palestinian people ... Both have inalienable
human rights ... justice demands giving the Jews and the
Palestinians the same human rights ....''
   In parts of the Holy Land, torn by an 11-month Palestinian
uprising and clashes with Israeli soldiers, the patriarch said,
``The oppressed and suffering are the Palestinians, so I must speak
for them. Were the oppressed and suffering the Jewish people, I
would equally plead their cause ... as the Latin patriarch ... my
concern is not only for Catholics, but for all peoples, Christians,
Moslems and Jews.''
   Archbishop Sabbah, born in Nazareth, was named Latin patriarch
by Pope John Paul II and ordained by him in Rome last January.
Previously, he had served seven years as president of the Catholic
University of Bethlehem.
   The Nobel laureates who signed the letters included Christian B.
Anfinsen, biochemistry, 1972; Julius Axelrod, biochemistry, 1970;
Hans Bethe, physics, 1967; Konrad Bloch, physiology and medicine,
1964; Val L. Fitch, physics, 1980; Walter Gilbert, chemistry, 1980;
Sheldon Glashow, physics, 1979; and Robert W. Holley, medicine and
physiology, 1968.
   Also, Willis E. Lamb Jr., physics, 1955; Daniel Nathans,
biology, 1978; Marshall Nirenberg, biochemistry, 1968; Linus
Pauling, chemistry, 1954, and peace, 1962; Edward M. Purcell,
physics, 1952; Herbert A. Simon, economics, 1978; Henry Taube,
chemistry, 1983; James Tobin, economics, 1981; and Charles H.
Townes, physics, 1964.
</TEXT>
