<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Nancy-Wardrobe 1stLd-Writethru a0690 10-18 0684</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nancy-Wardrobe, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0690,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mrs. Reagan Broke Own Promise To Discontinue Accepting Gowns</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 2nd graf pvs, bgng: `Spokeswoman Elaine,' with 2 grafs
to CLARIFY that promise related to accepting clothing, sted
disclosure of such, and includes background on 1982 statements on
clothing; SUBS 7th graf pvs, bgng: `Questions about,' to include
language, background on ethics law. Picks up 8th graf, `Pressed to'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First lady Nancy Reagan ``broke her little
promise'' to stop accepting expensive designer gowns and jewelry
lent to her by leading couturiers, her press secretary said Tuesday.
   Spokeswoman Elaine Crispen said that when the practice came into
question in 1982, it was decided that Mrs. Reagan's transactions
would be reported on President Reagan's financial disclosure form.
She also acknowledged that the first lady vowed at the time to
discontinue accepting designer clothing.
   Sheila Tate, then-press secretary to Mrs. Reagan, told reporters
in February 1982 the first lady would stop accepting free clothing.
Her purpose was to help the fashion industry, but ``she felt it was
being misunderstood,'' Mrs. Tate said.
   ``Basically, she set her own little rule,'' Mrs. Crispin said
Tuesday. ``She made a promise not to do this again and she broke
her little promise because she just didn't feel she had to do it.''
   Meanwhile, the Office of Government Ethics reaffirmed its 1982
decision that such disclosures on Reagan's financial forms were not
technically required under the Ethics in Government Act.
   Deputy director Donald Campbell said: ``At this time, there is
no belief here in the office that the decision was not the correct
one.''
   But Campbell also said that officials would reassess the
situation ``if there's any indication of an error that we made.''
   The ethics law requires reporting by an official, or by the
official's spouse, of any loans in excess of $10,000 in any year.
   In 1984, then-Rep. George V. Hansen, R-Idaho, was convicted in
federal court of failing to disclose on his ethics form two loans
made to his wife by Texas millionaire Nelson Bunker Hunt. Hansen
served 11 months in prison.
   Questions about Mrs. Reagan's dealings with designers dominated
the White House news briefing for a second consecutive day.
   Pressed to discuss what implications Mrs. Reagan's
clothes-acquisition proclivities might have on the president's tax
forms and financial disclosure forms, spokesman Marlin Fitzwater
said: ``As far as we're concerned, there's no consequence ... for
the president's financial disclosure form or his tax forms, period.
   ``There is no legal problem. There is no ethical problem,'' he
said. ``There are all kinds of innuendo and insinuations of
illegality and improprieties that are totally incorrect.''
   In a May 4, 1982, letter, then-White House counsel Fred F.
Fielding told J. Jackson Walter, director of the Office of
Government Ethics:
   ``We have agreed that the practice of making the clothing and
other (personal property) available for the first lady's use does
not constitute a `gift' within the meaning of that term in the
Ethics in Government Act of 1978, and therefore it need not be
reported in the president's financial disclosure form.''
   Fielding went on to say that ``I advised, nonetheless, that
although there is no requirement to list these uses, nor manner in
which to evaluate them, the president's report should err on the
side of disclosure.''
   Walter initialed the letter with his approval and returned it to
Fielding.
   Mrs. Reagan has been borrowing expensive gowns and other
merchandise since 1982 without any disclosures, her spokeswoman had
acknowledged. But Mrs. Crispen said these clothes have been
returned.
   Mrs. Reagan's transactions during 1981 were reported
subsequently on a gifts attachment to the disclosure form the
president filed late in May 1982.
   Mrs. Crispen on Monday denied that Mrs. Reagan has kept any of
the expensive items, although she said the first lady ``regrets
that she failed to heed'' Fielding's advice to report the
transactions anyhow.
   At his news briefing Tuesday, Fitzwater was peppered with
questions. When asked what the president thought about the story,
he replied that Reagan considers it ``a cheap political shot
against the first lady.''
</TEXT>
