<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-88 2011EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-WarPowers     10-18 0450</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-War Powers,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Dismisses Lawmakers' Claim on War Powers Act in Persian Gulf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court dismissed a claim by
110 members of Congress that President Reagan should have invoked
the 1983 War Powers Resolution when Navy ships were sent to the
Persian Gulf last year, the court said Tuesday.
   A three-judge panel of the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in
Washington said the cease-fire in the Iran-Iraq war had rendered
the war-powers issue moot.
   The ruling was made by Circuit Judges Patricia Wald, Harry
Edwards and Stephen Williams in a brief order filed Monday and made
public Tuesday.
   The panel had been asked to review a lower court's dismissal
last year of the lawsuit on the ground that it presented a
political question upon which judges cannot rule.
   The appeals court, however, dismissed the case without deciding
that question.
   The issue in the case filed by Rep. Mike Lowry, D-Wash., and 109
colleagues was whether President Reagan should have notified
Congress within 48 hours of sending Navy ships to escort reflagged
Kuwaiti oil tankers in the Persian Gulf last year.
   The 1983 War Powers Resolution requires the president, in the
absence of a declaration of war, to notify Congress whenever U.S.
forces are sent into hostilities.
   The lawmakers claimed they were denied participation in the
warmaking process because Reagan did not submit notice. Under the
resolution, the president must withdraw forces within 60 days
absent a declaration or war or seek an extension from Congress.
   The members of Congress ``can claim no present injury as a
result of their reduced ability to participate in a process which
has been completed,'' the court said.
   ``Appellants' assertion of continuing injury is thus logically
dependent upon their ability to demonstrate that hostilities are
currently present or imminent. That demonstration cannot be made,''
the court said.
   One of the plaintiffs, Rep. Peter DeFazio, D-Ore., said the
court's decision ``was a disaster for the War Powers Resolution and
the Constitution.''
   ``Future presidents will have no hesitation (to ignore) the
clear requirements of this law. ... As of today, the War Powers
Resolution isn't worth the paper it was printed on,'' he said in a
statement.
   The court had asked both sides to file briefs on how the
cease-fire between Iran and Iraq affected the case.
   Lawmakers argued in their brief that U.S. forces still faced
imminent hostilities because the cease-fire between the two
countries is unstable.
   But the court said the court could not decide the merits of that
claim because it ``would require an inquiry into the likely
intentions of the Iranian and Iraqi governments'' that is ``beyond
the judicial competence.''
</TEXT>
