<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-88 2012EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Peyote     10-18 0357</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Peyote,0368</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Peyote Use OK in Indian Ceremonies, Court Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALEM, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The use of the hallucinogenic drug peyote in
American Indian religious ceremonies is protected by the First
Amendment of the U.S. Constitution, the state Supreme Court ruled
Tuesday.
   The ruling concerns two former Douglas County drug counselors
who were fired and denied jobless benefits for using the drug
during American Indian religious ceremonies.
   Peyote is a cactus that contains mescaline, an illegal
hallucinogenic drug. The drug long has been used in ceremonies of
the American Indian church, even though peyote possession is a
felony.
   Tuesday's ruling echoed the court's 1986 decision in which it
said denying jobless benefits to Alfred Smith and Galen Black
violated their constitutional rights to freely practice religion.
   Attorney Suanne Lovendahl said the ruling ``puts the Native
American Church on equal footing with majority religions in this
country.''
   ``This case shows our constitutional system does work and it
does protect people who are out of the mainstream,'' Lovendahl said.
   Deputy Attorney General Bill Gary said the state hasn't decided
whether to seek further court review of the case. However, Gary
expressed concern the ruling would set a precedent.
   ``Clearly, if some forms of drug use must be permitted under the
constitution because they are religiously motivated, (the courts)
are going to have to deal with other claims of religious
exemptions,'' he said.
   The case had earlier reached the U.S. Supreme Court, which sent
it back to the state court for a definitive ruling on whether
peyote could be legally used in religious ceremonies in Oregon.
   In arguments before the state Supreme Court earlier this year,
the attorney general's office said the state has constitutional
authority to impose a ban on all uses of peyote.
   The Supreme Court, in Tuesday's decision, noted that Oregon laws
against the possession of controlled substances, including peyote,
``make no exception for the sacramental use of peyote.''
   At the same time, the court said that the ``outright prohibition
of good faith religious use of peyote by adult members of the
Native American Church would violate the First Amendment directly
and as interpreted by Congress.''
</TEXT>
