<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-Fords     10-18 0344</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Fords,0356</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guardian Recommends Approval of Settlement in Ford Estate Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A retired judge appointed to look
after the financial interests of minor and unborn heirs to Henry
Ford II's estate has recommended approval of a proposed settlement.
   Retired Palm Beach County Circuit Judge Robert Hewitt, acting as
guardian ad litem for four minor grandchildren and unborn
grandchildren and great-grandchildren, said the proposed settlement
protects their financial interests. He recommended Circuit Judge
Vaughn Rudnick approve the settlement.
   Rudnick's ruling on the proposed settlement was delayed Sept. 26
when an attorney representing the grandchildren suggested
appointment of such a guardian.
   All attorneys involved were pleased with Hewitt's recommendation.
   ``I anticipated that he would approve it and I'm delighted that
he did,'' said Robert Montgomery, an attorney representing Kathleen
DuRoss Ford, third wife and widow of the automotive heir.
   ``The real benefit is that now the trust can get on with the
administration and not be bogged down in the sniping,'' said
attorney Arthur England, also representing Mrs. Ford.
   Rudnick's ruling, expected in the next few days, should settle
the widow's lawsuit challenging the administration of the trust.
   She and Edsel Ford II, Henry Ford's son by a previous marriage,
had disagreed over how the money should be invested, which attorney
would be counsel for the trust, and whether the trust should pay
family friend William Donaldson $1 million a year to manage the
money as a third trustee.
   Specific terms of the settlement have not been disclosed, but
Mrs. Ford's attorneys said she withdrew her objection to Donaldson.
Donaldson's payments under the settlement haven't been disclosed.
   Mrs. Ford is entitled to receive a minimum of $1.5 million a
year from the trust.
   Ford died at age 70 on Sept. 29, 1987, in Detroit. He filed his
will, which contained little information, in Palm Beach County,
which was his legal residence.
   The family hoped to avoid a public airing of their dispute, but
it erupted when Mrs. Ford objected to the selection of Donaldson, a
former undersecretary of state.
</TEXT>
