<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-88 2252EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-MacArthurStatue     10-18 0259</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-MacArthur Statue,0265</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Philippines Reconstructs Dynamited Statue Of MacArthur</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALO, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Filipinos hurriedly reconstructed a
dynamite-blasted statue of Gen. Douglas MacArthur and pronounced it
ready on Tuesday for an anniversary ceremony this week.
   The rebuilt concrete figure has MacArthur's left shoulder larger
than the right, making it look like it's about to tip over. Missing
is the imperial air given the late American four-star general by
the original sculpture.
   But this coastal village on Leyte island wanted to have the
10-foot-high statue back up in time for a ceremony Thursday marking
the day when MacArthur led U.S. troops in liberating the
Philippines from Japan on Oct. 20, 1944. World War II veterans
already have begun arriving here.
   Four days earlier, vandals blasted apart the statue, which shows
MacArthur, flanked by Filipinos and American soldiers, wading
ashore on Leyte.
   Police suspect despoilers under the influence of alcohol or
drugs may have been responsible, but do not rule out communist
rebels as suspects.
   Laborers reinforced the statue's steel frame to minimize damage
in case of a second attack.
   Dozens of former Japanese soldiers visited the site Tuesday,
about 300 miles southeast of Manila. Most of them posed for
photographs in front of MacArthur's statue.
   Among the Americans in Palo was Dr. Alfredo Mescallado, 75, of
New York City, a naturalized American of Filipino descent who
served as a physician under MacArthur during the war.
   ``I think (the vandalism was) immoral,'' said Mescallado.
``Maybe (the vandals) didn't know that MacArthur liberated the
Philippines ... They don't know their history.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
