<DOCNO> AP881018-0176 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-88 1834EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Senate     10-18 0708</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Senate,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Affirms Support For Contras, Passes Montana Wilderness Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate, warning that it might attempt to
renew military aid to Nicaraguan rebel forces at a future date,
voiced its moral support for the Contras on Tuesday and also
formally embraced Chile's movement toward democracy.
   The non-binding ``sense of the Senate'' proposals were attached
as amendments to an unrelated bill which designates 1.43 million
acres of Forest Service land in Montana as wilderness.
   Another amendment called upon U.S. allies to turn back efforts
of the Soviet Union to obtain millions of dollars worth of loans.
   The bill was approved by the Senate, but it faces an uncertain
future. It must still be approved by the House, and that chamber
may not finish work on it before the 100th Congress adjourns.
   The Contra amendment, endorsed on a 54-12 vote, supports
unspecified ``continuing efforts to strengthen the internal
democratic opposition and the independent media of Nicaragua.''
   It also calls for ``maintaining the Nicaraguan freedom fighters
as one of the few `pressure points' on the Sandinistas by providing
the resistance urgently needed humanitarian assistance.''
   The proposal was offered by Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., who said,
``we need to send a message, not only to the resistance in
Nicaragua, but to people throughout the world.''
   White House officials and GOP lawmakers have said prospects are
nil for obtaining a $16.5 million cache of weapons for the rebels
in the waning days of the 100th Congress.
   The dwindling Contra forces are subsisting on $27 million in
food, clothing and medical supplies approved by Congress last month
as part of a Pentagon money bill. They have received no weaponry
from the United States since February, when lethal aid was
suspended.
   The mood in Congress remains strongly opposed to sending new
military aid. But Congress has approved a complicated process
permitting President Reagan to request the release of the $16.5
million in weapons, if certain conditions were met.
   Reagan said last week he might call the Congress into special
session to vote for the aid, should the Sandinistas strike hard
against the Contra guerrillas before the new Congress convenes next
January.
   The plan approved Tuesday endorsed that view. It warns that
Nicaraguan failure to comply with Central American peace accords
``will inevitably cause the Congress to approve additional military
assistance for the Nicaraguan resistance.''
   Sen. William Armstrong, R-Wyo., complained about the amendment.
``Anybody can send a message ... What I think we ought to send is
military support. I don't think we ought to kid ourselves, this
resolution isn't much.''
   The Chilean proposal was sponsored by Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa,
and was added to the Contra measure on a voice vote.
   He noted the Oct. 5 vote to reject a new presidetial term for
Gen. Augusto Pinochet, the military leader who has ruled the nation
since a 1973 coup overthrew the socialist civilian president,
Salvador Allende.
   ``We've have a long night of despair in Chile, from the coup in
1973 to until this year,'' said Harkin. ``It's incumbent on us to
support the Chilean people, to support this election they had, to
say that we are going to work with them in this restoration of full
democracy.''
   Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., complained that the proposal was ``a
feel-good amendment'' and said Pinochet had saved Chile from going
communist.
   Sen. Steve Symms, R-Idaho sponsored the Soviet loan amendment,
which was approved 64-2.
   The Soviets are trying to secure loans of U.S. dollars through
third nations, Symms said. ``The Soviets are using the eagerness of
the western allies to play one nation off against another, to get
them to compete with each other for the opportunity to donate hard
currency to finance socialist economic failures and Soviet foreign
policy,'' he said.
   The wildneress bill affects more than 6 million acres of Montana
and is the result of a compromise worked out among competiting
interests, including conservationists and the timber and lumber
industries.
   The bill designates about 1.43 million acres of Forest Service
land as wilderness, 360,000 acres as special management areas, and
another 20,000 acres as federal study areas. It also releases for
non-wildnerness uses more than 10 million acres in Montana's 10
national forests.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
