<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-88 2258EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-GulfTalks     10-18 0467</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Gulf Talks,0484</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraq Offers POW Exchange `Unrelated' To Peace Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq has agreed to send home all Iranian
prisoners of war if Iran reciprocates, and an Iranian diplomat said
Tuesday he saw no reason why the exchange could not proceed.
   But Iraq said the POW exchange would be unrelated to other
issues in the U.N.-sponsored peace talks between the Persian Gulf
neighbors that went to war in September 1980.
   An Iraqi diplomat said his government's proposal would apply to
all prisoners of war if Iran accepts the plan.
   An Iranian envoy noted both nations had exchanged sick and
wounded POWs previously on a humanitarian basis, and said similar
repatriation could begin for the remaining prisoners.
   Both diplomats spoke on condition of anonymity.
   According to the Red Cross, which has sought the exchange, Iran
has 50,182 POWs and Iraq 19,284.
   But U.N. officials and Iraqi and Iranian diplomats place the
figures much higher, with many of the prisoners not registered.
They estimate Iran is holding from 60,000-70,000 POWs and Iraq
30,000-50,000.
   Ismat Kittani, Iraq's ambassador to the United Nations, said in
a letter given Monday to Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar
that Iraq is ready to begin the POW exchange.
   But he added: ``Since the exchange of prisoners is a
humanitarian matter ... our agreement on this step is unrelated to
the other issues referred to'' in the U.N. agenda for peace talks.
   Security Council Resolution 598 called for an immediate
cease-fire, withdrawal of troops to internationally recognized
boundries and an exchange of prisoners.
   If the exchange occurs, it could help end a deadlock in the
peace talks that have not gone beyond acceptance of the cease-fire
that began Aug. 20 and the opening of negotiations five days later.
   A senior U.N. official close to the discussions told The
Associated Press that although Iraq said the exchange would be
unrelated to the talks, the offer represented an advance in Iraq's
position.
   A major issue is the dispute over control of the Shatt-al-Arab
waterway that forms the southern border between the two countries.
   In Baghdad, Iraq, Deputy Foreign Minister Nizzar Hamdoun said
Iran was setting unacceptable conditions by insisting that both
countries follow a 1975 treaty that placed the border down the
middle of the Shatt-al-Arab.
   Iraq wants the border to be drawnl along the Iranian shorline
and has said the treaty is not valid.
   ``The Iranian position ... is an attempt to pressure Iraq to
relinquish its political and legal rights while the two sides are
discussing purely technical issues,'' Hamdoun said.
   Iran's foreign minister, Ali-Akbar Velayati, said Monday that
Iran agreed to a U.N. peace plan but with the condition that the
1975 treaty is upheld.
   Negotiations are to resume next week in Geneva.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
