<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Sweden-Spies     10-18 0185</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sweden-Spies,0188</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hungarian Brothers Given 18-month Sentences For Espionage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GOTEBORG, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Hungarian-born brothers were
sentenced Tuesday to 18 months in prison after they were convicted
of relaying NATO military secrets to Hungary.
   Sandor Kercsik, 48, and Imre Kercsik, 34, both naturalized
Swedes, were arrested in August after authorities uncovered a spy
ring. Officials said the ring was headed by former U.S. Army
sergeant Clyde Lee Conrad in West Germany, which is a member of the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization.
   The prosecution said the Kercsik brothers acted as conduits for
information that Conrad sold to Hungary. Hungary belongs to the
Soviet-led Warsaw Pact military alliance.
   During their trial at the Molndal District Court outside this
southwestern city, the Kercsiks said they came under pressure by
agents who constantly reminded them that they had a sister and an
ailing mother still in Hungary.
   They maintained that they were innocent of espionage, saying
they did not collect secret material but only relayed it. Their
lawyers also said the brothers' activities were not directed
against neutral Sweden and had been carried out in other countries.
</TEXT>
