<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Litton     10-18 0171</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Litton,160</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Litton Division Pays $1.95 Million to Settle Government Claims</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A division of Litton Systems Inc. paid $1.95
million to resolve claims that the company inflated bids to supply
the government with military hardware, aircraft instrumentation and
radar equipment, the Justice Department said Tuesday.
   The civil settlement with Clifton Precision, Special Devices, of
Springfield, Pa., was reached following an audit cnducted and paid
for by Litton under a 1986 agreement with the government.
   The government alleged the company had failed to submit accurate
labor cost history when it bid on the contracts, despite Litton's
certification that it had done so. The government says it overpaid
labor costs during a nine-year period in connection with the
contracts.
   Litton was indicted and pleaded guilty in 1986 to defrauding the
government in bidding the material costs on the contracts. Litton
paid $11.9 million to settle the material issues and agreed to pay
double damages and interest on other claims, after losses were
determined. The new agreement addresses that determination.
</TEXT>
