<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Sudan 1stLd-Writethru a0705 10-18 0719</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sudan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0705,0735</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>At Least Quarter-Million Sudanese Died This Year</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADD 2 grafs at end UPDATING with plane reported hit by
gunfire.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DALIA BALIGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sudan's dusty paths became trails of
death where an an estimated 260,000 refugees, mostly children,
starved or died in the gunfire of a civil war this year, Western
relief officials said Tuesday.
   Among the victims were 180,000 children fleeing the war with
their parents, and about 95,000 could have been saved by simple
medical help such as vaccination, said Cole Dodge, Khartoum
representative of the United Nations child-welfare organization
UNICEF.
   The relief officials said most of the quarter-million people
died during long treks northward toward Khartoum or eastward into
Ethiopia in search of safety.
   The officials said the refugees, of whom one in five died,
suffered from lack of food or medical care after they left their
home villages.
   ``You have to notice that exceptionally large numbers of people,
affected by an accumulation of the effects of five years of war,
left their homes this year. Deaths in other years have been much
lower,'' said Dodge.
   Up to 2 million people have fled their homes in the southern
battle zone since the rebel Sudan People's Liberation Army, led by
U.S.-educated renegade army Col. John Garang, took up arms against
the government in 1983.
   The rebels, who are mostly Christian or animist Dinka tribesmen,
are fighting the government dominated by Arab-descended Moslems.
   Dodge said dimished farming and commerce in southern Sudan since
the war began have contributed to conditions that led to the high
number of deaths in 1988.
   ``The result is staggering: 260,000 estimated deaths. And that's
a conservative estimate,'' said one official, who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   Haj Tayeb, acting commissioner of relief, said Western agencies
have exaggerated the casualties. However, he said the government
has no estimates on the numbers of civilians who died or were made
homeless in the war.
   An army spokesman, who requested anonymity, said there also were
no official estimates of government or rebel battlefield casualties.
   Western relief figures show that in 1988, 700,000 southerners
walked to the northern capital of Khartoum, 150,000 to the southern
town of Juba, 300,000 to Ethiopia and 150,000 to the regions of
Kordofan and Darfur in western Sudan.
   Bryan Wannop, representative of the U.N. Development Program,
said relief organizations must distribute the food cautiously so
that it doesn't fall into the hands of the rebels.
   The government in Khartoum has accused some agencies of
supporting the guerrillas and has expelled several organizations.
   The guerrillas say they control more than 90 percent of the
southern countryside, but the government says it controls the main
towns. The towns are restricted to most Western relief agencies,
making it difficult to assess conditions there.
   The U.S. Agency for International Development announced last
week it was beginning a $1 million airlift to Abyei, a refugee town
of about 35,000 just north of the war zone. An estimated 3,000
residents starved or died of diseases during the summer. Up to
10,000 people were estimated to have died in the southern Kordofan
area near Abyei.
   Sources who spoke on condition of anonymity said the U.S. agency
also was trying to charter aircraft for a relief mission to the
rebel-besieged town of Aweil in the heart of the war zone. An
estimated 6,000 civilians and an undetermined number of troops were
reported stranded there with almost no food or supplies.
   But the sources said the American agency was having trouble
chartering a plane, since insurance rates have soared because of
rebel threats to shoot down relief planes. Another problem was
obtaining military approval for the flights, the sources said.
   A military spokesman who asked not to be identified charged that
some non-governmental Western relief organizations provide aid
mainly to the rebels.
   A Sudan Airways Boeing 707 was shot at on takeoff from Juba
airport Monday in southern Sudan and one engine was hit, but the
plane flew back to Khartoum on three engines and landed safely,
informed sources said.
   The sources, speaking in Khartoum on condition of anonymity,
said Tuesday they did not know who did the shooting or how many
people were on the plane, which mainly carries relief supplies to
Juba, capital of the Equatoria region.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
