<DOCNO> AP881018-0182 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-88 1850EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Poland 2ndLd-Writethru a0686 10-18 0721</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0686,0740</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Talks Postponed Until At Least Oct. 24</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout with reax from opposition, prosecutor
investigating demonstration; church expressing concern at treatment
of former strikers; Rakowski to go to Soviet Union. No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government announced Tuesday that
talks with the opposition have been delayed until after Oct. 24,
and urged its partners in the dialogue to disavow ``extreme
elements'' before the talks begin.
   The outlawed Solidarity labor federation replied it was ready to
begin talks immediately and blamed the government for the delay.
   Government spokesman Jerzy Urban strongly criticized
anti-communist banners and slogans during a street protest in
Gdansk on Sunday and asked participants in the discussions to
disassociate themselves from the protesters.
   Urban denied that the government was losing its will to enter
the talks or putting new conditions on the discussions, which are
to cover such questions as relegalizing Solidarity and economic and
political pluralism.
   ``There are justified fears that not all the partners of the
round table are being led by the same intention,'' he said.
   Urban said talks originally due to start Monday were delayed
because church representatives who will take part won't return from
Rome until Oct. 24 and because of remaining disagreements over who
will participate.
   ``It's difficult to talk with those who are shouting that they
want to hang communists,'' said Urban.
   ``In this situation, the constructive, pro-reformatory
opposition has to make its decision. Either it will be willing to
seek agreement, against the extreme wing, or it will get linked
with the extreme elements.''
   Solidarity denied any extremism on its side.
   ``Solidarity, by the fact that it seeks relegalization,
obviously is ready to act as a legal union which accepts the
constitution, and all the people participating in these talks will
share the same view,'' Solidarity spokesman Janusz Onyszkiewicz
said.
   Onyszkiewicz said the opposition has been ready since Monday to
begin. He said further delay could raise questions about the
government's desire for dialogue and prolongs an ``atmosphere of
hopelessness'' that he said led to the Gdansk episode.
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa and Interior Minister Gen. Czeslaw
Kiszczak originally agreed to the talks on Aug. 31.
   Walesa then brought a halt to nationwide strikes that were
Poland's worst labor unrest since 1981.
   While refusing to give a likely date for convening the round
table, Urban said officials would like discussions to begin between
Oct. 24 and the Nov. 2 visit to Poland by Britain's Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher.
   He said the atmosphere for the talks was made worse by the
Sunday march by about 700 youths in the Baltic port city of Gdansk
that ended with youths throwing rocks at riot police. Official
state publications and television gave heavy coverage to the
incident.
   The state-run PAP news agency said a prosecutor was
investigating.
   Urban said that among slogans chanted were ``Communists will
hang on trees instead of leaves!'' and ``Better the coffin than the
commune!''
   ``I think that the organizers of this demonstration were
striving for torpedoing the agreement (for talks) and for
overturning the round table,'' he said.
   But Solidarity spokeswoman Barbara Madajska-Krasowska on Sunday
said Solidarity activists tried to persuade the demonstrators to
disperse. The youths left only after police with water cannon
arrived, she said.
   Urban said Tuesday that ``a problem'' remained with the proposed
participation of longtime Solidarity advisers Jacek Kuron and Adam
Michnik.
   ``Gen. Kiszczak's offer ... said that all who stand on the
ground of socialism and the constitutional order can sit at this
table,'' Urban said. ``It's difficult for Michnik and Kuron to fit
into this category.''
   The Roman Catholic Church expressed concern Tuesday night that
job guarantees given workers who ended strikes in August and
September were violated.
   The episcopate secretariat, representing Catholic bishops
nationwide, said it sent a letter Monday to Kiszczak reminding him
of the guarantees of personal and employment security for strikers.
   Coal miners in southern Silesia and steel workers in the
southeastern city of Stalowa Wola complained that strikers lost
their jobs or suffered other reprisals, the secretariat reported.
   In another announcement, Urban said that Prime Minister
Mieczyslaw F. Rakowski plans to visit the Soviet Union this week in
his first trip abroad as head of government. Urban did not give an
exact date.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
