<2ND_LINE>AM-Pakistan-Bomb,0159</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Seven Reported Killed in Bomb Blast</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARSADDA, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb blasted the center of this
northwestern Pakistani village Tuesday and witnesses said seven
people were killed and 12 injured.
   Police put the toll at two killed and ``many'' injured.
   Details about the explosion were not immediately available and
no group claimed responsibility. Police have charged that agents of
the Afghan government secret service, Wad, are smuggling explosive
devices into Pakistan.
   Charsadda is several miles from the Afghan border.
   Witnesses, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said some of the
seriously wounded were transferred to the provincial capital of
Peshawar about 12 miles to the northwest..
   Provincial police official Agha Saadat Ali told a news
conference in Peshawar on Tuesday police had recovered 14
foreign-made plastic explosive devices over the weekend.
   U.S.-backed Islamic guerrillas, based in Pakistan, have been
fighting the Marxist government in Afghanistan for 10 years.
</TEXT>
