<DOCNO> AP881018-0185 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-88 1901EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bentsen 2ndLd-Writethru a0719 10-18 0716</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bentsen, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0719,720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen Says He's Fed Up With Negative Campaigning</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES with UCLA speech as delivered; appearance in
Huntington Beach; EDITS to tighten.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Lloyd Bentsen unleashed a snarling
attack Tuesday on the Republicans for running a campaign that has
turned the presidential election ``into a carnival sideshow of
nonsense and negativism.''
   ``We have witnessed, through the combined efforts of the
Republican party and their image makers and their nominees for
president and vice president, one of the most outrageous displays
of negative campaigning ever seen in the history of national
politics,'' Michael Dukakis' running made said in a speech before
more than a thousand students in a UCLA auditorium. They were
attending a forum on public service sponsored by Sen. Sam Nunn,
D-Ga.
   ``The idea of citizenship, in fact, the very idea of
self-government itself, is under attack,'' the Texas senator said.
``And there is no greater violation of that trust than to turn a
great national election into a carnival sideshow of nonsense and
negativism.''
   ``What has happened _ almost without notice _ is an utterly
vicious assault of distortion and character assassination''
directed at Dukakis, he said.
   ``They don't seem to mind what they say is untrue,'' he said.
``They don't seem to mind if it's misleading. They don't seem to
care that what they do is downright mean. If it sounds good, say
it. If it sells, package it. If it looks good, nominate it.''
   Bentsen said the Democrats have at times been slow to respond to
the charges. ``But I don't think we ever imagined that George Bush
and the Republicans would be so willing to debase that precious
currency of our democracy.''
   The Democrats have ``taken a beating from the pundits and the
pollsters'' who have ``pointed to an open casket in the ground and
virtually invited us to jump in.'' But Bentsen, who had been
promisng a ``give-'em hell'' campaign for days, said, ``We've got
three weeks to go, there's a lot of work ahead, and there's no time
for mourning because we intend to win.''
   Bentsen ridiculed Bush's statement that he believed in public
service, saying the Republican White House philosophy preaches
contempt for government and ``get while the getting's good.''
   ``They don't believe in much of anything at all when it comes to
public service because they have nothing but disdain for the role
government can play in the life of this nation,'' he said.
   ``They don't understand the need for strong, ethical boundaries
between public service and private gain,'' he said.
   Following the UCLA forum, Bentsen visited a McDonnell Douglas
aerospace plant in nearby Huntington Beach with Nunn, the
conservative chairman of the Senate Armed Services Committee. Nunn
blasted the Republican assertion that the Democrats would cut
defense, recalling former Louisiana Gov. Earl Long's remark that to
tell when the opposition was lying, watch for when they ``move
their lips.''
   And then Bentsen emerged from a mock-up of a space station to
deliver a stump speech on defense and the space program.
   Bentsen was traveling next to a rally in San Jose, completing a
sweep of the three biggest California media markets in one day.
   Tuesday morning, Bentsen told local elected officials meeting in
San Diego that Democrats would pursue a much needed change in the
nation's trade and economic relations with its allies.
   ``We're not going to become hewers of wood and carriers of water
for the rest of the world. That's not our idea of America's
future,'' Bentsen told the League of California Cities convention.
   Bentsen said the Republican administration has failed to promote
U.S. trade, and has led the nation further and further into debt to
foreign countries.
   ``Many years ago, the famous pitcher, Satchel Paige, coined the
phrase: `Don't look back _ somebody might be gaining on you,' '' he
said. The need, he said, was for America to ``work harder and
smarter than the competition.''
   Dukakis, he said, had proven ``an ability to attract and sustain
high technology industries.''
   Bentsen said the United States must continue its role in
protecting its allies militarily. But, he said, it was time for
Japan and Europe to start paying their fair share of the cost.
</TEXT>
