<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Yugoslavia 1stLd-Writethru a0659 10-18 0669</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslavia, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0659,0686</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Party Wrangle Persists; No Word on Leadership Changes</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-4 UPDATE with meeting adjourns for night, no
announcements made. Picks up 3d graf pvs, Ten members ... with
minor editing to trim</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist Party factions argued
Tuesday about ethnic and social strife straining the fragile
Yugoslav union but the Central Committee ajourned for the night
without making any major announcements.
   The session ended without a vote on personnel changes. The
Tanjug news agency said the meeting would resume Wednesday morning.
   Early Wednesday editions of the official newspaper Borba said
many of the 200,000 Serbs in troubled Kosovo province were
dissatisfied with the ``fruitless and marathon discussions'' by
Central Committee members and planned a protest rally Thursday in
Pristina, the provincial capital.
   The committee is expected to make major personnel and policy
changes in efforts to quiet demands for dismissal of leaders blamed
in public protests for the nation's worst economic crisis since
World War II.
   Ten members of the 23-man ruling Politburo, including national
party chief Stipe Suvar, face a secret vote of confidence in the
162-member Central Committee.
   Four Politburo members are not involved in the vote because they
already have promised to resign. Nine are exempt because they hold
their seats as party leaders of the armed forces and of
Yugoslavia's six republics and two autonomous provinces.
   One of those exempt from the vote is Slobodan Milosevic, the
populist party leader of Serbia. His is the largest republic and
the two autonomous provinces, Vojvodina and Kosovo, are part of it.
   His campaign for greater Serbian control over the provinces has
split the national party leadership, pitting him against
politicians who fear his standing with the people will rise at
their expense.
   Serbs have rallied by the hundreds of thousands in recent weeks
to express anger at alleged harassment of the Slavic minority by
the huge ethnic Albanian majority in Kosovo region, the ancient
Serbian heartland adjacent to Albania.
   At a time of growing economic hardship, Milosevic has found
broad sympathy for his demand that sweeping leadership changes be
made.
   Inflation is running at an annual rate of 217 percent, causing
real wages to plummet, and the foreign debt currently stands at $21
billion. Austerity measures imposed in May have inspired strikes
and protests by workers, whose average monthly wage is the
equivalent of less than $100.
   Yugoslavia has not had strong leadership since President Josip
Broz Tito died in 1980.
   Each republic and autonomous province has its own government and
party structure. Tito put the decentralized system and collective
federal presidency in his 1974 constitution to prevent one republic
from gaining sway, but the result has been ineffective government
by compromise.
   Milosevic's activities have put him in open conflict with Suvar
and Milan Kucan, party chief in Slovenia, a liberal,
Western-oriented northern republic.
   Branko Greganovic, leader of Yugoslavia's official youth union,
indirectly attacked Milosevic on Tuesday.
   ``Those leaders who are putting themselves at the head of
discontented masses behave as if they were gifts from God,'' he
said. ``They behave as if they did not come to power with the
leaders they now attack mercilessly.''
   Raif Dizdarevic, current head of the nine-member collective
federal presidency, seemed to rebuke both Milosevic and Kucan in
backing Suvar's call for party unity.
   ``The lack of unity in the leadership, multiplying of late, is a
great danger for the country,'' he told the Central Committee.
   ``We need accord to unite in fighting problems, without imposing
some kind of hegemony over one another,'' said Dizdarevic, who
threatened nine days ago to impose ``emergency measures'' if unrest
continued. He did not specify the measures.
   In Parliament, a government plan to relax austerity measures for
workers in profitable firms and social services foundered because
deputies said proposed salary increases were too small.
   The International Monetary Fund, which insisted on the austerity
program introduced in May, was said to have approved easing the
rules for some workers.
</TEXT>
