<2ND_LINE>AM-Teacher Strike,0332</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Seven Teachers Arrested In Ohio Teachers Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BARBERTON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven striking elementary school teachers
were arrested Tuesday when they tried to block a van carrying
substitutes from entering the school.
   Second-grade teacher Mary Beth Foore said police arrested her
and six other women and put them in a police van after they draped
a 30-foot-long banner across a driveway to the Memorial Elementary
School in this Akron suburb in northeast Ohio.
   The banner said ``Kids Count _ Teachers On Strike For Class
Size.''
   The teachers were charged with disorderly conduct and released,
she said.
   The arrests came after the Barberton Teachers Association
rejected the school board's latest contract offer at a meeting
Sunday night. The association represents 285 teachers that struck
the 4,600-student system on Oct. 3.
   Lt. Ray Todd of the Barberton Police Department said the women
were arrested Tuesday morning after they refused to move away from
the front of the van. He identified the six other women as Carol
MacFarland, Jean Aleman, Maxie Muckleroy, Gloria Fickert, Paulette
Walker and Lynn Daverey.
   ``It was very scary, most of us have never had a parking or
traffic ticket before,'' Ms. Foore said. ``Elementary teachers are
normally very meek and very mild and very passive. I would do it
again. It's not the money, it's the class size.''
   Police said Ms. MacFarland and Ms. Foore were also arrested
Monday and charged with disorderly conduct after they tried to
block a van carrying substitute teachers to the same school.
   Ms. Foore said those arrested are scheduled to appear in
Barberton Municipal Court on misdemeanor charges Oct. 24.
   Superintendent Ron Clemmer said the board has offered pay raises
of 4.9 percent, 4 percent and 4.5 percent over three years.
   Violet Berlin, president of the association, said the teachers
want a two-year contract with 5 percent raises, improved health
benefits and class size limited to a maximum of 30 students.
</TEXT>
