<2ND_LINE>AM-Central America,0152</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Salvador Says Central American Summit Canceled</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The five Central American
presidents have canceled their November summit meeting, Foreign
Minister Ricardo Acevedo said Tuesday.
   Acevedo gave as the reason _ ``We don't have a concrete agenda
or any positive points to offer our people.''
   The meeting may be rescheduled for early December in El
Salvador, he said.
   ``We don't want a presidents' meeting that is an international
political propaganda act, which would be counterproductive in the
long run,'' Acevedo told reporters.
   The presidents of Guatemala, Costa Rica, Honduras, Nicaragua and
El Salvador had agreed to meet to discuss reviving the regional
peace plan they signed on Aug. 7, 1987.
   The plan was aimed at ending civil wars in Guatemala, Nicaragua
and El Salvador. A fragile truce is in place in Nicaragua but
conflicts continue unabated in Guatemala and El Salvador.
