<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush 2ndLd-Writethru a0693 10-18 0787</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0693,790</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Vows to `Campaign As An Underdog' Until Election Day</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS pvs 20th graf, bgng, On an..., to record Springfield
appearance.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FULTON, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush said Tuesday that with
inspiration from Winston Churchill and Harry Truman he would
``campaign as an underdog'' until Election Day, despite polls
showing he has widened his lead over Democrat Michael Dukakis.
   ``No votes can be taken for granted and I'm not taking any votes
for granted,'' Bush told an audience at Westminister College.
   Westminster was the scene of Churchill's famous 1946 speech
declaring that a postwar ``Iron Curtain'' of secrecy and
self-imposed isolation had surrounded the Soviet Union and the
communist Eastern bloc.
   ``Churchill was right,'' Bush said, although few Americans
wanted to hear his message at the time.
   Several dozen protesters demonstrated outside the hall where the
vice president spoke. One carried a sign reading, ``Bush Is No
Churchill,'' echoing Democratic vice presidential nominee Lloyd
Bentsen's assertion that Bush running mate Dan Quayle was ``no Jack
Kennedy.''
   Bush said ``a rusting curtain'' separates East and West today,
but that ``in Europe and other parts of the world, we have yet to
see the full promise of Soviet change turn into change itself.''
   If elected president, Bush said, he would remain wary of Soviet
intentions, even though the Kremlin leadership under Mikhail S.
Gorbachev is more enlightened than before.
   ``Now is not the time to abandon realism about what moves the
Soviet Union,'' he said.
   Bush mentioned Churchill and President Truman, who came to
Fulton for the former prime minister's speech on March 5, 1946, in
connection with his own election campaign.
   Churchill had suffered many setbacks and rebounds from oblivion
during his long, tempestuous career in British politics, and Truman
scored a stunning upset when he defeated Thomas E. Dewey, the
heavily favored Republican candidate, in the 1948 presidential
election.
   ``Those two men offer a very personal lesson for me. They knew
the ups and downs of political life like few others. They knew that
political opinion polls can be very misleading. And they knew that
no vote could be taken for granted,'' Bush said.
   Paraphrasing baseball great Yogi Berra, the vice president said
both Churchill and Truman ``knew that no election was over until it
was really over.''
   ``There are undecided voters out there,'' Bush said. ``The race
is close in many states,'' including Missouri, he said.
   As he left his hotel for the Westminster speech, Bush was asked
how he could call himself an underdog when a new NBC News-Wall
Street Journal poll gave him a 17-point lead over Dukakis.
   ``We're not going to lighten up,'' he replied. ``We're going to
stay right down to the wire. ... If I find anybody letting up in my
campaign, they're history.''
   Asked how he could expect people to believe he was fighting like
an underdog, Bush replied, ``Watch my smile and watch me work.
Watch how fast we go and where we go. We're not letting up. The
worst thing to do would be to show a complacency I don't feel or an
overconfidence that I do not feel.''
   In his speech 42 years ago, Churchill said that ``from Stettin
in the Baltic to Trieste in the Adriatic, an Iron Curtain has
descended across the continent.''
   Bush said: ``We and our allies did not prevent the Iron Curtain
from shutting out the light to the East. But we did secure peace
and freedom for the West.''
   He said his campaign theme of ``peace through strength'' was
modeled after Churchill's world view.
   On an otherwise light campaign day, Bush used his official Air
Force Two jet plane as a backdrop in taping a campaign film, and
attended a rally attended by more than 3,000 people at Missouri
State University in Springfield.
   ``I have a feeling it's going to be tough for the liberals next
month,'' Bush said to the wildly cheering crowd.
   Bush aides said a new campaign commercial ridiculing Dukakis'
ride in an Army battle tank began airing Tuesday in several areas
around the country.
   ``This is no time to train somebody in how to meet with the
Russians,'' says the ad, which uses news footage of a helmeted
Dukakis standing in the turret of an M-1 tank.
   The Bush campaign is expected to intensify its TV commercials
dramatically in the final three weeks of the contest. Aides said
the vice president would hammer away at proven campaign themes such
as U.S.-Soviet relations, space and defense.
   Bush planned to make a campaign swing Wednesday through
Michigan, which Dukakis toured all day Tuesday, before he returns
to Washington for the first time in eight days.
</TEXT>
