<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Falklands     10-18 0481</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Falklands,0497</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Argentina Offers Talks Without Preconditions On Falklands</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Argentine Foreign Minister Dante Caputo said
Tuesday his government is ready to talk to Britain about the
Falkland Islands without preconditions, dropping its insistence
that sovereignty must be on any agenda.
   Caputo told Independent Television's Channel 4 in a broadcast
interview pre-recorded in Argentina that he believes the time is
right to start a dialogue between Argentina and Britain.
   The two countries have had no diplomatic relations since the
74-day Falklands War in 1982, won by Britain.
   ``I think there is a little light at the end of the tunnel,''
Caputo said. ``I think that we have enough common history, both
countries, and if we start a dialogue _ without preconditions _
just the dialogue, this is going to be very important.''
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's government has repeatedly
stated its willingness to talk with Argentina on ways to mend
relations, but has refused to discuss Falklands sovereignty with
Buenos Aires.
   A July 1984 meeting between British and Argentine government
officials at Bern, Switzerland, broke down over Argentine
insistence that Falklands sovereignty should be on the agenda.
   A Foreign Office statement Tuesday night reiterated Britain's
refusal to discuss sovereignty over the islands, which Britain has
ruled since 1833 and which Argentina claims as an inheritance from
the days of Spanish colonial rule. An Argentine invasion of the
islands touched off the Falklands War.
   ``The British government is determined to seek more normal
relations with Argentina and uphold its commitment to the Falkland
islanders,'' the Foreign Office said, referring to the 1,900 mostly
British-descended residents who have repeatedly stated their desire
to remain British.
   ``Sovereignty is not for discussion,'' the Foreign Office said.
   ``If Argentina genuinely wishes to improve relations with
Britain, she could do so by responding to the large number of
British proposals already on President (Raul) Alfonsin's table.''
   Britain and Argentina have held indirect talks through the
United States on some issues. Britain has said it wants to discuss
trade, air links and fishing with Argentina.
   Caputo, currently president of the United Nations General
Assembly, was asked if he meant Argentina would be prepared for
talks without discussing sovereignty.
   ``I'm saying without preconditions,'' he replied. ``This is a
very precise formula, without preconditions. No preconditions from
our side, no preconditions from their side.''
   Caputo said he hopes the talks will be held before Alfonsin
leaves office in December 1989.
   In an accompanying report on next May's presidential election,
Channel 4 asked Carlos Saul Menem about Caputo's proposal for talks
without preconditions. Menem, the opposition Peronist Party
candidate, is leading Eduardo Cesar Angeloz of Alfonsin's Radical
Civil Union in the polls.
   ``Sovereignty has got to be on the table,'' Menem said.
``Otherwise, there's no point in talking. I don't have any problem
negotiating with Mrs. Thatcher as long as she knows that the
islands' sovereignty is ours.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
