<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0475</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Snow in Minnesota; Cold Front Moves Across Northeast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A cold front spread over the Midwest and eastern parts of the
country Tuesday, bringing snow showers to Minnesota and high winds
to other areas.
   Areas in the central and southern Great Plains that had record
high temperatures in the 80s and 90s on Monday were only in the 50s
and 60s Tuesday.
   The first heavy snow of the season was reported at Hibbing,
Minn. Some accumulation was possible Tuesday afternoon in the
higher terrain.
   The cold front that is spreading the cooler air moved into New
York. Wind gusts between 30 to 50 mph were common from Buffalo,
N.Y., to Burlington, Vt.
   Rain showers continued to the east of the cold front and
extended south into the mid-Atlantic coastal states.
   Showers and thunderstorms developed in northeast Oklahoma and
brought pea-size hail and gusts to 40 mph in Muskogee. Showers and
thunderstorms continued in portions of Arkansas and extreme western
Tennessee. Patchy light rain was over Kansas and southwest Missouri.
   Light rain occurred throughout the morning in much of Washington.
   Heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 2 p.m. EDT
included three-tenths of an inch at Charleston, W.Va., and a
quarter-inch at Quillayute, Wash.
   Skies were mostly sunny over the Rocky Mountains and
southwestern states.
   Afternoon temperatures were in the 40s and 50s in the Great
Lakes region and from the northern Rockies to the Pacific Northwest.
   Readings were in the 70s and 80s from southern Virginia and the
Carolinas across the gulf coastal states to the southern half of
Texas.
   Temperatures were in the 60s and 70s over the southern and
central Rockies and much of the intermountain West. Readings in the
desert Southwest and interior valleys of California were mostly in
the 70s and 80s, with a few 90s in the deserts.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 37
degrees at Ely, Minn., to 92 degrees at Palm Springs, Calif. The
nation's low Tuesday morning was 15 degrees at Gunnison, Colo.
   The forecast for Wednesday called for scattered showers and
thunderstorms across southern portions of the Gulf coastal states.
Widely scattered showers were forecast near the eastern Great Lakes
and western Pennsylvania.
   High temperatures were to be in the 80s across the Gulf Coast
region and southern Texas. Readings were to be in the 80s and 90s
over the desert Southwest and interior California.
   Temperatures were expected to be in the 40s and 50s from New
England across the Great Lakes region to eastern portions of the
Dakotas and Nebraska. Highs were to be in the 50s from northern
Montana to northern Washington state. Highs elsewhere across the
nation were to reach the 60s and 70s.
</TEXT>
