<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MandalayRuby 1stLd-Writethru   10-18 0653</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mandalay Ruby, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0715,0667</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mandalay Ruby Goes On _ And Off _ The Block</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, `Instead, a...', to CORRECT high bid to $7.6
million sted $7.7 million. UPDATES throughout with Christie auction
of diamond Wednesday, auction of Star of Sierra Leone Diamond No.
2, and quote from Block.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY21</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY NEUMEISTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Mandalay Ruby, a royal red gem that weighs
48 carats, was supposed to sell for a record $15 million at auction
Tuesday.
   It didn't.
   Instead, a high bid of $7.6 million was rejected as insufficient
by the gem's owner, and the ruby _ which Sotheby's earlier called
the centerpiece of ``the most important jewelry sale ever held in
America'' _ was taken off the block.
   Meanwhile, Christie's auction house announced that the largest
diamond ever auctioned to the public would be offered at a sale
Wednesday.
   The 407.48-carat gem is second in size only to the 530.20-carat
Cullinan I, which is set in Britain's Imperial Sceptre as part of
the Crown Jewels.
   ``I'm certain this jewel will set a record price for a single
precious stone,'' said Francois Curiel, head of Christie's Jewelry
Department.
   He refused to estimate the price. The record auction price for
any jewel $9.31 million, the amount paid in April 19 for an
85.91-carat white diamond at Sotheby's.
   The diamond, currently owned by two New York jewelry dealers and
a jewelry retail chain in Dallas, was purchased as an uncut
890-carat stone in August 1984 but has since been cut into a
flawless stone.
   At Sotheby's auction house Tuesday, about 300 people strained
their necks to catch a glimpse of those who put up the
multimillion-dollar bids for the Mandalay Ruby. But the
auctioneer's gavel slammed down a short time later to end the
bidding without a sale.
   Jennifer Brown, a Sotheby's spokeswoman, said the identity of
the ruby's seller would not be revealed.
   ``Obviously, we're disappointed,'' said John D. Block, head of
Sotheby's jewelry department. ``This was expected to bring a record
and it didn't. It was such an enormous price we were trying to get.
On unique objects, it's very hard to put a price on it. Sometimes
it doesn't work.''
   The ruby was offered in the same session as the Star of Sierra
Leone Diamond No. 2, which was sold for $3.52 million Tuesday. The
diamond is one of 11 stones cut from a 969-carat diamond discovered
in the west African nation in 1972.
   Several Mandalay Ruby bidders, who asked not to be identified,
suggested that perhaps extensive pre-sale publicity about the ruby
had backfired on Sotheby's.
   In its pre-auction report, Sotheby's had given the Mandalay a
glowing review.
   ``The combination of pleasant shape and proportions, fine color,
transparency and luminosity, make it an exceptional gemstone,''
said a report released by the auction house.
   Block described the Mandalay Ruby as ``the largest faceted gem
known'' and estimated it would command about $15 million.
   The record price for a ruby is $1.9 million, paid at a Paris
auction in July for a 10.4-carat stone.
   The Mandalay Ruby is framed by 18 diamonds within a
gold-and-platinum broach mounting. Small, diamond-set fleur-de-lys
designs decorate the corners.
   The Mandalay Ruby, named after the Burmese city near which it
was mined, was brought to England in 1875. ``It is questionable if
the London market would ever have seen (the gem) but for the
necessities of the Burmese government,'' wrote Edwin W. Street, a
contemporary gem expert. ``In Burma, the sale ... created intense
excitement; a military escort was considered necessary to escort
the persons carrying the parcel to the vessel.''
   The gem was sold at Sotheby's in 1896. ``The buyer was reputed
to be an important Indian gem connoisseur acting on behalf of a
royal Indian family,'' according to a note by gem expert Benjamin
Zucker printed in the catalog for Tuesday's sale.
</TEXT>
