<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Chile     10-18 0299</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chile,0308</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Frees Prominent Leftist</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court on Tuesday reduced the
sentence of former Foreign Minister Clodomiro Almeyda, allowing the
Socialist politician to be freed after 15 months' political
imprisonment.
   Opposition parties called for Almeyda's release last week,
saying it would represent a good-will gesture by President Augusto
Pinochet.
   Gen. Pinochet lost a plebiscite two weeks ago on extending his
rule to 1997, and the triumphant opposition is pressing for
democratic reforms it says are needed for a transition to elected
civilian rule.
   As Almeyda left Santiago prison to the applause and cheers of
about 100 supporters, he declared his ``decision to join the
struggle of the Chilean people to recover full democracy.''
   Almeyda, president of the United Left, a five-party alliance,
was sentenced to 541 days for violating internal security laws by
making anti-government statements. The court cut that sentence to
390 days, less than the time already served.
   Almeyda, 65, was foreign minister under Marxist President
Salvador Allende, whose elected government was toppled by Pinochet
in a 1973 military coup. He served briefly as acting president
during a trip abroad by Allende, who died in the takeover.
   Imprisoned after the coup and later expelled, Almeyda
disregarded an official ban on his return and re-entered Chile in
March 1987. He was quickly jailed and senteced to three months
internal exile in a small southern town.
   After that exile ended in June, a federal court convicted him of
``apology of violence,'' stemming from his verbal attacks on the
Pinochet government, and sentenced him to prison.
   Last December, he was politically banned for 10 years for
allegedly violating a constitutional article banning pro-Marxist
statements and propaganda.
   With Pinochet's plebiscite defeat, an open presidential election
is due to take place in December 1989.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
