<2ND_LINE>AM-Switzerland-Marcos,0179</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Swiss Judge Orders Release of Marcos' Banking Records</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Geneva judge said Tuesday he has ordered that
banking records on assets linked to ousted President Ferdinand
Marcos be released to Philippine authorities.
   But his decision is certain to be fought by Marcos' lawyers.
They have appealed every court ruling involving the assets of
Marcos, who left the Philippines in February 1986 during a
civilian-military uprising. He is now living in Hawaii.
   Geneva Investigating Magistrate Vladimir Stemberger told
reporters his order released the records on the accounts held in
Geneva-based banks by 12 corporate bodies and people including
Marcos and his wife, Imelda.
   Marcos' lawyers have 10 days to file appeals.
   The Geneva ruling did not apply to the assets, which remain
frozen, Stemberger said. He declined to say what amounts are
involved.
   Officials in the Philippines claim about $1 billion in
``ill-gotten wealth'' were channeled into Swiss bank accounts
during Marcos' 20-year rule. The assets are reported to be placed
in the cantons of Geneva, Fribourg and Zurich.
</TEXT>
