<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881018-0203 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-88 2221EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PTL 1stLd-Writethru a0652 10-18 0619</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-PTL, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0652,0634</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bakker Says He's In Fight For His Life</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 5 grafs after 12th, According to...' to UPDATE with
afternoon testimony; picks up 6th graf pvs, `Under
cross-examination...'; new last graf to include testimony from IRS
agent.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CF1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TRIP DuBARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   PTL founder Jim Bakker said Tuesday he is
fighting for his life in his defense against a $52 million lawsuit
accusing him, his wife and a former aide of mismanaging the
ministry he left in disgrace.
   Bakker's work for the ministry, with its television programs and
Heritage USA religious theme park, was praised in court by a former
member of the PTL board, who said Bakker deserved his high salary
and every bonus he received.
   And the evangelist's former financial secretary testified that
he reimbursed the ministry for personal expenses that were paid for
out of PTL funds.
   During a lunch break at the trial in U.S. Bankruptcy Court,
Bakker said of the case, ``It may be business as usual for everyone
else, but this is my life I'm talking about.'' He called it
``literally a trial for my life.''
   In the first week of the trial, held last month, PTL's current
managers presented testimony and evidence that Bakker received
millions of dollars in bonuses and salaries.
   The ministry went into Chapter 11 bankruptcy, seeking protection
from creditors while it reorganized, in June 1987, three months
after Bakker resigned in a sex-and-hush-money scandal.
   In testimony Tuesday, pastor Evelyn Spencer of The House of
Truth Church in Oakland, Calif., said that she and other PTL board
members consistently voted unanimously in favor of bonuses for
Bakker.
   ``If a bonus came up, I voted for it,'' said Ms. Spencer, who
was on the board from November 1985 to March 1987, when the board
resigned.
   According to IRS figures presented in court, Bakker received
$278,000 in salaries in the fiscal year ending in May 1987, plus an
additional $1,167,000 in bonuses in that year.
   Bakker was to testify Tuesday but that was postponed a day to
allow him time to review canceled checks and reimbursement vouchers
that were supplied to his attorneys Monday.
   Bakker said he was ``a touch angry'' that he was only now
receiving information he needs to defend himself, and hinted at
intentional sabotage. ``I think somebody calculated they would hold
all the materials until the middle of the trial,'' he said, though
he did not say who.
   And he predicted his research would satisfy at least 90 percent
of the IRS's concerns.
   Also testifying Tuesday was independent financial analyst James
Wilson, who said PTL's finances from 1978 to 1986 showed it to be a
healthy, growing ministry without financial problems.
   According to Wilson, the ministry's fixed assets grew at an
annual compound rate of 28 percent during that time while revenues
increased 19 percent.
   Under cross-examination by PTL attorney Tom White, Ms. Spencer
could not recall the precise salary of Bakker during her time on
the board.
   ``Everything you can get your hands on would be fair?'' Judge
Rufus Reynolds asked Ms. Spencer about Bakker's compensation. Ms.
Spencer denied that.
   Also testifying was Patricia Harrison, Bakker's former financial
secretary, who said her job was to keep his personal expenses
separate from the ministry's money. She said she routinely wrote
reimbursement checks to the ministry for Bakker's expenses.
   But she said former Bakker aide David Taggart, also a defendant,
frequently received cash advances for himself and Bakker for which
she never saw documentation. Taggart told her he kept that
documentation at home, she said.
   An IRS agent also testified he found cash advances to Bakker and
Taggart that apparently served no legitimate business purpose.
</TEXT>
