<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LoneRangerCommittee 1stLd-Writethru   10-18 0335</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lone Ranger Committee, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0689,0338</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lone Ranger Committee Appears Ready To Ride Off Into Sunset</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 2 grafs to CORRECT that Beemer not the original
Lone Ranger but was original narrator. Picks up 3rd graf, `At
what's...'.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>OXFORD, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A debt-ridden committee formed to promote
Oxford as home of the original Lone Ranger narrator on radio is
about to ride into the sunset without erecting a hoped-for statue
in a city park.
   The committee had sought to erect a statue of Brace Beemer, the
original Lone Ranger radio show narrator and the fourth voice of
the Lone Ranger in the 1940s, but fell far short of the $75,000
that would have been needed for the monument, committee members
said.
   At what's expected to be its final meeting Thursday, the group
will discuss how to dispose of its assets of about $3,000, said
Jacqueline Wassil. A $2,000 printing bill is still unpaid, she
said. The committee has already repaid $20,000 in debts, committee
members said.
   In its first year, the group spared no expense in its promotion
of the city, about 35 miles northwest of Detroit, as home of the
Lone Ranger. The committee sponsored a Super Week, held in
conjunction with the Super Bowl, which was played in Pontiac on
Jan. 24, 1982.
   ``We threw a three-day party like this town has never seen _ and
never will again,'' Wassil said. Events included a concert by
country music star Tammy Wynette that cost $10,000.
   In the years following Super Week, the Lone Ranger Committee
hosted other fund-raisers but none were successful, Wassil said.
   Robert L. Bunting, an attorney who hasn't given up on erecting a
Lone Ranger statue, said he won't miss the committee.
   ``I've never had much faith in committees. I think the Lone
Ranger would have ended up on a camel,'' Bunting said.
   Bunting said he believes private funding, particularly corporate
donations, could finance the statue.
   ``It's just going to take a while,'' Bunting said.
</TEXT>
