<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Senate-Veterans 1stLd-Writethru a0784 10-18 0753</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Senate-Veterans, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0784,740</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Approves Bill Making VA a Cabinet Department</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 4 grafs after 15th graf pvs bgng, `The House,' to
UPDATE with Agent Orange amendment</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate granted election-year benefits to
one of the nation's largest interest groups Tuesday when it
approved bills elevating the Veterans Administration to a Cabinet
department and granting veterans the right to have courts review VA
denial of benefits.
   Both measures were approved on voice votes. The measure creating
the new Cabinet department now goes to President Reagan, who is
expected to sign it, while the judicial review plan must be
returned to the House for approval.
   The Senate also passed on a voice vote a bill granting a series
of cost-of-living increases in a variety of VA payments. The House
has yet to act on its version of that legislation.
   The Department of Veterans Affairs would be the 14th Cabinet
seat and the fifth created since 1960. The House passed the bill by
voice vote Oct. 6.
   Backers of the change said the Veterans Administration already
has the fifth-largest budget among federal agencies and giving it
Cabinet status will assure that the money is spent properly.
   The VA, with an annual budget of $30 billion, serves 27 million
veterans and 49 million dependents or survivors. It will pay out
about $14 billion this year in income maintenance and $626 million
for education and rehabilitation assistance in the current fiscal
year.
   The agency and its 240,000 employees administer about 90,000
patient beds in 534 health facilities and VA doctors will see about
20 million outpatients this year. It runs 109 national cemeteries
and will bury 300,000 veterans in the next 12 months.
   According to the Congressional Budget Office, switching the VA
to a Cabinet department will cost $33 million over five years. Most
of that will be spent on changing signs on VA buildings.
   The second major piece of legislation gives veterans, for the
first time in 170 years, the right to ask federal courts to review
VA denials of benefits.
   The bill creates a new ``U.S. Court of Veterans Appeals,'' and
abolishes the current Board of Veterans' Appeals. That panel is
part of the VA and is now the last resort of veterans who are
unhappy with decisions to reject their claims.
   The measure also eliminates a Civil War-era law which limits
attorney's fees for veterans' claims to $10 per claim. That made it
difficult for veterans to hire lawyers other than those provided by
the VA.
   Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., chairman of the Senate Veterans
Affairs Committee, called the measure a ``historic advance in
veterans' rights.''
   The House approved somewhat similar legislation on Oct. 3 by a
400-0 vote, but there were minor differences between that proposal
and the Senate package. The Senate bill will now be returned to the
House for another vote.
   The benefits increase legislation provides that 2.2 million
veterans with service-connected disabilities and 310,000 widows and
orphans will receive the same cost-of-living increases paid to
Social Security recipients.
   The House is expected to pass its own version, which would
provide a specific 4.1 percent increase, according to Cranston. The
Senate ``will undoubtedly concur'' with the House proposal, he
predicted.
   The Senate added an amendment which could provide interim health
care payments to some of the Vietnam veterans who were exposed to
Agent Orange, a highly toxic defoliant used by the United States in
Southeast Asia.
   The measure provides a ``presumption of service connection,''
under which the VA would assume that two types of cancer _
non-Hodgkin's lymphoma and soft-tissue sarcoma _ were caused by
Agent Orange. Veterans could receive benefits while the U.S.
government, which hasn't finally agreed that Agent Orange caused
cancers, studies the problem.
   Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., a Vietnam veteran, said Agent Orange
provisions will have ``a very limited effect.''
   ``I find it highly disturbing that those people who went to
fight the VC (Viet Cong) in Vietnam spend too much time fighting
the VA back here in this country,'' Kerry said.
   Before passage, the Senate approved, 47-15, an amendment to
permit the VA to offer Vietnam-era veterans flight training courses
under the auspices of the GI bill.
   Sen. Tom Daschle, D-S.D., the sponsor, said airline deregulation
has created vacancies among pilots and there will be thousands of
pilot jobs to be filled in the next decade.
   But critics said the program was offered on a trial basis in
past years and hadn't worked.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
