<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-88 2226EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Wildfires     10-18 0376</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wildfires,0387</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Animal Shelter and Giant Sequoias Out of Immediate Fire Danger</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDY FARAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wildfires were slowed Tuesday by lower
temperatures and diminished winds after burning more than 7,300
acres and an exotic animal refuge and ancient Sequoia trees were
put out of immediate danger.
   The good news came after nearly 2,000 firefighters attacked two
big blazes with water-dropping helicopters and ground crews that
cut fire lines around the threatened animals and trees.
   The Divide fire in the Angeles National Forest 30 miles
northwest of Los Angeles had burned 4,110 acres by Tuesday but
stopped advancing toward the Wildlife Waystation, a shelter for
1,000 exotic animals that have been abandoned or wandered into
neighborhoods.
   ``It's still a long-range threat,'' cautioned Robert Brady, a
spokesman for the U.S. Forest Service.
   ``It looks like we have survived this one well. We've made it,''
said Martine Colett, owner of the shelter. ``My face is a picture
of wonderfulness.''
   The lions, tigers, giraffes, jaguars, horses, alligators and
other animals housed at the shelter became agitated as smoke and
ashes surrounded the area and airplanes buzzed overhead, but they
calmed down Tuesday as the fire slowed, she said.
   Ms. Colett praised the firefighters, who worked to clear an area
around the shelter and set a backfire to burn brush down the
mountain toward the fire, she said.
   The fire, started by a 10-year-old boy playing with matches,
burned in inaccessible mountain terrain and was 50 percent
contained Tuesday with full containment expected Wednesday evening.
Two of the 1,030 firefighters battling the blaze suffered minor
injuries.
   In the Sequoia National Forest 125 miles north of Los Angeles,
lower temperatures of 70 degrees and winds 3 to 10 mph aided
firefighters battling a 1,900-acre brushfire that threatened
2,700-year-old Sequoia trees in the 3-square-mile Giant Forest.
   Firefighters quickly extinguished a flare-up Tuesday morning
near the grove of trees which are considered the largest living
things on Earth.
   Although the trees were out of immediate danger, the threat
remained.
   The fire, which officials believe was started by a careless
camper or smoker, was 20 percent contained Tuesday but no estimate
was given on full containment. Four of the 930 firefighters on the
blaze suffered minor injuries.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
