<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru   10-18 0625</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0680,0641</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Legislators Fail to Elect Speaker of Parliament</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 4 grafs after 7th pvs, ``Two rival, to UPDATE with
new U.S. ambassador visitng Foreign Ministry. Pick up 8th pvs,
``When the...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RODEINA KENAAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Right-wing Christian legislators
boycotted a voting session that was to elect a new speaker of
parliament Tuesday, and a lawmaker said his colleagues were
``dancing on the grave'' of Lebanon.
   The failure to elect a successor to Hussein Husseini, a Shiite
Moslem whose one-year term ended Sunday, sparked a new feud between
Christians and Moslems.
   In the absence of the 39-member quorum required to extend
Husseini's term or elect a new speaker, the 26 Moslem deputies who
showed up for the voting session declared Husseini a caretaker
speaker until a successor can be elected.
   The Christian deputies countered by issuing a statement
rejecting Husseini, a staunch ally of Syria, and naming their own
speaker pro tempore _ Kazem Khalil, 88, the eldest deputy among the
76 members of parliament.
   ``This is the fatal blow,'' said Khalil, a Western-oriented
Shiite who lives in Christian east Beirut. ``We're actually dancing
on the grave in which we have buried Lebanon.''
   Lebanon has been without a head of state since President Amin
Gemayel's six-year term ended Sept. 22 and no successor was elected
because parliament could not gather the necessary quorum.
   Two rival governments, one Moslem and one Christian, have since
emerged, splitting the army and security forces along religious
lines.
   Newly arrived U.S. Ambassador John McCarthy made his first visit
to the Foreign Ministry Tuesday, apparently to smooth tensions
after he was criticized by the ministry's director general, Farouk
Abil-Lamaa, for not presenting his credentials to the Christian
government of army commander Gen. Michel Aoun.
   ``I came to see the director-general to discuss basically the
general state of relations between Lebanon and the United States,''
McCarthy told reporters after the meeting at the building in east
Beirut.
   McCarthy took up his post Sept. 24, two days after the
expiration of Gemayel's term. He has been meeting almost daily with
Christian and Moslem leaders.
   McCarthy has declared he will present his credentials only to
the newly elected president, not to Aoun's Cabinet or the rival
government of incumbent Acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss, a
Syrian-backed Sunni Moslem.
   When the Moslem deputies arrived for the 11 a.m. session at the
Parliament in Syrian-policed west Beirut, sniper fire crackled
overhead and some of the men were seen ducking for cover as they
approached the building in the devastated city center.
   Police said the bullets probably were fired by Christian
militiamen hiding in battle-scarred apartment buildings nearby.
   ``(The naming of Husseini as caretaker speaker) is essential to
preserve the integrity of the legislative authority, especially at
a time when the top executive post remains vacant,'' the Moslem
legislators said.
   The Christians justified their boycott of Tuesday's session by
declaring the area near Parliament unsafe. They demanded the
session be shifted to Villa Mansour, a two-story building near
Beirut's dividing Green Line that has served as temporary
headquarters for the Parliament since 1976.
   The Christians boycotted three previous Parliament sessions
called for Aug. 18, Sept. 22 and Sept. 23 to elect a successor to
Gemayel.
   Minutes before he bowed out 26 days ago, Gemayel, a Maronite
Catholic, named Aoun, then army commander and also a Maronite,
prime minister of a caretaker military Cabinet.
   But Moslems claimed Aoun's appointment violated an unwritten
national agreement dating to Lebanon's independence from France in
1943, under which the president has always been a Maronite, the
prime minister a Sunni and the speaker of Parliament a Shiite.
   The Moslems pledged allegiance to the incumbent Cabinet of Sunni
Moslem Prime Minister Salim Hoss.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
