<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines-US 1stLd-Writethru a0606 10-18 0572</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines-US, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0606,0585</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Critics Say New Agreement On U.S. Bases A Deception</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-6 UPDATE with Wednesday newspaper comment and
CORRECT number of bases in 2nd graf from four to six. PICKS up 6th
graf pvs, ``We asked ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By YASMIN ARQUIZA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Critics accused the foreign secretary
of deceiving his people for signing a new agreement o U.S. military
bases, but President Corazon Aquino said the pact enhances
Philippine-U.S. relations.
   The accord, signed Monday in Washington by Secretary of State
George Shultz and Philippine Foreign Secretary Raul Manglapus,
allows the United States to use six military bases in the
Philippines until 1991.
   ``He has sold out his country and grossly deceived his people,''
the national Malaya daily said of Manglapus. ``For these treasonous
acts, he ought never to show his face again in Manila.''
   Critics said the accord could prompt even stronger opposition to
U.S.-run Clark Air Base, Subic Bay Naval Base and four smaller
garrisons.
   ``The general perception is that the Philippines got the short
end of the deal, and this perception is expected to be exploited by
the anti-bases bloc to further fan the wave of anti-Americanism in
the country,'' wrote columnist Alvin Capino in Wednesday's issue of
the Philippine Daily Globe.
   Under the agreement, the U.S. government will pay the
Philippines $962 million a year for the use of the bases. The
Philippines had demanded $1.2 billion a year.
   ``We asked for 12 boxes of delicious apples, they gave us four
small bags of peanuts,'' said Sen. Ernesto Maceda, chairman of the
senate defense committee.
   He called the payment ``a publicly unacceptable compensation
package certainly strengthens the hand of those who are batting for
no extension after 1991.''
   Senators on Tuesday debated whether the pact required their
approval in accordance with a constitutional provision on
international agreements, but were unable to resolve the issue and
postponed discussion to a later date.
   ``I think many people, even those who are pro-bases, were
disappointed by the outcome so that would even help our cause,''
said Sen. Wigberto Tanada, a leading opponent of the bases and
principal sponsor of a senate bill banning the presence of nuclear
arms in the Philippines.
   The pact allows the United States to maintain its policy of
neither confirming nor denying the presence of nuclear weapons in
aircraft and ships visiting the bases.
   Although U.S. policy was upheld, Mrs. Aquino said a
constitutional ban on nuclear weapons on Philippine territory ``is
being implemented,'' since the storage of such arms here requires
government consent.
   The Philippine constitution, approved in 1987, adopts a policy
of freedom from nuclear weapons ``consistent with the national
interest.'' Legal experts say the phrase falls short of an outright
ban.
   ``The agreement reaffirms the enduring bilateral relationship
between our respective countries and allows us to proceed to
improve other aspects in that relationship,'' Mrs. Aquino said in a
statement.
   Communist guerillas, whose demand for the removal of the bases
has fanned a 20-year-old rebellion, accused the goverment of
``shamelessly selling out'' Philippine sovereignty.
   ``We call on the Filipino people to reject this new agreement
and hold President Corazon Aquino accountable for this act of high
treason,'' the outlawed Communist Party of the Philippines said in
a statement.
   The accord ends a nearly seven-month review of the 1947
agreement governing the U.S. bases in the Philippines, which are
the largest in the Pacific.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881018-0211 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-88 2234EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Argentina     10-18 0556</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Argentina,0574</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Alfonsin Sets May 14 Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Raul Alfonsin on
Tuesday called national elections for May 14 and hailed in advance
what he termed ``a singular accomplishment'' in Argentina _ the
peaceful handing over of political power.
   ``On Dec. 10, 1989, 61 years since the last time it happened, I
will hand over the sash and cane (Argentine symbols of office) to
the president who will succeed me in the honorable task of leading
Argentines on the unstoppable path to progress and greatness,''
Alfonsin said.
   In 1928, Hipolito Yrigoyen won national elections and replaced
President Marcelo T. de Alvear. Two years later Yrigoyen was
toppled by a military coup.
   Since Gen. Juan D. Peron completed his first term in 1952, no
Argentine president has finished the traditional six years in
office. A military coup ousted Peron in 1955 and the party that
carries his name was banned for the next 18 years.
   ``This is a victory for democracy,'' Alfonsin said in a
seven-minute speech taped at Government House and broadcast
nationwide at 9 p.m. ``We will complete the triumph of today in the
ballot boxes.''
   Interior Minister Enrique Nosiglia announced last month that
elections would be held in May. No exact date was set until
Alfonsin's speech.
   The two main political parties already have begun campaigning.
Eduardo Angeloz, the presidential candidate of Alfonsin's centrist
Radical Civic Union, began his campaign on Sept. 30 with a
multicity tour.
   Carlos Menem of the Peronist Party started his campaign Saturday
night.
   About 75,000 Peronists gathered Monday in the River Plate soccer
stadium to celebrate the anniversary of Peron's release from prison
in 1945 _ a pivotal event in Argentine history. Peron went on to
dominate Argentine politics for years.
   The third main candidate is Alvaro Alsogaray of the Union of the
Democratic Center.
   Both Menem and Angeloz are lawyers and provincial governors.
Alsogaray is an engineer, former economy minister and ex-ambassador
to the United States.
   Up for election are the presidency, vice presidency, many seats
in the House of Deputies, and thousands of provincial mayors and
local legislators.
   The main issue probably will be the economy. Gross national
production has been stagnant for eight years and inflation has
soared.
   The cost of living increased by 440 percent over the past 12
months. Public employees including doctors, railway engineers,
teachers and mail carriers hold frequent strikes to press demands
that wages keep pace with inflation.
   Polls indicate that Menem, who promises wage increases and tax
cuts, has a wide early lead over the more conservative Angeloz.
   The surveys gave Alsogaray virtually no chance of victory.
   Alfonsin's inauguration on Dec. 10, 1983, following elections
that October, ended nearly eight years of right-wing military
dictatorships.
   An attorney and human rights leader, Alfonsin has defended his
political record by stressing that whatever he did took place in a
democracy.
   ``In stable democracies, this occurrence (an election) is
routine,'' said Alfonsin on Tuesday, dressed in a dark suit and
seated at an ornate desk. ``In our country, which is subject to
shocks and disasters, it is a singular accomplishment.
   ``I have been an actor in a historic episode, but the authors,
those ultimately responsible, are each and every Argentine. None
should be indifferent to the jubilation ... and true national
celebration.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
