<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-88 2234EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Theater     10-18 0362</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Theater,0369</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`What Did He See?,' A Play by Richard Foreman, Opens Off-Broadway</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs planned.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stage is a medieval dungeon with furniture
and costumes that could have come from a seedy Greenwich Village
antique shop. Plexiglas panels separate the actors from the
audience, forcing the performers to wear body microphones so they
can be heard.
   One cast member, sporting a black beret festooned with tiny pink
roses, resembles a prancing Che Guevara masquerading as Isadora
Duncan. A second performer dresses in what looks like a nurse's
uniform _ only she's wearing patent leather shoes topped with
little black bows. A third actor wears red pajamas and a red
stocking cap. He's the hero of the piece, or at least the performer
with the most lines.
   It's hard to learn anything about these people in ``What Did He
See?'' _ Richard Foreman's latest exercise in avant-garde
incomprehensibility that opened Tuesday at off-Broadway's New York
Shakespeare Festival Public Theater.
   The three-character play lasts one hour. It seems like more,
especially if you attempt to decipher what the author is trying to
say. Foreman should know, since he wrote, directed and designed the
production. It's theatergoers who are left in the dark.
   In interviews, Foreman has described the play as being about the
dangers of retirement or the lure of idleness. You'll have to take
him at his word. The evening is mostly a series of independent
statements.
   For example, the pajama-clad hero announces, ``I have to tell
the truth. I no longer function as a normal human being.'' He's
right.
   The actors work hard at seeming to believe all they have to say.
Will Patton, best known as the villain in the film thriller ``No
Way Out,'' projects what appears to be an appropriate air of
desperation. Lili Taylor and Rocco Sisto are his mysterious
sidekicks, the people who alternately support or berate him,
depending on the whims of the playwright. Their dedication is
admirable.
   The title of the play asks ``What Did He See?'' It poses a murky
question that can only have one answer _ not very much.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881018-0213 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-88 2235EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-France-Strikes     10-18 0353</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Strikes,0361</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Marches, Strikes Disrupt Services</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist-led General Confederation of Labor,
France's largest union, launched its ``Day of Action'' Tuesday with
marches in all major cities and strikes that disruped public
services.
   The one-day walkout was to support demands for an increase in
the minimum monthly wage from $758 to $968. The confederation also
is asking for protection of purchasing power, more employment,
better working conditions and retirement protection.
   Tuesday's strike hit hardest public transportation, the postal
service and the state-run electricity company. But it is only a
foretaste of more widespread strikes scheduled for Thursday by the
other unions representing public employees.
   Michel Durafour, the civil service minister, has refused to
consider any new pay increases for 1988. Talks between the
government and the unions on 1989 salaries are to begin soon.
   Also joining the strike were employees at French diplomatic
posts around the world, where staff are fighting a series of cuts
in their cost-of-living allowments.
   It coincided with a nationwide strike by France's nurses and
hospital employees who demand higher wages. The nurses want $325 a
month more. The government has offered about $105, depending on
experience and seniority.
   President Francois Mitterrand, on a visit to Normandy, told a
group of nurses that they were asking ``much too much,'' saying the
government of Premier Michel Rocard already had ``given a lot.''
   The workers' demonstration in Paris turned out 100,000 people,
according to the union. Police estimated the crowd at 15,000 to
20,000. About 5,000 marched in Lyon, Bordeaux and Marseille, each
and smaller demonstrations were held in other cities.
   The Paris subway ran at about 50 percent to 70 percent of its
normal service Tuesday, while service was normal in Lyon and
Marseille. Long distrance rail lines were practically normal in
most parts of the country, except for the west, where a third of
the scheduled trains did not run.
   Hardest hit was the state-run electric company. Sporadic power
cuts hit nearly all areas. The postal service also was heavily
affected. Strikes in main sorting centers spelled delays of mail
for the next several days.
</TEXT>
