<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-KoreanTension     10-18 0455</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Korean Tension,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Praises Roh, Plans New Policy Support</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Korean President Roh Tae-woo's proposal
for ending four decades of rivalry and conflict with North Korea is
being praised by a senior U.S. official as an ``imaginative and
constructive policy of reconciliation and accommodation.''
   The United States plans in a few days to announce changes in
American policy toward North Korea in a new effort to lower tension
on the Korean peninsula going back to the 1950-53 Korean War, the
official said Tuesday.
   U.S. policy toward North Korea is currently under review, in
consultation with South Korea, and changes probably will be
announced soon after Roh's talks with President Reagan at the White
House Thursday, the official added. The source briefed reporters on
Korean issues and the forthcoming Reagan-Roh meeting on condition
he not be identified.
   ``Dramatic change'' should not be expected in U.S. policy toward
North Korea because ``after all, we're talking about a state which
we have officially characterized as terrorist,'' he said. But the
United States wants to take some steps ``which we hope will be in
conformity with President Roh's desires and the desires of the
Korean people to ease the tensions on the peninsula and to create
an atmosphere which will allow for a peaceful resolution of the
differences that exist there,'' he said.
   The United States put North Korea on its list of terrorist
countries in January, citing evidence that North Korean agents were
responsible for blowing up a Korean Air Lines jet near off Burma
last November in which 115 people died. The move cancelled an
earlier relaxation of rules against informal U.S. contacts with
North Korea diplomats.
   The changes under discussion cover matters other than diplomatic
contacts and trade, the source said, declining further details.
   U.S. policymakers are not giving South Korea veto power over
U.S. decisions, the official said. ``It's going to be our
determination where we go and how far we go, but we're certainly
not going to'' upset the close relations between South Korea and
the United States, he said.
   The source said officials ``have no trouble at all'' with the
idea of cross-recognition under which South Korea would be formally
recognized by North Korea's allies, China and the Soviet Union,
while the United States, Japan and other friends of South Korea
would recognize North Korea.
   He did not comment, however, on Roh's proposal to stage a peace
conference among the United States, the Soviet Union, China, Japan
and the two Koreas.
   North Korea has staunchly resisted the kind of cross-recognition
used for more than a decade with East and West Germany, on the
grounds that it would perpetuate division of the country.
</TEXT>
