<HEAD>Hirohito's Condition Grows Worse</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New material and editing throughout. No pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The condition of 87-year-old Emperor Hirohito
apparently grew worse early Wednesday after he vomited blood in a
health crisis that began a month ago.
   Palace spokesman Kenji Maeda said, however, that the emperor was
resting and there was no need for concern, Kyodo News Service
reported.
   The palace said Hirohito coughed up a small amount of blood
around midnight Tuesday, followed by a discharge of blood from his
bowels, and that doctors administered .42 pints in blood
transfusions.
   Hirohito has discharged blood intermittently since Sept. 19,
when an intestinal hemorrhage caused him to vomit a substantial
amount of blood and confined him to intensive care. In one month he
has received 20.2 pints in transfusions, according to news reports.
   Persistent news media reports have said Hirohito has cancer in
the area of his upper intestine. The palace has refused to comment
and asked news organizations to refrain from speculation that could
dishearten the emperor.
   Hirohito's pulse was rising slowly and reached 101 by Wednesday
morning, up from 94 a day earlier. He ran a slight fever of 99.1
degrees, Maeda told a regular news briefing. Hirohito's normal
temperature is about 95.9.
   Court physicians have unsuccessfully tried to combat his anemia
with blood transfusions. In recent days they have allowed the
world's oldest living monarch to take a few spoonfuls of weak
porridge, and acknowledged he is losing strength because his
intravenous feedings cannot supply enough nutrients.
</TEXT>
