<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LostBoat     10-18 0407</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lost Boat,0419</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Boat That Helped Adrift Family Rescued</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINE DONNELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Coast Guard on Tuesday rescued two men on a
sailboat who gave food and water to a starving family adrift in the
Pacific, then ran into trouble themselves, a spokesman said.
   The family was rescued last Thursday.
   The men aboard the Early Light called the Coast Guard for help
Monday, saying their boat was disabled about 60 miles northwest of
the Hawaiian island of Maui, said Coast Guard spokesman Scott
Hartvigsen.
   A C-130 search plane found the 33-foot vessel and directed the
cutter Cape Cross to the boat, Hartvigsen said. The Cape Cross
reached the men around noon.
   Hartvigsen said the Early Light would be towed to Maui. The men,
who were reported in good health, and their craft were expected to
reach the island late Wednesday, 34 days after they left California.
   When the men made their distress call, they said they had gone a
day without food and water and that a storm had broken the boat's
boom and torn its mainsail, Hartvigsen said.
   ``They gave away most of their food and water, so they were in
trouble out there,'' he said. ``But they were in radio contact with
the Coast Guard, so they knew they'd be rescued. It was just a
matter of when.''
   The men on Oct. 7 gave food, water and fishing gear to a San
Diego man and his five sons who were adrift on the Pacific Ocean
for 33 days. The Navy rescued the six Thursday 550 miles northeast
of Honolulu on Thursday.
   Clint Fleishour and his five sons were lifted off their disabled
sailboat, Paloma, after eight days without food and five days
without water.
   Fleishour said Tuesday that the crew of the Early Light, whom he
knew only as John and ``Stretch,'' gave him and his sons five
gallons of water, a fish and some fishing equipment.
   The two boats planned to sail together, but the Early Light
headed in a more westerly direction, he said.
   ``They weren't in any trouble at all when we saw them,''
Fleishour said. ``They said they had 100 gallons of water and lots
of groceries on board. They seemed like they were in really good
shape.''
   Although the Coast Guard released few details about the Early
Light, Fleishour said the crew told him they were headed from Santa
Barbara, Calif., for Maui.
</TEXT>
