<1ST_LINE>a a AM-ReligionToday Adv21   10-18 0841</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Religion Today, Adv 21,0866</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv21</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri AMs, Oct. 21, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Religious Right Program Falters But Is Now Political Staple</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the twilight of President Reagan's
administration, he hasn't pulled off most of his social programs
dear to the religious right, but he's made them practically a
political staple.
   They simmer in the current national campaign, and religious
scholars say Reagan has excelled at using his office as a ``bully
pulpit'' for his upbeat-style sermonizing.
   ``The Reagan years have been good for public theology'' despite
its often thin quality, writes church historian Martin Marty.
``Religion, which had seemed a private affair in the 1970s, went
public again in the l980s.''
   Marty of the University of Chicago notes that in Reagan's
presidency, growing attention has centered on such issues as
values, virtue, education, moral formation, sexuality, family life,
abortion and euthanasia.
   Rabbi A. James Rudin of the American Jewish Committee writes in
the Christian Century that Reagan ``is clearly the dominant
American theologian of the l980s.''
   But the content, he adds, is ``only sparkling optimisim _
theological Perrier.''
   While Reagan has not achieved most of his social agenda, such as
banning abortion, reinstating prayers in schools and providing tax
credits for children in private schools, he's still preaching them.
   They're also backed by his party's candidate to succeed him,
George Bush. Says Reagan:
   ``Although we Americans have done much to put our national life
back on the firm foundation of traditional values, there is still a
great deal to be done.''
   He told a summer Youth for Christ rally in Washington that ``as
a nation we must embrace our faith, for as long as we endeavor to
do good...we will find our strength, our hope and our true
happiness in prayer and the Lord's will.''
   Although Reagan rarely attends church himself, he strikes his
vintage religious chords. He told the youths:
   ``I would like someday to entertain an atheist at dinner and
serve the most gourmet, perfect dinner that has ever been served,
and then at the end of the meal, ask that atheist if he believes
there's a cook.''
   He said 4,000 abortions a day ``must stop,'' and he said Vice
President Bush ``believes with me'' about it. ``Abortion is the
taking of a human life.''
   ``So far, we haven't succeeded in persusading the Congress to
enact legislation that would once again permit voluntary prayer in
America's schools,'' he said. ``But I'm convinced that, one day
soon, such a measure will be passed.''
   In Reagan's term, Congress has repeatedly rejected measures to
authorize school prayers, give tax breaks for for private school
tuition or to amend the constitution to overturn the Supreme Court
decision allowing abortion.
   Some leaders of the religious right, which had strongly backed
Reagan for the presidency, have criticized him as not pushing hard
enough for the measures, suggesting he gave them only lip service.
   While the Christian right emerged as a political force in the
1980s, it is losing ``influence on the national level,'' says
historian Leo Ribuffo of George Washington University.
   However, historian Marty advices against underestimating it,
saying it ``did get people talking about the family and personal
values.''
   He says it has gained legitimacy by adding ``scores of causes''
to its prime anti-abortion cause, and also has overcome objections
to its involvement in politics.
   ``By and large the New Christian Right won its point'' _ that it
had a legitimate voice in politics, Marty writes in Context, his
journal of commentary on religion and culture.
   But he says the Christian rightists ``did not win much'' in the
Reagan years. ``They wanted less government and they got more; they
wanted less debt and ended up with the greatest ever; they wanted
dismantled social welfare programs and got some, but it was
selective.''
   However, Reagan asserted a ``major victory'' in the Supreme
Court's recent upholding of an act allowing grants to religious
groups to counsel the young against promiscuity.
   On that subject, he offered his advice to 9000 youths at their
Congress on Evangelism, saying ``it's important for you not to pay
any attention at all to all those who say that promiscuity is
somehow stylish or rewarding.''
   He said ``the right thing to do is to wait for that one special
person.'' To be true in marriage, he said, ``you can start being
true to that one special person beginning now.''
   Reagan also took credit for the Equal Rights Act, giving
religious groups the same right to meet after school the same as
other clubs. However, schools are still refusing to do so,
challenging the law in court.
   Recalling a story of the country's origins, Reagan played one of
his frequent themes:
   ``If Benjamin Franklin rose to invoke the Almighty as the
Constitution itself was being drafted _ if the Congress of the
United States opens each day with prayer _ then isn't it time we
let God back into the classroom?''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri AMs, Oct. 21</NOTE>
<TEXT>
