<1ST_LINE>a i AM-IslamicTelevision Adv24   10-18 0566</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Islamic Television, Adv 24,0585</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv24</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs, Oct. 24, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Television Serves as Islamic Moral Guardian</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Viewers may tire of a mullah chanting
from the Moslem holy book, but there is no alternative when he's
on. The government runs television in Pakistan and uses it as a
watchdog of Islamic morality.
   ``Pakistan television has prepared interesting programs
reflecting Islamic social values for the October-to-December
quarter,'' program director Zaheer Bhatti told the government news
agency.
   In an interview with The Associated Press, he said that should
not be interpreted as fundamentalist or reactionary.
   Bhatti dismissed the self-righteous view of Western television
as a sinkhole of promiscuity, alcoholism and drug addiction, but
also said there are basic differences between East and West, Moslem
and non-Moslem.
   ``We want to make (the young) aware of the positive values in
our society,'' he said. ``We don't see the past of any society as a
separate entity. It is a progression and we say we are a
progressive religion.''
   Television is a tool for preserving Pakistani culture, Bhatti
said, and mentioned such things as keeping traditional dress from
being supplanted by T-shirts, jeans and three-piece suits.
   Weekly television series display the cultures of Pakistan's five
provinces. Love is a common theme, with the young in search of love
often pitted against an older generation clinging to the tradition
of arranged marriages.
   ``We don't believe in sermonizing through the box,'' Bhatti
said. ``We do not talk down to people; we talk to people.''
   A series called ``Waris'' was a favorite of the late President
Mohammed Zia ul-Haq.
   It was set in the interior of Punjab province and told of a
powerful, dictatorial landowner who clashed with his sons and
tenants.
   Some Pakistanis said the landlord was intended as a portrayal of
former Prime Minister Zulfikar Ali Bhutto, who was hanged in 1979,
two years after Gen. Zia overthrew him in a mlitary coup.
   Bhutto's daughter Benazir now leads the Pakistan People's Party,
which was founded by her father and is the main political
opposition.
   About two months before his death in a plane crash Aug. 17, Zia
announced that Pakistan would adopt Islamic law.
   Women protested in the streets, feeling their hard-won gains
would slip away, and whether to implement Islamic law now will be
left to the government organized after elections Nov. 16.
   Subtle changes began occuring on Pakistan television after Zia's
pronouncement and continued after his death.
   Fewer women were seen on the tube, particularly in commercials,
and more covered their heads. Women anchoring the evening news wore
headscarves.
   Bhatti acknowledged the number of women in commercials has been
reduced.
   Glamorous women in skin-tight dresses slipping into the latest
car never were part of Pakistani television, but Bhatti said even
tamer depictions of women to sell products is being reduced.
   If a product is for use by either men or women, a man will
appear in the ommercial, he said, and ``the unnecessary use of
females to sell products'' will be stopped.
   Foreign programs will continue to appear because Pakistan's
television industry cannot produce enough programs to fill the
time, but officials are selective, he said.
   Dramas are included, but the emphasis is on such educational and
informative programs as documentaries by Jacques Cousteau and the
National Geographic Society.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, Oct. 24</NOTE>
</DOC>
