<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-88 1325EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s e BC-APN--TheaterWeek ADV30-1stLd-Writethru b</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Theater Week, ADV 30-1st Ld-Writethru, b0716,0944</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv30</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Oct. 30</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf from end ``After ...'' to CORRECT that it was
Crawford's final performance, not final performance of show.</NOTE>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&w
photo.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Is there life after ``The Phantom of the Opera''
for Michael Crawford?
   Emphatically ``yes'' says the man who conquered Broadway last
season, carting off every theater award in sight, including a Tony.
Now Crawford has left the cast of the New York production of
``Phantom,'' but even his departure from the hit musical was
spectacular.
   After missing more than a week because of a virus, the star
returned Oct. 8 for one final performance. During curtain calls,
the entire cast showered Crawford with red roses. They were
assisted by members of the audience, some of them running down the
aisles of the Majestic Theater to toss flowers on the stage.
   An emotional Crawford spoke to the theatergoers, choking on what
he said was the same thing he told his mother on his 21st birthday.
   ``I'd like to thank you for having me,'' he told the cheering
crowd.
   ``You're perfection,'' yelled one enthusiastic woman.
   But Crawford has not hung up his ``Phantom'' mask and put away
his makeup for good. The actor plans to do at least a nine-month
engagement, beginning next May, in the Los Angeles company of
``Phantom.'' It's the best possible audition for the movies.
   ``The film people are there, and they'd see it,'' he says. ``I
have got very strong interest and offers from two studios. If I'm
in Los Angeles, I can work on development as it is happening.''
   Crawford has made movies before. Film buffs know him from ``The
Knack,'' ``A Funny Thing Happened on the Way to the Forum,''
``Hello, Dolly!'' and ``How I Won the War.'' But this is the first
time a movie will be planned around him. What a difference a hit
musical can make to a career.
   ``I don't think I was known over here at all,'' Crawford says.
In England, he was a star. He appeared in several hit British
television series and had done three big musicals in London's West
End _ ``Billy,'' ``Flowers for Algernon'' and ``Barnum.'' The last
show, an American musical, had an even longer run in England than
it did in the United States.
   ``It ran so long we had births and deaths in the audience,''
Crawford says. ``People died, and we had a woman give birth once.
It was like life aboard a 747 on an around-the-world trip.''
   ``Phantom'' _ with the help of exposure on national television
shows such as ``West 57th Street'' _ has made his face familiar to
fans in the United States.
   ``When I first opened in `Phantom' in New York even the stage
managers would ask, `Are you Michael Crawford?,''' he says. Before
he left the show, there were crowds of 50 to 60 people waiting each
night at the stage door to see him.
   And the letters never stopped coming. Every day he would receive
more than 100 letters, some from overseas and addressed simply,
``Michael Crawford, Broadway, U.S.A.''
   Crawford's most dedicated followers have been an informal group
of Britishers called the OGRES, which stands for Opera Ghosts
Return Enthusiasts. Many of them came to New York for his final
Broadway appearance. Some had been here twice before, unfurling
banners down the Majestic alleyway that proclaimed ``Bring Him
Home.''
   ``There are about 25 of them and they won't let anyone else
join,'' he says. ``They are very exclusive. And if anyone
misbehaves, they are out. Or if they bother me. They don't like to
annoy me. They are very good to me.''
   Crawford also has widened his appeal with his first solo
recording, ``Songs From the Stage and Screen'' that he made before
he opened ``Phantom'' in New York.
   ``They have sold over 200,000 copies on the East Coast, so it's
on its way to gold,'' he says. ``And I'm very pleased. There was a
terrific amount of care gone into that record.''
   The album, which includes a medley of songs from ``West Side
Story'' and such Broadway classics as ``If I Loved You,''
``Memory'' and ``You'll Never Walk Alone,'' has sold well all over
the world.
   ``It's triple platinum in New Zealand, which means it has sold
20,000 copies,'' Crawford says. ``Even the sheep are buying it.''
   Crawford will go back into the recording studio early next year
in London to record a second album, this time a collection of love
songs. He hopes to include ``Music of the Night,'' his big number
from ``Phantom,'' if composer Andrew Lloyd Webber grants his
permission.
   The performer also is considering several new Broadway musicals,
although none he can talk about. ``But it's nice that I've been
asked,'' he says. ``And one of them is of particular interest to
me.''
   After his final performance in ``Phantom,'' a role now being
played by Timothy Nolen, Crawford flew to Australia to make a
documentary film for a British charity. Then he may begin to relax
for a few weeks.
   Crawford admits he'll miss the hoopla that accompanied his
10-month ``Phantom'' run in New York, although there are tradeoffs.
   ``I'll be glad to have it quiet after all that attention,'' he
says. ``You need that quiet whenever you have finished a show that
is an event.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Oct. 16</NOTE>
