<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   10-18 0514</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0537</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Philip Morris Cos. Inc. launched an $11 billion
cash tender offer for Kraft Inc., a bid that would be the second
biggest corporate acquisition in U.S. history if it succeeds.
   The only deal bigger was the $13.4 billion purchase of Gulf
Corp. in 1984 by Standard Oil Co. of California, which later
changed its name to Chevron Corp.
   Philip Morris said it had no plans to sell off any parts of
Kraft to finance the deal. The offer of $90 a share in cash,
announced Monday, was 51 percent above Kraft's current stock price.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Financier Carl C. Icahn met with leaders of
ailing Eastern Airlines' unions about a joint takeover of Eastern.
   But sources close to the talks said Monday the meetings this
weekend adjourned after the two sides failed to agree on an offer
for the airline.
   Icahn, the chairman of Trans World Airlines Inc., was seeking
wage concessions from the Eastern unions that union leaders
considered too severe, according to the sources, who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. lost a round in its
fight against civil fraud charges when a senior judge rejected the
Wall Street giant's motion that he quit the case.
   In an angrily worded opinion, U.S. District Judge Milton Pollack
also denied Drexel motions to stop him from ruling on other cases
involving the firm and convicted insider trader Ivan Boesky.
   Pollack, a respected 82-year-old jurist who has been presiding
over most Boesky-related litigation for more than a year, deemed
the defense strategy to remove him on grounds of prejudice a
ludicrous, time-wasting ploy.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cardinal Acquisition Corp. sweetened its tender
offer for Interco Inc., raising its hostile bid for the furniture
and apparel manufacturer to $2.84 billion.
   Interco, which rejected several earlier Cardinal offers and
announced plans to restructure, had no comment Monday on the latest
bid.
   Cardinal, led by Steven and Mitchell Rales of Washington, D.C,
offered $74 a share in cash for each of Interco's 38.4 million
outstanding shares.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MOBILE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Delchamps Inc. has filed a federal lawsuit
to block a $210 million hostile takeover of the company by the
Great Atlantic & Pacific Tea Co.
   The suit was filed Monday in U.S. District Court in Mobile.
Delchamps Chairman A. F. Delchamps Jr. said Delchamps' board also
rejected the $30-a-share offer as ``cheap.''
   This marks the third time in two years that Delchamps has fought
off an offer from A&P.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Delaware judge refused to grant British
publisher Robert Maxwell's request for an order against a key
element in Macmillan Inc.'s buyout agreement with a rival suitor.
   Monday's ruling could further complicate Maxwell's efforts to
acquire the publishing and information services giant, which
already agreed to a $2.5 billion buyout bid from a group led by the
investment firm Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co. and including
Macmillan senior management.
   Maxwell has offered $2.51 billion for Macmillan under certain
conditions.
</TEXT>
