<1ST_LINE>r f PM-EconomyRdp     10-18 0449</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp,0464</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Evidence of Slowing Economy Lifts Stock Market</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Will be updated with Commerce Department report on personal
income for the second quarter; Report is due at 9 a.m. EDT</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market has gotten a modest boost from new government
reports pointing to an economic slowdown.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 7.29 points Monday
to 2,140.47.
   The Commerce Department reported that goods held on shelves and
backlots in August rose 0.8 percent to $733.7 billion, following a
0.7 percent gain in July. It was the 20th consecutive monthly
increase.
   Rising inventories can be a sign of economic sluggishness as
manufacturers order production cuts and layoffs while goods in
reserve are sold off.
   In another government report, the Federal Reserve Board said the
overall operating rate last month at U.S. factories, mines and
utilities fell to 83.6 percent of capacity, down 0.2 percentage
point from August.
   The strain on the nation's industrial capacity eased for the
first time in seven months as utilities scaled back after the
summer heat wave, the Fed said.
   The latest government reports also supported bond prices,
driving interest rates lower. The yield on the Treasury's closely
watched 30-year bond fell to 8.86 percent from 8.90 percent late
Friday.
   In foreign-exchange trading, the dollar rose against most major
currencies after reports of intervention by the Bank of Japan
lifted it from its lows of the day. The U.S. currency finished in
New York at around 127.07 Japanese yen, up from 126.70 yen late
Friday.
   As part of its business inventories report, the Commerce
Department said August sales totaled $487.7 billion, up a brisk 1.1
percent from July, when the gain was a slight 0.1 percent. It was
the ninth increase in a row.
   In other economic developments Monday:
   _A Harvard Business Review report concluded that an entrenched
budget deficit and fundamental policy flaws have destabilized the
nation's economy, and the next president will have to take major
steps to turn it around.
   _The oil ministers of the six-nation Gulf Cooperation Council
said they supported an increase in OPEC's output quotas as a way to
try to stabilize prices.
   Analysts said stock traders took a generally upbeat view of the
current state of the economy, believing that growth has slowed of
late to a steady, sustainable pace.
   But inflation worries haven't been entirely snuffed out on Wall
Street, and brokers said investors were looking ahead warily to
Friday's scheduled report on the consumer price index for September.
   Furthermore, just about all market-watchers agree, investors are
likely to be leery of stocks all week with the anniversary
Wednesday of last fall's crash, and all the attendant publicity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881018-0233 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-88 0117EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     10-18 0319</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures prices continue to climb, but
analysts warn that trading will be volatile while OPEC members hold
a series of meetings in hopes of lowering crude oil production.
   The November contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
grade of U.S. crude, rose 29 cents Monday to close at $15.21 a
42-gallon barrel on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   Subsequent contract months settled about 22 cents a barrel
higher. Analysts said the November contract had additional strength
because of tight supplies.
   Refined products traded on the exchange followed a similar
pattern, with near-term contracts posting the largest gains. The
November contract for wholesale unleaded gasoline picked up 1.34
cents to settle at 46.76 cents a gallon, while the November
contract for home heating oil rose 0.67 cent to 43.88 cents a
gallon.
   Prices zigzagged Monday before rising amid optimism that the
OPEC meetings could end the cartel's overproduction problems.
   ``People are expecting a lot of volatility in the market for the
next few weeks,'' said Jim Fiedler, a trader with E.D.&F. Man
International Futures Inc. ``The market still looks strong, but
people are afraid it's overbought and will run out of good news to
keep it up.''
   Oil prices fell below $12.30 two weeks ago because of
overproduction by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries, then began to climb as meetings to discuss the situation
approached.
   This past weekend, oil ministers of the six-nation Gulf
Cooperation Council met and proposed a production ceiling of 18.5
million to 19 million barrels a day for the 13 OPEC members.
   The GCC proposal is expected to be presented to OPEC's
committees on strategy and pricing, which are meeting Thursday in
Madrid, Spain. OPEC also has a ministerial conference scheduled for
Nov. 21.
   ``It's going to be meeting, meeting, meeting, and that's going
to keep the market in an uproar,'' Fiedler said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881018-0234 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-88 0119EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Drexel Bjt   10-18 0710</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drexel, Bjt,0736</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Firm Says It Will Appeal In Effort Remove Judge From Fraud Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. will appeal a
judge's refusal to quit presiding over the government's massive
civil-fraud suit against the firm, raising the prospect of more
delays and pretrial theatrics in a case that already has acquired
celebrity status in Manhattan federal court.
   Although U.S. District Judge Milton Pollack's angry rejection
Monday of Drexel's move to disqualify him was seen outwardly as a
setback for the Wall Street giant, some attorneys following the
courtroom battle saw it as a plus for the defense, which is trying
to portray Drexel as a victim of prejudice.
   ``You can't lose,'' said one attorney, who spoke on condition he
not be identified. ``This effort has to be for the purpose of
creating the picture that Drexel is a fine company mistreated by
the courts.''
   Pollack denied Drexel motions to stop him from ruling on its
case as well as in other cases involving the firm and Ivan Boesky,
the imprisoned inside trader who implicated Drexel and others in
alleged wrongdoing when he was exposed nearly two years ago.
   Pollack, a respected 82-year-old jurist who has been presiding
over most Boesky-related litigation for more than a year, deemed
the defense strategy to remove him a ludicrous, time-wasting ploy.
   His opinion seemed to further raise the level of antagonism
between Drexel lawyers and the judge since the Securities and
Exchange Commission filed its wide-ranging fraud suit against the
firm and other defendants last month.
   Pollack already has chastised several defense lawyers for their
conduct in the case and referred two of them to the chief judge of
Manhattan federal court for possible disciplinary sanctions.
   A raucous hearing last week on defense efforts to disqualify
Pollack on grounds of possible bias featured emotional exchanges
between him and Drexel attorneys, who are among the most highly
paid in the country. That session drew a packed audience, unusual
in securities law cases.
   SEC lawyers applauded Pollack's opinion Monday and expressed
eagerness to proceed. Private attorneys suing Drexel and Boesky
also welcomed the ruling.
   Defense attorneys did not return telephone calls for comment.
But Drexel spokesman Steven Anreder said in a statement: ``Our
attorneys had a professional obligation to bring this issue before
the court. Since it is their considered view that, based on the
facts in the motion, Judge Pollack's position is incorrect, the
matter will be placed before the 2nd Circuit Court of Appeals.''
   Drexel claims Pollack has a conflict of interest because his
wife, Moselle, stands to gain $30 million from the sale of her
stock in Palais Royal Inc., a Houston-based concern going private
in a transaction that indirectly involves Drexel financing.
   Although Mrs. Pollack's financial interest would make it appear
that Pollack is biased in Drexel's favor, defense lawyers had
argued they wanted a judge whose impartiality could not possibly be
questioned by the public.
   ``There is no financial or business connection, or other
relationship between Mrs. Pollack and Drexel,'' the judge wrote.
   ``There is simply no reasonable basis for doubting the court's
impartiality in this case by reason of the Palais Royal stock sale;
no facts, no rational basis, have been supplied.''
   Pollack wrote that Drexel's motion seemed so far-fetched ``as to
be ludicrous and hardly a basis for a judge to step aside.''
   Privately, many lawyers have speculated the Drexel defense wants
another judge because of Pollack's reputation as a tough,
no-nonsense securities-law expert tending to side with the
government in fraud cases.
   Legal experts familiar with courtroom strategies to disqualify
judges doubted the Drexel effort to remove Pollack would prevail.
   ``It is fairly common to use a motion to disqualify as sort of a
diversion,'' said Arthur Miller, a professor at Harvard Law School.
   ``Sometimes the strategy is serious, when there are reasons to
fear the judge. Sometimes the motion is made because you don't like
the judge,'' Miller said. ``It generally fails, miserably.''
   The SEC sued Drexel and four key employees of the firm Sept. 7
alleging they secretly plotted with Boesky to manipulate stock,
profit on inside information about corporate takeovers, cheat
clients and engage in other frauds. The defendants have denied the
charges.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
