<2ND_LINE>PM-Kraft-Markets,0206</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Light Trading in Philip Morris And Kraft Stocks</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Kraft-Morris</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wall Street was kept in the dark, as the law
requires, before Philip Morris Companies Inc. announced its $11
billion bid for Kraft Inc.
   The best evidence that there were no widespread leaks of the
surprise takeover bid late Monday is that trading in both stocks
was about average and there were no big price changes. The offer
was announced after the close of trading.
   Small amounts of insider trading would not affect volumes or
prices, but a rumor that traveled far quickly would have pushed
Kraft's stock price toward Philip Morris's offer of $90 a share,
and trading would have been heavy.
   In consolidated New York Stock Exchange trading Monday, Kraft
stock rose 62{ cents a share to $60.12{. Philip Morris stock rose
$1.37{ a share to $100.
   Trading in Kraft was 123,100 shares, less than the daily average
volume of 232,900 shares so far this month and 233,548 shares so
far this year.
   Trading in Philip Morris was 691,800 shares, slightly above the
daily average of 558,790 shares so far this month and 626,242
shares so far this year.
</TEXT>
