<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Interco Bjt   10-18 0433</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Interco, Bjt,0449</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rales Brothers Increase Interco Bid to $2.84 Billion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In their latest attempt to win over Interco Inc.
shareholders, the Rales brothers sweetened their tender offer for
the furniture and apparel maker to $2.84 billion.
   Through Cardinal Acquisition Corp., the Washington-based sibling
team of Steven and Mitchell Rales on Monday offered $74 a share in
cash for each of Interco's 38.4 million outstanding shares.
   The offer tops the tender offer the duo launched in August by $4
a share, but also represents the fourth time the Rales brothers
have bid for the St. Louis-based company.
   Interco, which rejected the earlier Rales offers and instead
unveiled a restructuring plan, had no immediate comment on the
latest bid, said company spokesman Carter Dunkin.
   The Rales brothers made their first overtures to Interco's
management in July, offering to acquire the company for $64 a
share. In August, the group launched a tender offer at $70 a share,
which Interco immediately rejected.
   On Sept. 20, the brothers again were rebuffed after proposing a
friendly merger at $72-a-share that was conditioned on the company
providing them with certain confidential information.
   The sweetened tender offer was announced shortly before the
close of trading on the New York Stock Exchange. Interco's stock
closed at $71.50 a share, up $1.62{ but still below Cardinal's
latest offer.
   Cardinal said the offer would remain open until midnight Oct.
31, unless extended. However, last week, a federal appeals court in
Philadelphia ordered the brothers to keep their bid open pending a
further ruling in litigation between Cardinal and Interco over the
tender offer.
   Interco has filed suit against Cardinal, charging it violated
federal regulations by failing to disclose that the investment firm
Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. was a co-bidder.
   Interco also charged that the proposed takeover violates federal
regulations by being too highly leveraged.
   At the time Interco rejected the Rales group's $72-a-share bid,
the company unveiled a $2.8 billion restructuring and
recapitalization program that Interco said could include a sale of
its Ethan Allen furniture unit and other businesses.
   Interco's other products include Broyhill furniture, London Fog
rainwear and Florsheim and Converse shoes.
   The restructuring also includes payment of a special dividend of
$25 in cash and securities per share.
   Interco Chairman Harvey Saligman said the restructuring plan was
worth $76 a share.
   The Raleses have insisted on a chance to bid on any assets
Interco might put up for sale and warned of ``unfortunate
consequences'' _ possibly legal action or a shareholder proxy fight
_ if they are not consulted before any assets are sold.
</TEXT>
