<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Delchamps-A&P     10-18 0368</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Delchamps-A&P,0381</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Delchamps Files Suit to Block Hostile A&P Takeover</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOBILE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Delchamps Inc. executives, saying they won't
be ``beaten, bought or buried,'' filed a lawsuit to halt a hostile
takeover of the Alabama-based grocery chain by A&P.
   The Great Atlantic & Pacific Tea Co. has offered $30 a share, or
$210 million for Delchamps, which operates supermarkets in Alabama,
Florida, Louisiana and Mississippi. The latest offer marks the
third time in two years that A&P has bid for the company.
   In announcing the suit filed Monday in U.S. District Court at
Mobile, Delchamps Chairman A. F. Delchamps Jr. called the A&P offer
``cheap.''
   The lawsuit accused A&P and others of failing to disclose
potential violations of antitrust laws and failure to reveal an
alleged plan to financially cripple Delchamps even if it fails to
buy the company.
   Delchamps said A&P's motive was to either purchase the firm ``at
a cheap price and proceed with its plan to achieve dominance in the
Gulf Coast retail stores market'' or cause the firm to suffer high
legal bills and induce a leverage buyout that would weaken
Delchamps as a competitor.
   ``A&P has not been able to compete with us effectively in the
marketplace, so it has obviously decided, `If you can't beat them,
buy them or bury them with investment bankers and lawyers.' We
don't intend to be beaten, bought or buried,'' Delchamps said.
   A&P spokesman Michael Rourke could not be reached for comment
Monday.
   Delchamps operates 102 grocery stores and six liquor stores.
A&P, headquartered in Montvale, N.J., is 52 percent owned by the
Tengelmann Group of West Germany.
   A&P made its first offer for Delchamps in October 1986, another
in October 1987 and another this month. Between the first and last
attempts, the offering price has risen from $23 to $30 a share.
   Delchamps' stock was trading at $26.50 a share in the
over-the-counter market Monday afternoon, up 50 cents from Friday,
while A&P's stock was down 37{ cents at $46.62{ a share on the New
York Stock Exchange.
   Delchamps had sales of about $700 million last year. A&P had
sales of $9.6 billion in 1987, from its 1,170 stores in this
country and Canada.
</TEXT>
