<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Macmillan 1stLd-Writethru   10-18 0522</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Macmillan, 1st Ld-Writethru,0538</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chancery Judge Refuses To Rule Against Macmillan Lockup Provision</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: TOPS with 10 new grafs with Maxwell plans to appeal. Picks up
10th graf pvs, Macmillan agreed ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British publisher Robert Maxwell said today he
will appeal a Delaware judge's refusal to overturn a key element in
Macmillan Inc.'s buyout agreement with a rival suitor.
   Maxwell said he also planned to seek an order barring the
consummation of the rival group's tender offer for the publishing
and information services giant.
   Macmillan has agreed to a $2.5 billion buyout by the investment
firm Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co. and Macmillan senior management.
   Maxwell has offered $2.51 billion for Macmillan under certain
conditions, and both sides have tender offers out that are
scheduled to expire at 12:01 a.m. EDT Wednesday.
   On Monday, Jack B. Jacobs, a judge in Delaware Chancery Court in
Wilmington, Del., denied Maxwell's request for an injunction
against a ``lockup provision'' that Macmillan granted Kohlberg in
case its buyout offer failed.
   The provision gives the Kohlberg group the right to buy four of
Macmillan's businesses for $865 million should the merger fail to
materialize.
   Maxwell, who is making his bid through his Maxwell Communication
Corp., had argued that the provision was unfair and said he would
be willing to pay $900 million for the same units, which include
the Berlitz language centers, the directory division, the direct
marketing division and a division that publishes state legal codes.
   But Macmillan argued that the provision was needed to persuade
the Kohlberg group to raise its bid for the company.
   In today's statement, Maxwell Communication said it ``intends to
appeal the court's decision and will move today in the appropriate
courts for an injunction barring the consummation of KKR's tender
offer and barring Macmillan from entering into any transactions out
of the ordinary course of business pending that appeal.''
   When the company concluded an auction for itself late last
month, Maxwell offered $89 a share in cash for its 27.8 million
shares, while Kohlberg offered $90.05 a share in cash and
securities.
   Macmillan agreed to the Kohlberg offer, but Maxwell subsequently
raised his offer to $90.25 a share in cash.
   Jacobs said in his ruling that while ``the auction procedures
were deficient in several respects ... the evidence is not
sufficient to persuade the court that those infirmities were
responsible in a legal sense for Macmillan not receiving
(Maxwell's) highest bid before the auction gavel fell.''
   The judge did grant Maxwell's request for an injunction against
Macmillan's poison-pill defense, which could have been used to
dilute his stake in the company if he were to begin to accumulate
Macmillan stock.
   The judge said he granted the request on condition that Maxwell
proceed with his offer.
   Among Maxwell's options are to appeal the decision to a higher
court.
   He had conditioned his tender offer on, among other things, the
elimination of both the poison pill provision and the lockup
option. He had argued that if Kohlberg were allowed to buy the four
units, Macmillan would be left with a $250 million tax liability on
the sale.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
