<1ST_LINE>r f PM-GMBonuses     10-18 0171</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-GM Bonuses,0177</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GM's Pay-for-Performance Plan May Be Scrapped</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp.'s pay-for-performance
program for its salaried workers is under review because it
requires a ranking of non-union employees that some workers feel is
unfair, a spokeswoman says.
   Patricia Malloy said Monday a decision on a compensation plan
for salaried employees in 1989 has not been made. But she said the
company is reacting to changes in the program which resulted in
some employee concern that judgments about their performance
weren't fair.
   She said GM has used some form of a pay-for-performance plan for
its salaried employees for years.
   ``The problem with the modifications made last year was not so
much that it distinguished among employees as much as the
perception that some people were judged, in their minds,
unfairly,'' Malloy said.
   The rankings were created to determine how large a raise, if
any, GM's 114,000 salaried employees should receive. But workers
who learned of the rankings began grumbling that such information
should not be widely circulated.
</TEXT>
