<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0351</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened narrowly mixed
today on the Chicago Board of Trade, reflecting concerns about the
rain-slowed harvest and disappointment in the pace of U.S. wheat
exports.
   Soybeans opened a little stronger in reaction to the wet
Midwestern weather that has slowed harvesting and farmer selling of
both soybeans and corn, analysts said.
   ``The corn market is very quiet,'' said Dale Gustafson, an
analyst in Chicago with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. ``There
obviously is not much movement and harvesting has been slowed but
the demand side of the market has been slow at the same time.''
   Corn harvesting was 63 percent complete as of Sunday in the top
17 producing states while soybean harvesting was 90 percent
finished in the top 19 producing states, the Agriculture Department
said late Monday.
   Wheat futures prices retreated slightly amid disappointment over
the USDA's rejection of bids from Egypt and China for large
shipments of subsidized soft red wheat. But China did buy 110,000
metric tons of hard red wheat at a subsidized price, analysts said.
   In early trading, wheat was 1\ cents to 3\ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.27 a bushel; corn was
unchanged to { cent lower with December at $2.94{ a bushel; oats
were 1{ cents to 3 cents higher with December at $2.58 a bushel;
soybeans were unchanged to 2\ cents higher with November at $8.12{
a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were lower in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .12 cent to .62 cent lower with October at
72.67 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent to .57 cent lower
with October at 81.90 cents a pound; live hogs were .15 cent to .42
cent lower with October at 39.70 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .48 cent to .80 cent lower with February at 48.25 cents a
pound.
   Cattle futures settled higher on Monday while pork futures were
mixed.
</TEXT>
