<1ST_LINE>r f BC-HongKong-StockExchange     10-18 0218</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Hong Kong-Stock Exchange,0226</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Exchange Names New Chairman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new governing council of the Hong Kong
Stock Exchange on Tuesday named bank president Lee Quo-wei as it
chairman.
   It also announced the appointment of Francis Yuen as the
exchange's chief executive to succeed Robert Fell, who was
appointed to the post in the aftermath of last October's market
crash.
   Lee, head of Hang Seng Bank Ltd, was one of five nonbrokers
appointed to the 22-member council by the government from outside
the exchange's membership.
   Prior to his appointment, Yuen was managing director of Citicorp
Scrimgeour Vickers Hong Kong Ltd.
   The appointments completed a shakeup of the exchange's
management, transforming the council from a virtual private club of
local brokers into a more broadly representative body.
   The chanmges followed criticism of the closure of the market
during last October's global crash and a bribery scandal that has
resulted in the arrest of eight former exchange officials.
   Four seats in the new council are reserved for individual
members; four for officers of corporate brokerages; five for
independent representatives of the public, the investment community
and listed companies; and one for the chief executive. The
remaining seats are open to any members.
   Previously, the exchange was run by a 21-member general
committee comprised of individual brokers.
</TEXT>
