<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Pillsbury 3rdLd-Writethru   10-18 0554</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pillsbury, 3rd Ld-Writethru,0572</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Pillsbury Board Recommends Shareholders Reject Grand Met Bid</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS byline and INSERTS 4 new grafs after 7th graf pvs bgng,
`Now is ... to UPDATE with Smith news conference. Picks up 8th graf
pvs, Wall Street ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pillsbury Co.'s board of directors urged
stockholders today to reject Grand Metropolitan PLC's unsolicited
$5.23 billion bid for the food and restaurant company.
   The board described the $60-a-share offer as inadequate.
   Pillsbury said its board instructed management to work with the
company's financial and legal advisers to consider alternative
courses that would boost the price of the company's stock and
protect the best interests of the company and its shareholders.
   The company's stock was unchanged at $58.62{ a share in midday
trading on the New York Stock Exchange.
   Walter Montgomery, a spokesman for Grand Met, said the British
conglomerate had no immediate response to today's action by
Pillsbury board.
   In a letter sent to all Pillsbury shareholders, Philip L. Smith,
chairman and chief executive officer of Pillsbury, said, ``The
board believes that shareholders would realize greater value by
retaining their stake in Pillsbury.''
   ``Now is not an appropriate time to sell the company. Remaining
independent would be a superior alternative over the long term to
accepting the Grand Met offer,'' Smith added.
   At a news conference today, Smith said Pillsbury's options could
include selling the company to a third party, restructuring
Pillsbury's finances by selling some businesses or going ahead with
a leveraged buyout.
   He said Pillsbury will give shareholders a better idea of the
company's strategy before the deadline for tendering stock to Grand
Met expires.
   ``The offer made by Grand Met, $60 a share, is not adequate,''
Smith said. ``Greater values are available to the shareholder in
the long term.''
   Asked what he thought Pillsbury's chances were in defending
against a takeover bid by a well-heeled suitor, Smith said, ``It
ain't over 'til it's over.''
   Wall Street analysts had speculated Monday that Pillsbury would
reject Grand Metropolitan's offer, which was made Oct. 4, and
possibly announce a dividend-yielding restructuring in an effort to
remain independent or possibly attract a better offer from Grand
Metropolitan.
   There also was speculation that a European ``white knight,''
possibly Britain's Unilever PLC, might emerge as a friendly merger
partner.
   But Smith said Pillsbury was not currently up for sale and that
``remaining independent would be a superior alternative over the
long term to accepting the Grand Met offer.''
   In his letter to shareholders, Smith said, ``The board found
that Grand Met's offer failed to reflect the values currently being
developed at Pillsbury and its subsidiaries under programs that are
in the process of being implemented.''
   Those programs include ``reinvesting'' in the company's core
businesses, he said.
   Pillsbury is a diversified international food company with
operations in packaged consumer foods, including Green Giant and
Haagen Dazs products, and restaurants.
   Among its restuarants are Burger King, Steak and Ale and
Bennigan's.
   The Grand Met bid is one of two takeover attempts in among
giants in the food industry that are currently under way. On
Monday, Philip Morris Cos. announced a $11 billion bid for Kraft
Inc. that would make it the world's largest maker of consumer
goods. Like Pillsbury, Kraft indicated it might fight the takeover.
</TEXT>
