<2ND_LINE>BC-Chevron Well,0281</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chevron Plans Well In Beaufort Sea</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chevron Co. USA says it plans to drill
an exploratory oil and gas well this winter from an ice island in
the Beaufort Sea.
   Construction of the island and an ice road connecting it to
shore is expected to begin in mid-December, a U.S. Army Corps of
Engineers permit application said.
   Tom Cook, Chevron's exploration manager, said Monday that
drilling of the Karluk prospect would be finished by May 1 to allow
removal of all equipment before breakup.
   The prospect is about eight miles east of the Endicott oil field
operated by the Standard Alaska Production Co. It is inside the
barrier islands, on a state lease Chevron acquired in 1979 in the
joint state-federal Beaufort Sea lease sale.
   Chevron has been interested in the area for quite awhile, Cook
said. He said the company drilled a well on Jeanette Island, about
four mile north of the new prospect, several years ago.
   The well will be Chevron's first since 1986, when it teamed with
Standard on the only well drilled to date in the coastal plain of
the nearby Arctic National Wildlife Refuge. Cook said there is no
particular reason the company has planned the well for this winter,
other than that it is a prospect Chevron identified some time ago.
   State oil and gas officials said the 10-year lease on the
prospect is about to expire and speculated that might be Chevron's
primary reason for drilling this year.
   The company is planning an ice island that is about 1,000 feet
in diameter and about 50 feet thick.
</TEXT>
