<1ST_LINE>r f BC-S&N-Elders     10-18 0263</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-S&N-Elders,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brewer's Message In a Bottle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scottish & Newcastle Breweries PLC said Tuesday it
will paste its labels upside down on 36 million bottles of its
Newcastle Brown Ale to protest an Australian takeover bid.
   A special ``hands off'' message _ yet to be written _ will be
pasted onto the back of 24 million of those bottles, brewery
spokesman Jim Merrington said. ``We sell Newcastle Brown to 30
different countries so we expect this message will soon find its
way to Australia,'' said Merrington, head of the brewery's public
affairs department.
   Australian brewing company Elders IXL Ltd. launched a takeover
bid Monday for the Scottish-based beverage company, valuing it at
$2.8 billion.
   Scottish & Newcastle promptly rejected the offer, calling it
``totally unwelcome and unacceptable.''
   Merrington said, ``The aim of the upside down labels is to
demonstrate a thumbs down to Elders.''
   Three million of the bottles will be distributed nationally by
the end of the week and another nine million by the end of the
month, he said.
   Merrington said the takeover proposal should be referred to the
government's Monopolies and Merger Commission.
   He noted that S&N's profit of $197 million in its latest fiscal
year was up 25 percent over the previous year. The company employs
24,000 workers.
   Scottish & Newcastle rejected a merger proposal from Elders last
summer.
   Elders, through its Courage Holdings PLC subsidiary, is offering
$6.96 a share in cash for Scottish brewery.
   The Australian company, which makes the popular Fosters brand
lager, already owns 9.65 percent of Scottish & Newcastle's stock.
</TEXT>
