<HEAD>Judge Orders Divestiture in Plastics Merger</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Occidental Petroleum Co. was ordered Tuesday
to sell Tenneco Polymers Inc., after an administrative law judge
ruled that the 1986 acquisition of the company reduced competition
in the production of materials needed to make plastics.
   The ruling by Judge Thomas F. Howder upheld a 1986 complaint by
the Federal Trade Commission, which had challenged Occidental's $70
million takeover of the polymer company.
   The acquisition substantially reduced competition in the
production of three types of polyvinyl chloride resin, Howder
concluded.
   The judge ordered Occidental to divest Tenneco Polymers within
12 months to a buyer that the commission must approve.
</TEXT>
