<DOCNO> AP881018-0267 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-88 2332EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f BC-World-Steel     10-18 0192</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-World-Steel,0199</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Steel Output Of Major Producers Up 8.7 Percent In September</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The output of crude steel by producers
in the non-Communist world rose 8.7 percent in September to 39.549
million metric tons from 36.384 million tons a year earlier, the
International Iron and Steel Institute said Tuesday.
   The European Economic Community registered the sharpest increase
with output rising 12.7 percent to 11.672 million tons in September
from 10.36 million tons in the year-earlier month.
   Japan's production rose in the same time period by 7.8 percent
to 8.638 million tons from 8.01 million tons while U.S. production
climbed 7.4 percent to 7.5 million tons from 6.98 million tons.
   For the first nine months of 1988, the output of crude steel by
the non-Communist nations rose 10.6 percent to 351.368 million tons
from 317.59 million tons in the year-earlier period.
   Steel producers in the institute's monthly survey come from 32
countries and account for 59 percent of 1987 world production and
for 97 percent of world output excluding the Soviet Union and other
countries in the Council for Mutual Economic Assistance as well as
China and North Korea.
</TEXT>
