<HEAD>Crop Futures Close Mostly Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures closed mostly lower
Tuesday on the Chicago Board of Trade, reflecting the weak tone of
the grain export business.
   Soybeans swung in a range from $8.04 to $8.16 a bushel. The
market opened higher in response to the wet weather that has slowed
corn and soybean harvesting in the Midwest, then sold off on the
lack of strong overseas demand for U.S. soybeans, said Cathy Leow,
a grain-market analyst with Thomson McKinnon Securities Inc. in New
York.
   Corn finished mostly lower while wheat was down moderately on
liquidation linked to the continuing disappointment over the lack
of a new long-term Soviet agreement to buy grain from the United
States, Ms. Leow said.
   ``It does not look like we're going to get an agreement prior to
the (presidential) election,'' she said.
   At the close, wheat was 1 cent to 7} cents lower with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.22{ a bushel; corn was 3
cents lower to 1{ cents higher with December at $2.92 a bushel;
oats were 1 cent lower to 2\ cents higher with December at $2.57 a
bushel; soybeans were 2{ cents to 4} cents lower with November at
$8.06 a bushel.
