<1ST_LINE>u f AM-SoftwareFight Bjt   10-18 0473</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Software Fight, Bjt,0487</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tactical Battle Heats Up In Fight Over Unix</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of companies allied with American
Telephone & Telegraph Co. raised the stakes Tuesday in a battle
with other computer giants over control of Unix, a base layer of
software that makes it easier for different brands of computers to
work together.
   By banding together, the big computer makers gained more
bargaining power in the contest with the Open Software Foundation,
a group that includes International Business Machines Corp.,
Digital Equipment Corp. and Hewlett-Packard Co.
   Unix is portrayed by enthusiasts as a great hope of the computer
industry because it would allow programs to run on a wide variety
of computers without expensive alteration.
   However, the struggle over Unix has soured computer buyers, who
fear the standard is being split in two. Programs written to work
with one version of Unix might not run on computers that use
another version.
   Both sides in the contest say they want to unify Unix, but the
AT&T group insists that AT&T's Unix System V Release 4.0 should
serve as the basis, while the Open Software Foundation says IBM's
version, AIX, should be the core.
   The AT&T alliance scored a small victory when the Open Software
Foundation indicated Tuesday that there might be room for
compromise. Until now it has made its insistence on IBM's AIX a
non-negotiable point.
   ``Nothing has changed on that right now,'' Open Software
Foundation spokesman Gary McCormack said. ``But that doesn't mean
the world can't change tomorrow. Please bear with us.''
   A meeting between AT&T and the Open Software Foundation was
scheduled for later in the week, probably Friday, McCormack said.
   The new group rallying around AT&T's version of Unix is made up
of 18 companies, including giants such as Unisys Corp., NCR Corp.,
Japan's Fujitsu Ltd. and Italy's Ing. C. Olivetti & Co. SpA.
   The Open Software Foundation was created earlier this year
because of concerns that AT&T was manipulating Unix so it would be
best suited to run on its own computers and those of its
fast-growing Silicon Valley partner, Sun Microsystems Inc.
   But supporters of AT&T's version of Unix, known as System V
Release 4.0, say AT&T has taken steps to ensure that other
companies and customers have a big say in the development of Unix.
   ``What AT&T has done is resolve those issues,'' Jan Lindelow,
senior vice president for marketing and services at Unisys, said in
an interview.
   Among the other companies that have joined the new group are
Amdahl Corp., Control Data Corp., Gould Inc., Intel Corp., Motorola
Inc., Italy's Ing. C. Olivetti & Co. SpA, Prime Computer Inc. and
Japan's Toshiba Corp.
   Intel and two smaller companies are members of both groups. ``We
don't play favorites,'' said Kevin Teixeira, an Intel spokesman.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
