<DOCNO> AP881018-0272 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-88 1601EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Eastern     10-18 0653</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Eastern,0677</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Union Leaders Still Hopeful On Buyer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines labor officials said Tuesday they
are hopeful there will be other suitors for the carrier, from which
financier Carl Icahn has reportedly backed away.
   ``We'll just keep moving along,'' said Charles E. Bryan,
president of the Machinists District 100, said before leaving
Tuesday for out-of-town meetings concerning Eastern. ``We're
confident that we will still get something worked out.''
   Icahn, the chairman of Trans World Airlines Inc., said in an
interview with the Wall Street Journal that ``the talks are over.''
   ``It's unfortunate because a merger with Eastern would have been
very positive for TWA. But what will be will be,'' Icahn was quoted
in Tuesday's editions.
   Icahn reportedly notified Frank Lorenzo, the chairman of
Eastern's parent, Texas Air Corp., on Monday that he was unable to
reach an understanding with Eastern's three unions over the weekend.
   But with Eastern continuing to lose money and Lorenzo stalemated
in efforts to extract concessions from its unions, Wall Street
analysts and Eastern labor officials think he wants to sell.
   ``I don't think there's any question that his advisers and
lenders have advised him that his crusade against labor is going to
drag the whole Texas Air Corp. down the tubes,'' said Ron Cole, a
spokesman for Eastern's Air Line Pilots Association local. ``I
think he has realized the only way out is to sell.''
   However, The Miami Herald, quoting an unidentified source, said
Tuesday there were no other active offers for Eastern and that
Lorenzo is planning to keep the airline.
   Icahn had been negotiating for more than a week with Lorenzo and
Eastern's pilot and machinist unions, although Icahn never made a
specific acquisition proposal. Last Wednesday, New York developer
Donald Trump agreed to buy the Eastern shuttle for $365 million in
cash.
   Sources told The Associated Press on Monday that the union talks
broke down mainly because Icahn was seeking wage concessions from
the Eastern unions that the union leaders considered too severe.
   Icahn ``got too greedy,'' one union source told the Journal.
   The newspaper also reported that Icahn negotiators became angry
when TWA's Machinists union tried to tie its forthcoming contract
negoiations with the talks with Eastern.
   Lorenzo reportedly had given Icahn an exclusive right until the
end of the week to make an offer for Eastern to the Texas Air board
of directors. After that deadline, other interested parties could
come forward with offers.
   Texas Air executives have indicated that money-losing Eastern,
minus its Northeast shuttle, would be worth about $1 billion,
according to the New York Times.
   In addition to Icahn, other parties that have expressed an
interest in buying the rest of Eastern include TWA President Joseph
Corr, who is a close associate of Icahn, and a group of major
insurance companies, the Times said.
   Eastern has racked up losses of more than $302.5 million since
1987.
   Meanwhile, Eastern announced on Monday an unusual peak-season
cut in MaxSaver fares between Florida and northeast cities.
   ``Never before has Eastern offered such deep discounts so far
ahead of the peak winter travel season,'' said George Brennan,
Eastern's newly named vice president for marketing.
   Fares will range from $69 one way to $89 depending on
destination. Fares between Florida and New York, for example, are
$79 each way. That's 33 percent off the normal restricted MaxSavers
fares and 70 percent or more off regular coach prices.
   Roundtrip tickets must be purchased 24 hours after a reservation
is made and are nonrefundable. They must be bought by Oct. 31 for
trips beginning Nov. 1 through Feb. 15. A Saturday night stayover
is required.
   The new rates, announced Monday, involve 16 Florida cities and
40 northern destinations.
   The rates through the winter season, a peak travel time to
Florida from the northeast, exempts Nov. 23, 27, and 28; Dec. 22
and 23, and Jan. 2 and 3 from the cut-rate fares.
</TEXT>
