<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Earns-Banks     10-18 0427</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Banks,0446</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Citicorp, Wells Fargo Report Earnings Decline, Hanover Posts Gain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Citicorp and Wells Fargo & Co. on Tuesday reported sharp
declines in their third-quarter profits while another large banking
concern, Manufacturers Hanover Corp., posted significantly higher
earnings during the same period.
   But all three companies were ahead for the first three quarters
of the year following losses a year ago, when they added to their
loan-loss provisions to cover troubled Third World debt.
   Citicorp, the nation's largest bank holding company, said that
net income for the three months ended Sept. 30 totaled $394
million, or $1.13 per share, down 25 percent from earnings of $528
million, or $1.78 a share, in 1987.
   For the first nine months, the company's profit totaled $1.11
billion, or $3.17 a share, vs. a $1.8 billion loss a year ago.
   No. 7-ranked Manufacturers Hanover said it earned $197.7
million, or $3.77 a share, in the third quarter. That was 53
percent higher than net income of $129.1 million, or $2.73 a share,
in 1987.
   Hanover's nine-month earnings totaled $741.2 million, or $14.28
a share, compared with a $1.1 billion loss last year.
   Wells Fargo, ranked 10th, reported quarterly income of $131.7
million, or $2.36 per share, down 15 percent from earnings of $155
million, or $2.77 per share, in the year-ago period.
   Net income for the first nine months of was $376.6 million, or
$6.75 per share, vs. a loss of $60.4 million last year.
   Citicorp said its third-quarter results included an after-tax
reduction in earnings of $22 million as a result of its decision to
reclassify $566 million of its $1.4 billion in loans to Argentina,
reflecting the non-payment of interest for 90 or more days on those
loans.
   Last year Citicorp increased its loan-loss provision by $3
billion to $4.1 billion. Its loan loss provision so far this year
is about 78 percent lower.
   Hanover said its third-quarter profit included an after-tax gain
of $98 million from the sale of a London office building.
   Helping boost its nine-month profit were net gains of about $188
million from the sale of Manufacturers Hanover Consumer Services
Inc., two branch buildings and Manufacturers Hanover Investment
Corp. earlier this year.
   The nine-month profit had been hurt a year ago by the company's
decision to increase its reserve for possible credit losses by $1.7
billion.
   Wells Fargo said market conditions in California, where it is
based, were favorable, but the reduction in quarterly earnings
reflected a $369.3 million charge for reducing its portfolio of
loans to less developed countries.
</TEXT>
