<DOCNO> AP881018-0276 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-88 1641EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Crash-Anniversary Bjt   10-18 0830</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Crash-Anniversary, Bjt,0859</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Big Board Market Makers Less Busy, But Say Their System Still Best</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY24</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A year ago Wednesday, the world seemed to be
collapsing around Earl E. Ellis as he battled and screamed to keep
order in three tumbling stocks.
   ``It was a very scary time,'' said Ellis, a market maker on the
floor of the New York Stock Exchange, where prices collapsed in
frenzied selling on Oct. 19, 1987, put some of his colleagues out
of business and severely stretched the limits of others. ``There
was disbelief and certainly fear.''
   He spent that night in a nearby hotel, rather than returning to
his suburban Long Island home, wife and teen-age daughter. What
really worried him, he said, was what would happen on Oct. 20.
   ``Logic said it wasn't going to happen again,'' he said.
``Emotion said it was.''
   In an interview on the eve of the anniversary of the worst stock
panic of modern times, Ellis said the anxiety level has fallen
sharply, but so has interest in stocks. Like other NYSE market
makers, known as ``specialists,'' Ellis is now more concerned with
the absence of buyers and sellers, his bread and butter.
   ``Ours is a business of feast or famine. Always has been, always
will be,'' the 47-year-old said in his native Dallas drawl, as he
leaned against his trading post on the cavernous NYSE floor in
lower Manhattan's jungle of skyscrapers. ``It's certainly closer to
famine now.''
   A partner in the specialist firm Benjamin Jacobson & Sons, Ellis
has been in the business for more than a decade. During a typical
day, he buys and sells thousands of shares in Anheuser-Busch,
Tandem Computers and the Student Loan Marketing Association, known
on Wall Street as Sallie Mae.
   As a specialist, his firm has what amounts to a franchise in
these and 37 other stocks on the NYSE floor, acting as an
intermediary for buy and sell orders from brokers stationed along
the floor perimeters.
   In return, the specialist firm is obligated to set opening
prices and keep trading orderly, largely by selling from its own
inventory when other sellers are scarce and buying when buyers are
scarce.
   On Black Monday, Oct. 19, and its volatile aftermath, a
marauding avalanche of sellers threatened to overwhelm the ability
of the NYSE's 54 specialist firms to do their jobs.
   Many were reluctant to buy stocks because they were uncertain
whether other buyers would appear. Others who had spent enormous
amounts of borrowed money to buy stocks faced credit crises with
their banks.
   Ellis's firm, one of Wall Street's strongest, traded more than
$1 billion in securities during the week of the crash.
   The performance of the specialists was criticized in some
post-crash studies, which called them a weakness in a system that
experienced unprecedented strain.
   But Ellis defended what he called the fairest and most efficient
market system, even in the face of new technologies that have
replaced many of the trading functions once performed by humans.
   ``If you ask how the specialists did on Black Monday, you'd get
a different answer from every one,'' Ellis said. ``Some went out of
business, some made bad mistakes. But one has to understand what a
specialist does.
   ``We are a pricing mechanism. We're not here to buy every stock
for sale,'' he said. ``What we're here to do is make sure it's done
in an an orderly fashion. We could have done everything right and
the market could still have come down.''
   Computers can speed the delivery of buy and sell orders to the
trading floor, he said, but the auction process, the bargaining and
haggling that inevitably becomes part of securities trading, will
always be a human domain.
   ``You can't automate the interface of brokers,'' he contended.
``You can't black box that.''
   On the day before the anniversary, the NYSE floor was relatively
quiet, and few people were talking about the crash. ``It's
history,'' said James E. Garlinge, an Ellis colleague who trades
USG Corp. stock.
   In the first hour, Ellis traded a few thousand shares of
Anheuser-Busch with floor brokers and the price moved up | point _
or 62{ cents a share to $33.50. A blue-coated NYSE reporter, who
conveys all trades into a computer system that feeds the exchange's
electronic ticker tape, dutifully recorded the transactions. ``This
is slow,'' Ellis said.
   The biggest action was a few trading posts away at Stokes, Hoyt
& Co., the specialist firm for Kraft Co., where brokers were
screaming to sell because the stock was up nearly $30 a share on a
$90-a-share takeover offer by Philip Morris Cos. Inc.
   Several specialists watching from afar shook their heads in
dismay. To them, takeovers are bad news because the acquired
company's stock will no longer be traded.
   ``It's a product that we lose,'' said James A. Jacobson, another
partner in the Jacobson firm. ``It's very tough to lose a company.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
