<DOCNO> AP881018-0277 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-88 1724EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     10-18 0521</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0537</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Holds in Choppy Trading</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Precede LONDON BC</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar finished higher against most major
currencies Tuesday after a choppy day of trading in the foreign
exchange markets.
   Gold prices fell in New York. In late trading, Republic National
Bank of New York said gold was bid at $410.70 a troy ounce, down
from $411.90 a troy ounce late Monday.
   The U.S. currency began the day on the upswing in Asia, buoyed
by comments in Tokyo from Bank of France governor Jacques de
Larosiere who reiterated support for central bank intervention to
achieve exchange rate stability. The dollar then headed lower in
Europe before turning up again in domestic trading.
   Analysts said that despite the appearance of volatility, the
dollar was stuck in the same narrow range it has been trading in
since spring, between 1.80 and 1.90 West German marks.
   ``All we're seeing is the low end of the same range,'' said
James Pugh, of Bear, Stearns & Co. ``It will continue to do that
until the election.''
   Those following the dollar generally agreed that any drastic
moves up or down were unlikely before the presidential election is
decided next month. Smaller moves within the established trading
range are possible, they said.
   Indeed, some technical analysts attributed the move upward at
the end of day Tuesday to a bounce off the low end of the trading
range.
   In Tokyo, where the trading day begins, the dollar rose to
127.70 yen from Monday's 127.20 yen. Later, in London, it slipped
to 127.05 yen. Late in the day in New York the dollar moved to
127.155, up from 127.065 late Monday.
   The dollar gained against the pound in London, where it cost
$1.7515 to buy one pound, cheaper than the $1.7530 it cost late
Monday. But in New York, the pound fetched $1.74805, up from
$1.74635 late Monday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late rates
Monday, were 1.81125 West German marks, up from 1.80875; 1.52925
Swiss francs, up from 1.52745; 1.20075 Canadian dollars, down from
1.20375; 6.1675 French francs, down from 6.1710; and 1,346.50
Italian lire, unchanged.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late rates
Monday, included: 1.8050 West German marks, down from 1.8120;
1.5280 Swiss francs, down from 1.5295; 6.1735 French francs, down
from 6.1790; 2.0390 Dutch guilders, unchanged; 1,345.50 Italian
lire, down from 1,348.50, and 1.20095 Canadian dollars, down from
1.2047.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery closed at $411.80 a troy ounce, down from $412.20 an ounce
Monday.
   Gold rose in London to a late bid of $412.95 a troy ounce,
compared with late Monday's $412.25 an ounce. In Zurich, gold fell
to $411.00 an ounce from $412.30 late Monday. Earlier, in Hong
Kong, gold rose $1.99 an ounce to close at $416.05.
   On the Comex, silver bullion for current delivery was quoted at
$6.355 a troy ounce, down from $6.405 Monday. Silver bullion prices
fell on the London market, where the metal was trading at a late
bid of $6.39 a troy ounce, down from Monday's late $6.43.
