<HEAD>Copper Futures Resume Climb On Tight Supplies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Copper futures prices climbed sharply Tuesday on New York's
Commodity Exchange amid renewed fears of tight supplies linked
partly to a miners' strike in Peru, the world's seventh largest
copper producer.
   On other futures markets, precious metals were slightly lower;
most energy futures fell sharply; cattle posted steep while pork
futures were mixed; grains and soybeans were mostly lower; and
stock-index futures advanced.
   Reports that as many as half of Peru's 70,000 metals miners were
out on strike fueled a late rally in the copper market, analysts
said. The contracts for both spot and December delivery hit new
life-of-contract highs for the 10th time in the past 12 sessions.
   Copper for spot delivery settled at $1.38 a pound, up 3.9 cents
from Monday while the contract for delivery in December rose 3.2
cents to $1.246 a pound.
   The market opened steady and traded on a fairly even keel for
most the session in light of Monday's report that London Metal
Exchange stocks had fallen last week by 4,550 metric tons instead
of the 7,000-to-9,000-ton decline that had been expected, analysts
said.
   Nevertheless, ``LME stocks continued their down trend and
probably will continue to decline,'' said Fred Demler, metals
economist with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. in New York.
   ``Inventories are critically low, consumption remains good in
Japan, parts of Europe and the United States and production has
faltered a bit as of late,'' he said.
   ``The only thing that's negative in the copper market right now
is that it's due for a technical correction _ it's moved up much
too fast,'' Demler said. ``But most most of the fundamentals
suggest the market will be tight for another five to six months.''
   Gold and silver futures retreated slightly in reaction to a
reversal of recent trends toward a weaker dollar and lower prices
for crude oil and other commodities, Demler said.
   Gold settled $2 to $4 lower with December at $415.10 troy ounce;
silver was 5 cents lower across the board with December at $6.425 a
troy ounce.
   Crude oil futures plunged on the New York Mercantile Exchange
amid heavy profit-taking but market players still believes OPEC
members will reach agreement soon on a plan to stabilize prices,
analysts said.
   ``The market was overbought and a lot of people wanted to take
profits,'' said Peter Beutel, energy analyst with Elders Futures
Inc. in New York.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 60 cents to 67 cents
lower with November at $14.61 a barrel; heating oil was 1.59 cents
to 1.79 cents lower with November at 42.29 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was 1 cent lower to .16 cent higher with November at 46.92
cents a gallon.
   Cattle futures prices fell sharply on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange on profit-taking following Monday's advance to
life-of-contract highs for all delivery months, analysts said.
   The cattle market had rallied on expectations for higher cash
markets and ideas that the Agriculture Department's quarterly
cattle-on-feed report, due out after the close on Friday, will show
a significant reduction in the number of cattle being fattened for
slaughter.
   Live cattle settled .35 cent to 1.15 cents lower with October at
72.27 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .10 cent to 1.07 cents
lower with October at 81.80 cents a pound; live hogs were .07 cent
lower to .25 cent higher with October at 39.90 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .18 cent to .57 cent lower with February
at 48.77 cents a pound.
   Grain and soybean futures finished mostly lower on the Chicago
Board of Trade, reflecting the weak tone of the grain export
business, analysts said.
   Corn harvesting was 63 percent complete as of Sunday in the top
17 producing states while soybean harvesting was 90 percent
finished in the top 19 producing states, the USDA said late Monday.
   Wheat settled 1 cent to 7\ cents lower with December at $4.23 a
bushel; corn was 2} cents lower to 1 cent higher with December at
$2.92\ a bushel; oats were { cent lower to 2{ cents higher with
December at $2.57{ a bushel; soybeans were 2 cents to 5{ cents
lower with November at $8.05{ a bushel.
   Stock-index futures posted strong gains on the Chicago Merc,
where the contract for December delivery of the Standard & Poor's
500 index settled 2.95 points higher at 281.10
</TEXT>
