<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Computer,0245</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Apollo Losses Widen; Tandy Net Rises 1 Percent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Apollo Computer Inc., the struggling maker of computer work
stations, said Tuesday its losses widened in the latest quarter
from a year earlier, while Tandy Corp. said its profit rose
slightly.
   Apollo, based in Chelmsford, Mass., which has been losing the
race for customers with rival Sun Microsystems Inc., said it lost
$3.58 million in the third quarter, compared to a loss of $2.86
million a year earlier. Revenue rose 16 percent to $157.1 million
from $135 million a year earlier.
   For the first nine months of its fiscal year, Apollo said it had
a loss of $1.1 million, compared to a profit of $11.2 million, or
31 cents a share, a year earlier. Nine-month revenue rose 20
percent to $469.5 million from $390.7 million.
   Apollo said it had made a major transition in the quarter to new
products, including what it calls a personal supercomputer. It did
not project when it might return to profitability.
   Tandy, the Fort Worth, Texas-based owner of Radio Shack that
makes computers and other electronic products, said its earnings
rose 1 percent to $64.9 million, or 72 cents a share, in the first
quarter of its fiscal year, which ended Sept. 30, from $64.3
million, or 71 cents a share, a year earlier. Revenue rose 12
percent to $937 million from $838 million a year earlier.
</TEXT>
