<2ND_LINE>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0539</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Late Rally Lifts Wall Street to Post-Crash High</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A late rally catapulted the stock market Tuesday
to its highest close since last October's crash, as Wall Street
overcame its jitters on the eve of the debacle's one-year
anniversary.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials jumped 19.38 points to
2,159.85, scoring most of the gain in the waning minutes of the
session. The blue-chip average brushed past the previous post-crash
high of 2,158.96 reached on Columbus Day, Oct. 10.
   The crash anniversary ``has probably got some people a little
uneasy,'' said Bill Raftery, an analyst for Prudential-Bache
Securities Inc. ``People should look beyond it; the world isn't
coming to an end.''
   Tuesday's post-crash peak was still 21 percent below the
all-time high of 2,722.42 reached on Aug. 25, 1987.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 8-to-5 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
841 issues up, 568 down and 546 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the NYSE totaled 162.5 million shares, up
from 119.29 million in Monday's session. Nationwide, consolidated
volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trading at regional
exchanges and on the over-the-counter market, totaled 191.79
million shares.
   Stocks spent most of the session seesawing gently between the
plus and minus columns, until the late buying spree. The rally was
fueled by takeover activity involving several big food companies,
which gave the market support throughout the day.
   ``There's just rampant takeover speculation going on,'' said
Steve Becker, a partner in the investment firm Wayne Hummer & Co.
in Chicago.
   Kraft stock shot up 28[ a share to 88\ in heavy trading, just
below the $90 a share offered late Monday by Philip Morris in an
$11 billion takeover offer. Philip Morris stock dropped 4{ to 95{,
apparently because investors felt the acquisition would dilute the
earnings of the cigarette and food giant.
   Philip Morris said it has filed suit against Kraft and some of
its directors in an Illinois court.
   In another major development in the food industry, Pillsbury
rose ] to 59, after an earlier decline. Pillsbury said its board of
directors unanimously rejected a $60-a-share tender offer from
Grand Metropolitan of Britain.
   Pillsbury later disclosed that it had filed a suit against Grand
Met and Wendell Investments Ltd. for violations of the Shipping Act
of 1916.
   Among other blue-chip issues, IBM surged 3\ to 124], Citicorp
rose | to 25], AT&T gained } at 27{ and Exxon was unchanged at 45[.
   Warner Lambert dropped 4\ to 72{ amid uncertainty about whether
the Food and Drug Administration would allow the company to expand
the labeling of Lopid, an anti-cholesterol drug, to specify its use
in preventing heart disease.
   The NYSE's composite index was up 1.45, at 157.32.
   Standard & Poor's industrial index rose 3.69 to 321.44, and
S&P's 500-stock composite index was up 2.97 at 279.38.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index edged up
0.88 to 304.15. The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter
market closed at 386.25, up 1.24.
</TEXT>
