<HEAD>Rice Exports Expected to Rise 7 Percent</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. rice exports are expected to be up around
7 percent in the 1988-89 marketing year, rebounding from a 14
percent decline last season, the Agriculture Department said
Tuesday.
   Exports for the year that began Aug. 1 are forecast at 2.45
million metric tons, milled rice equivalent, up from 2.29 million
tons in 1987-88, the department's Economic Research Service said in
its new outlook report.
   A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds. There are slightly more than
22 hundredweight of rice in a ton.
   Rice production this year is estimated at 156.7 million
hundredweight, or about 7.1 million tons of unmilled (rough) rice
equivalent, a 23 percent increase from last year. On a milled
basis, that would be about 4.98 million tons.
   World production of milled rice in 1988-89 is forecast at a
near-record of 319.8 million tons, up 4 percent from last year's
drought-reduced harvest in South and Southeast Asia, the report
said.
</TEXT>
