<HEAD>Warner's Profit Up Nearly Doubles in Third Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Warner Communications Inc. reported Tuesday that
its third-quarter profit nearly doubled from a year earlier,
boosted by strong performances from its movie, recorded music and
cable television divisions.
   The communications and entertainment company said its net income
in the three months ended Sept. 30 jumped to $105.4 million, or 66
cents a share, from $66.2 million, or 41 cents a share, a year
earlier.
   Third-quarter revenue rose to $1.03 billion from $824.1 million.
   ``This achievement demonstrates the growing worldwide demand for
our entertainment products,'' Chairman Steven J. Ross said.
``Warner Cable continues to show dramatic growth and is becoming a
meaningful contributor to (Warner Communications') operating
results.''
   Late last month, Warner vowed to fight a state court ruling
blocking its proposed $1.2 billion acquisition of Lorimar
Telepictures Corp.
   In the first nine months of the year, Warner's net income surged
to $322.1 million, or $2.02 a share, from $236.1 million, or $1.50
a share.
   Nine-month revenue rose to $3.01 billion from $2.38 billion a
year earlier.
   Warner said its upcoming movie releases for the holiday season
include ``Tequila Sunrise'' starring Mel Gibson, Michelle Pfieffer
and Kurt Russell, and ``Accidental Tourist'' with William Hurt,
Kathleen Turner and Geena Davis.
