<1ST_LINE>u f AM-SmallBusiness 1stLd-Writethru   10-18 0429</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Small Business, 1st Ld-Writethru,0440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Small Businesses Healthy After Crash, Study Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 4th graf to CORRECT to Birch, sted Birth; uppicks 5th
graf pvs: The index ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Small business growth has remained healthy after
the stock market crash a year ago, with sales and employment gains
outpacing those of larger corporations, according to an economic
index reported Tuesday.
   American Express Co. said its Small Business Growth Index rose
sharply in the first half of 1988, to 4.46 from 1.48 for the
previous six months.
   The strongest gains were in the mid-Atlantic states of New York,
New Jersey and Pennsylvania, which recovered quickly from the Oct.
19 stock market plunge, which occured a year ago Wednesday.
   ``... The dramatic increase in the Growth Index reflects an
overall resiliency within the small business sector,'' said David
Birch, a professor at Massachusetts Institute of Technology who is
co-chairman of the American Express Small Business Partnership.
   The index measures the semi-annual growth in employment, sales
and new incorporations of some 7 million small companies _ defined
as those with 100 or fewer employees.
   The index found that small business employment rose 1.97 percent
and sales grew 1.3 percent in the first half of this year, compared
with a 1.90 percent jobs gain and 1.06 percent sales rise in the
second half of 1987. New incorporations remained steady.
   While small business sales and employment growth outpaced
similar rates for large business, the gap between the two narrowed
in the first six months of this year, the report said.
   In the last half of 1987, small business sales grew at a rate
8.2 times those of large business, but in the first half of 1988,
the rate narrowed to 3.7 times, the report said.
   ``Large business cutbacks, prevalent throughout the 1980s,
appear to have bottomed out,'' said Birch. ``Additionally, large
business employment is now accelerating and sales growth, almost
nonexistent last year, is beginning to rise to the level of
high-performing small business.''
   The weakest growth area for small business was in the Mountain
States region, where sales dropped 2.35 percent and employment
edged up 1.31 percent. This was the only area showing a negative
indicator, the report said.
   The biggest turnaround came in the region that includes
Kentucky, Tennessee, Alabama and Mississippi where overall sales,
employment and new incorporations grew 1.03 percent after a 3.94
drop the previous six months.
   New England ranked first for employment growth at 2.33 percent,
while the Pacific states led in sales growth with a rise of 2.72
percent, the report said.
</TEXT>
