<1ST_LINE>r f AM-FirstMaryland-Allied     10-18 0209</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-First Maryland-Allied,0216</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Maryland Bank Committee To Recommend Rejection of Allied Irish
Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First Maryland Bancorp was advised Tuesday to
reject a $327.6 million offer from Allied Irish Banks PLC to
purchase the 50.3 percent of stock in the bank it doesn't already
own.
   But a special advisory committee to First Maryland's board
recommended the bank continue discussions with Allied toward a more
acceptable offer.
   Dublin, Ireland-based Allied, which already owns 49.7 percent of
Maryland Bancorp, has offered $35.25 in cash for the remaining
outstanding common shares.
   The 183-year-old Maryland bank referred the offer to a special
committee for review. According to a statement issued Tuesday, the
panel will recommend the board reject the offer.
   The panel said, however, that it recommended discussions
continue ``with a view to negotiating improvements in the terms of
the Allied Irish offer.'' The panel noted, however, that ``there is
no assurance that an acceptable agreement will be ... agreed to.''
   Allied Irish Banks acquired its existing stake in First Maryland
for $151 million beginning five years ago. It bought 43 percent of
the stock outright, then purchased about 2 percent of the stock in
each subsequent year. Allied said it would use cash reserves to
purchase the remaining stock.
</TEXT>
