<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-88 2053EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-ShigellosisOutbreak     10-18 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shigellosis Outbreak,0406</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Passengers Apparently Not Shying Away Despite Illness Outbreak</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Northwest Airlines passengers are not shying
away from in-flight meals despite a link between food served aboard
some flights and the outbreak of an intestinal illness, an airline
spokesman said Tuesday.
   ``We haven't had any reports of any problems,'' said Redmond
Tyler. ``Can I say that nobody has turned (airline food) down? No,
I can't tell you that. But we haven't heard of anything major.''
   Shigellosis has been confirmed in passengers on nine flights
from Minneapolis-St. Paul to seven cities: Detroit; Denver;
Nashville, Tenn.; Newark, N.J.; Seattle; Chicago; and Louisville,
Ky., said Buddy Ferguson, a spokesman for the Minnesota Health
Department. In addition, there was a confirmed case on an in-bound
flight from Phoenix, he said.
   Ferguson said Tuesday that possible cases of the illness have
been identified by the department on about 145 flights since Sept.
15, including flights overseas to Japan and East Germany.
   State epidemiologist Michael Osterholm said Monday it's still
not clear whether food now being served on Northwest flights is
safe and Ferguson said Tuesday that the situation had not changed.
   ``I can't confirm that it is safe and I can't say it isn't,''
Osterholm said.
   Confirmed cases of the illness have been found among passengers
who flew on the airline as late as last Thursday, Osterholm said.
   All the confirmed cases have been traced to food prepared for
the airline at the Marriott Corp. kitchen, which services Northwest
at the Minneapolis-St. Paul International Airport.
   That facility serves Northwest exclusively and prepares 100,000
meals per week for more than 900 Northwest flights out of the Twin
Cities.
   Leslie Schlags, a corporate spokeswoman for Marriott, said
Tuesday that tests on the company's 360 workers should be complete
by Thursday and results should be complete before the weekend is
out. She said Marriott is testing all in-bound and out-bound food
at its kitchen in addition to testing employees.
   The bacterial infection was first identified in 21 Minnesota
Vikings football players and staff in the week after their Oct. 2
game in Miami.
   The disease causes intense diarrhea and other symptoms that can
last for five to seven days. It spreads easily from person to
person. Of people exposed to the bacteria, about 10 percent usually
get sick, Osterholm said.
</TEXT>
