<FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-88 2114EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-BurgerKing-Olcott     10-18 0403</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Burger King-Olcott,0417</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Burger King President Resigns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After serving two years as president of troubled
Burger King, Charles S. Olcott resigned Tuesday in the fast-food
company's second top management shakeup this year.
   The resignation comes as Burger King's parent, Minneapolis-based
Pillsbury Co., is scrambling to defend itself against an unwanted
takeover bid.
   Analysts said it was Olcott's failure to reverse Burger King's
losing trend that led to his departure. Under Olcott, Burger King
embarked on an expensive and ultimately disappointing marketing
campaign based on the slogan ``We do it like you'd do it.''
   William Maguire, an analyst at Merrill Lynch & Co. in New York,
said Olcott ``wasn't a marketing man when they needed a marketing
man badly.''
   Pillsbury is in the process of defending itself against an
unsolicited $5.23 billion tender offer launched by London-based
Grand Metropolitan PLC.
   Analysts speculated that Pillsbury might opt to sell Burger
King, the world's second-largest hamburger chain, in an effort to
preserve its independence. A sale could bring as much as $2 billion.
   Pillsbury's board unanimously rejected Grand Met's $60-a-share
offer Tuesday, calling it ``inadequate and not in the best
interests of the company and its shareholders.''
   ``They're fighting the only battle they can,'' said John
McMillin, an analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. in New
York.
   The hamburger chain accounts for about one-third of Pillsbury's
sales and about two-thirds of its profits but has not done well
recently. Its pre-tax profits have decline by more than 50 percent,
from $119.2 million in fiscal 1986 to $48.2 million for the year
ended May 31, the company reported.
   Pillsbury Chairman Philip L. Smith said Tuesday in urging
shareholders to reject Grand Met's bid that significant investments
have been made to improve Burger King operations. He said improved
performance is ``critical'' to the chain.
   Olcott's departure marks yet another major management shakeup
for the fast-food chain, which has had five chairman and eight
presidents since Pillsbury took over in 1967.
   Most recently, J. Jeffery Campbell resigned as head of
Pillsbury's ailing restaurant group in June.
   Jerry W. Levin, a Pillsbury executive vice president, was named
Burger King's chairman. He had worked previously in mergers and
acquisitions at Pillsbury, prompting financial analysts to
speculate Pillsbury might be preparing to get rid of the
Miami-based restaurant chain.
   ``The guy's good at doing deals,'' McMillin said. ``I've got to
think he's been brought in to do a deal.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
